\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Introduction to Rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Basic Definitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definition of a Ring
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
ring
\series default
 is a triple 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,+,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 consisting of a set 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 together with two operations 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 (addition) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot$
\end_inset

 (multiplication) such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,+)$
\end_inset

 forms an abelian group.
 This means
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Addition is associative: 
\begin_inset Formula $(a+b)+c=a+(b+c)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Addition is commutative: 
\begin_inset Formula $a+b=b+a$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The identity element exists and is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

; there is an element 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a+0=a=0+a$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Inverses exist: For each 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, there exists an element 
\begin_inset Formula $-a$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a+(-a)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 forms a monoid.
 This means
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Multiplication is associative: 
\begin_inset Formula $(a\cdot b)\cdot c=a\cdot(b\cdot c)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The identity element exists and is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

; there is an element 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $1\cdot a=a=a\cdot1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Multiplication is distributive with respect to addition.
 This means
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a\cdot(b+c)=a\cdot b+a\cdot c$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(b+c)\cdot a=b\cdot a+c\cdot a$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
commutative ring 
\series default
if multiplication 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is commutative: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=ba$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To clean notation, we abbreviate 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,+,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\cdot b$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $ab$
\end_inset

.
 We also denote the identity with respect to addition as 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and we denote the identity with respect to multiplication as 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
field 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a commutative ring with identity such that every nonzero element in
 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Integral Domains
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An 
\series bold
integral domain 
\series default
is a commutative ring with non zero divisors.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every field is an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is prime and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x},\overline{y}\in R\slash I$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}\overline{y}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $xy\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is prime, we either have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in I$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, either 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $xy\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}\overline{y}=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, we either have 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}=0$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, either 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A finite integral domain is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon R\to R$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(x)=ax
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is finite, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is bijective.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(b)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is a multiplicative inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ring Homomorphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be rings and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon R\to S$
\end_inset

 be a function.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
ring homomorphism 
\series default
if it satisfies the following three properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
it preserves addition: 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a+b)=\varphi(a)+\varphi(b)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
it preserves multiplication: 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(ab)=\varphi(a)\varphi(b)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
it preserves the multiplicative identity element: 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that property 1 is simply saying that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a group of homomorphism of the underlying abelian groups.
 This automatically implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 preserves the additive identity, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(0)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since multiplicative inverses do not necessarily exist in a ring, property
 3 is not guaranteed from property 2.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
monomial 
\series default
in 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 variables (or indeterminates) 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a power product 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{\alpha}=x_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}\cdots x_{n}^{\alpha_{n}},\qquad\alpha=(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{n})\in\mathbb{N}^{n}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 are rings where 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot$
\end_inset

 denote the usual addition and multiplication operations.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 be an integer.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{Z}/m\mathbb{Z},+,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is a ring.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A ring 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,+,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
commutative 
\series default
if multiplication is commutative.
 A ring 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,+,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 has 
\series bold
identity 
\series default
if there is 
\begin_inset Formula $1\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\cdot1=1\cdot a=a$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Unless otherwise stated, we will asume 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 always has an identity.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 is a noncommutative ring.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 we have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a\cdot0=0=0\cdot a$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(-a)b=-(ab)=a(-b)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(-a)(-b)=ab$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(-1)a=-a=1(-a)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 An nonzero element 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is said to be a 
\series bold
zero divisor 
\series default
if there exists a nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that either 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $ba=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

, then the zero divisors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\bar{a}\in\mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z}\mid a\neq0\mbox{ and gcd}(a,n)>1\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}\in\mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a zero divisor.
 So there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{b}\in\mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{b}\neq\bar{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}\bar{b}=\bar{n}$
\end_inset

.
 This means 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=nm$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(a,n)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell,k\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $1=a\ell+nk$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,n\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a<n$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $d=\mbox{gcd}(a,n)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as a liear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 be the smallest positive integer that can be expressed as a linear combination
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $t=a\ell+nk$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell,k\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $t=d$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid a\ell+nk$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid t$
\end_inset

 .
 We show that 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mid a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mid n$
\end_inset

.
 To obtain a contradiciton, assume 
\begin_inset Formula $t\not\mid a$
\end_inset

.
 Then by Euclid's Algorithm, 
\begin_inset Formula $a=tg+r$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq r<t$
\end_inset

.
 So
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
r & =a-tg\\
 & =a-(a\ell+nk)g\\
 & =a(1-\ell g)+n(-kg)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is a linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 which is strictly smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mid a$
\end_inset

.
 A similar argument show 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mid n$
\end_inset

 too.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mid a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mid n$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mid d$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mid d$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $t=d$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in R$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is not a zero divisor and if 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=ac$
\end_inset

, then either 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b=c$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=ac$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a(b-c)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

, then since 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is not a zero divisor, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $b-c=0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $b=c$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 An element 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
unit 
\series default
if there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=1$
\end_inset

.
 We denote 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{\times}$
\end_inset

 to be the set of units of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}^{\times}=\{\pm1\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}^{\times}=\mathbb{Q}\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
division ring 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{\times}=R\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is also commutative, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
field
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Subring
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
subring 
\series default
of a ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $R'\subseteq R$
\end_inset

 that is a ring under the same 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and shares the same multiplicative identity.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that a subring is in fact a ring itself.
 This is because all of the properties required are satisfied because they
 are satisfied in the bigger ring.
 For instance, if 
\begin_inset Formula $R'$
\end_inset

 is a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in R'$
\end_inset

, then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a(b+c)=ab+ac\quad\text{and}\quad(a+b)c=ac+bc
\]

\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $R'$
\end_inset

 since these identities hold in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\slash\langle6\rangle$
\end_inset

, the subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,3\}$
\end_inset

 with addition and multiplication mod 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 is a ring in its own right with identity 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $3^{2}=9=3$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,3\}$
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\slash\langle6\rangle$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

with a ring structure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Its multiplicative identity is not the multiplicative identity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\slash\langle6\rangle$
\end_inset

, so we do not consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,3\}$
\end_inset

 to be a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\slash\langle6\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
More Examples of Rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be two rings.
 Then we define the product of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R\times S=\{(r,s)\mid r\in R,\,s\in S\},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where addition and multiplication are defined pointwise.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Ring Homomorphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be rings.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:R\to S$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
ring homomorphism 
\series default
if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a+b)=\varphi(a)+\varphi(b)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(ab)=\varphi(a)\varphi(b)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a ring homomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\times\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is completely determined by where it maps 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1)$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(a,b) & =\varphi((a,0)+(0,b))\\
 & =\varphi(a,0)+\varphi(0,b)\\
 & =a\varphi(1,0)+b\varphi(0,1).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in\mathbb{Z}\times\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,0)=(1,0)^{2}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1,0)=\varphi(1,0)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1,0)\in\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(0,1)\in\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus there are only four possible ring homomorphisms from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\times\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{0}(a,b)=0
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{1}(a,b)=a
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{2}(a,b)=b
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{3}(a,b)=a+b
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\times\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 It's easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{0},\varphi_{1},$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 are ring homomorphisms, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{3}$
\end_inset

 is not: On the one hand,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{3}((a,b)(a',b'))=(a+b)(a'+b')=aa'+ab'+ba'+bb'
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
on the other hand 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{3}(aa',bb')=aa'+bb',
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{3}((a,b)(a',b'))-\varphi_{3}(aa',bb')=ab'+ba'$
\end_inset

 which is not necessarily equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathbb{Z}\to\mathbb{Z}/15\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a ring homomorphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is completely determined by where it maps 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(m)=m\varphi(1)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1)=\varphi(1)^{2}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $1=1^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1)(\varphi(1)-\bar{1})=0.$
\end_inset

 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1)\in\{\bar{0},\bar{1},\bar{6},\bar{10}\}$
\end_inset

.
 So there are four possible ring homomorphisms from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/15\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{0}(a)=\bar{0}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{1}(a)=\bar{a}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{2}(a)=\overline{6a}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{3}(a)=\overline{10a}
\]

\end_inset

All four maps are indeed ring homomorphisms.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{3}(ab)=\overline{10ab}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{3}(a)\varphi_{3}(b)=\overline{10a}\cdot\overline{10}b=\overline{10ab}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be rings and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:R\to S$
\end_inset

 be a ring homomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
kernel 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=\{x\in R\mid\varphi(x)=0\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
image 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Im}\varphi=\{\varphi(x)\mid x\in R\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ideals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
left ideal 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 under addition and if 
\begin_inset Formula $rx\in I$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in R$
\end_inset

.
 A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
right ideal 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 under addition and if 
\begin_inset Formula $xr\in I$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in R$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is both a left and right ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is commutative, then left and right ideals are the same.
 In general though, a left ideal may 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
be a right ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left\{ \left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & 0\\
b & 0
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\mid a,b\in\mathbb{Z}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a left ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}(\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is not a right ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}(\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & 0\\
b & 0
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\left(\begin{smallmatrix}0 & 1\\
0 & 0
\end{smallmatrix}\right)=\left(\begin{smallmatrix}0 & a\\
0 & 0
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\notin I$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left\{ \left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & b\\
0 & 0
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\mid a,b\in\mathbb{Z}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a right ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}(\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is not a left ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}(\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left\{ \left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & b\\
c & d
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\mid a,b,c,d\in2\mathbb{Z}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a two-sided ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}(\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle m\rangle=m\mathbb{Z}=\{mk\mid k\in\mathbb{Z}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Any ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be rings and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:R\to S$
\end_inset

 be a ring homomorphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We know 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an abelian subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, since if 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\mbox{Ker}\varphi$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x-y)=\varphi(x)-\varphi(y)=0$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $x-y\in\mbox{Ker}\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mbox{Ker}\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(rx)=\varphi(r)\varphi(x)=0=\varphi(x)\varphi(r)=\varphi(xr)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $rx$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $xr$
\end_inset

 belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:\mathbb{Z}\to\mathbb{Z}_{m}$
\end_inset

 be the standard quotient map, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(a)=\bar{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\pi=m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Quotient Rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 under addition.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is abelian, we can form the group 
\begin_inset Formula $R/I$
\end_inset

.
 We define multiplication on 
\begin_inset Formula $R/I$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}\cdot\bar{b}:=\overline{ab}$
\end_inset

.
 Multilpication is well-defined if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is an two-sided ideal.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a+x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{b+y}$
\end_inset

 are different representatives.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{a+x}\cdot\overline{b+y} & =\overline{(a+x)(b+y)}\\
 & =\overline{ab+ay+xb+xy}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In order for 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{ab+ay+xb+xy}=\overline{ab}$
\end_inset

, we need 
\begin_inset Formula $ay+xb+xy\in I$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 tells us 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 must be a left ideal.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $y=0$
\end_inset

 tells us 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 must be a right ideal.
 It's easy to see that multipication in 
\begin_inset Formula $R/I$
\end_inset

 is associative and distributive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be a two-sided ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R/I$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
quotient ring
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is commutative, then 
\begin_inset Formula $R/I$
\end_inset

 is commutative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 has identity, then 
\begin_inset Formula $R/I$
\end_inset

 has identity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Properties of Ideals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring with identity and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
left ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle A\rangle_{\ell}=\bigcap_{\substack{I=\mbox{left ideal of }R\\
A\subseteq I
}
}I
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is similarly defined for right ideals and two-sided ideals.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle A\rangle_{\ell}=RA=\{r_{1}a_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}a_{n}\mid n\in\mathbb{N},\,r_{i}\in R,\,a_{i}\in A\}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It is clear 
\begin_inset Formula $RA$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 We prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $RA$
\end_inset

 is a left ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}a_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}a_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}'a_{1}'+\cdots+r_{n}'a_{n}'$
\end_inset

 are two elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $RA$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{1}a_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}a_{n}-(r_{1}'a_{1}'+\cdots+r_{n}'a_{n}')=r_{1}a_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}a_{n}-r'a_{1}'-\cdots-r_{n}'a_{n}'\in RA
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $RA$
\end_inset

 is subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 under addtion.
 Next suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}a_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}a_{n}\in RA$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
r\cdot(r_{1}a_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}a_{n}) & =(rr_{1})a_{1}+\cdots+(rr_{n})a_{n}\in RA.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $RA$
\end_inset

 is closed under left scalar multiplication.
 Finally, the distributivity laws follow from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $RA$
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and shares the same addition and scalar multiplication action.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle A\rangle_{\ell}\subseteq RA$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we show 
\begin_inset Formula $RA\subseteq\langle A\rangle_{\ell}$
\end_inset

.
 To do this, we show for any left ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, that 
\begin_inset Formula $RA\subseteq I$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}a_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}a_{n}\in RA$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is an ideal which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}a_{i}\in I$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is closed under addition, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}a_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}a_{n}\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $RA\subseteq\langle A\rangle_{\ell}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $RA\supseteq\langle A\rangle_{\ell}$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $RA=\langle A\rangle_{\ell}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is similarly proved for right ideals and two-sided ideals, using 
\begin_inset Formula $AR=\{a_{1}r_{1}+\cdots+a_{n}r_{n}\mid n\in\mathbb{N},\,r_{i}\in R,\,a_{i}\in A\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $RAR=\{r_{1}a_{1}s_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}a_{n}s_{n}\mid n\in\mathbb{N},\,r_{i},s_{i}\in R,\,a_{i}\in A\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{a\}$
\end_inset

, then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $Ra=\{ra\mid r\in R\}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
left principal ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $aR=\{ar\mid r\in R\}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
right principal ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $RaR=\{r_{1}as_{1}+\cdots+r_{n}as_{n}\mid r_{i},s_{i}\in R,\,n\in\mathbb{N}\}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
left principal ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

, the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle2,x\rangle$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
principle.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 A proper ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
maximal 
\series default
if the only ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is maximal in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 Then every proper ideal is contained in some maximal ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
 A proper ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is maximal if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R/\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime.
 We show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p,x\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

 by showing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]/\langle p,x\rangle\cong\mathbb{Z}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathbb{Z}[x]\to\mathbb{Z}_{p}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a_{0}+a_{1}x+\cdots+a_{n}x^{n})=\overline{a_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 We show 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a ring homomorphism.
 It is clearly additive, so we show it is multiplicative:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi((a_{0}+a_{1}x+\cdots+a_{n}x^{n})(b_{0}+b_{1}x+\cdots+b_{n}x^{n})) & =\varphi(a_{0}b_{0}+(a_{0}b_{1}+a_{1}b_{0})x+\cdots+(a_{0}b_{n}+\cdots+a_{n}b_{0})x^{n})\\
 & =\overline{a_{0}b_{0}}\\
 & =\overline{a_{0}}\overline{b_{0}}\\
 & =\varphi(a_{0}+a_{1}x+\cdots+a_{n}x^{n})\varphi(b_{0}+b_{1}x+\cdots+b_{n}x^{n})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the first isomorphism theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]/\mbox{Ker}\varphi\cong\mbox{Im}\varphi\cong\mathbb{Z}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly the kernel is 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle2,x\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 Denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Max}(R)=\{\mathfrak{m}\mid\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R\}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]/\langle x\rangle\cong R$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
 An ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
prime 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\neq R$
\end_inset

 and if whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, then either 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Spec}(R)=\{\mathfrak{p}\mid\mathfrak{p}\mbox{ is a prime ideal in }R\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The prime ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle0\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a prime number.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
 Then an ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is prime if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a},\overline{b}\in R/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 such 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{ab}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, which implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, which is exactly the same as saying either 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{b}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $R/\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{ab}=0$
\end_inset

 implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{b}=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

, which is the same as saying either 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Maximal ideals are prime ideals.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
local ring 
\series default
if it has a unique maximal ideal.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
 The following statements are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a local ring.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $1+x\in R^{\times}$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R\setminus R^{\times}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(1)\implies(2)$
\end_inset

: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\in\mbox{Max}(R)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R\setminus R^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

 must be contained in a maximal ideal, and the only one available is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+x)\neq R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $1+x\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 by the same argument.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $1=x-(1+x)\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $1+x$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(2)\implies(1):$
\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m'}$
\end_inset

 are maximal ideals such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m\neq m'}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\subset\mathfrak{m}+\mathfrak{m'}\subset R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\neq\mathfrak{m'}$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}+\mathfrak{m'}=R$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $1=a+b$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mathfrak{m'}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1-b$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b\notin R^{\times}$
\end_inset

, but that would make 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R^{\times}$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Basic Theorems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Isomorphism Theorems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
First Isomorphism Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (First Isomorphism Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be rings and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon R\to S$
\end_inset

 be a ring homomorphism.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a two-sided ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and moreover we have the ring isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash\ker\varphi\cong\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 First let us check 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a two-sided ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 First note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an additive subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, this follows from the first isomorphism theorem for groups.
 So to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a two-sided ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, it suffices to show that it is closed under scalar multiplication: let
 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(ax) & =a\varphi(x)\\
 & =a\cdot0\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\in\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 A similar computation shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $xa\in\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a two-sided ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 First let us check 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Again, it follows from the first isomorphism theorem for groups that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an additive subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 So to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 is closed under multiplication in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and shares the same identity: let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a),\varphi(b)\in\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a ring homomorphism, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(a)\varphi(b) & =\varphi(ab)\\
 & \in\mathrm{im}\,\varphi.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 is closed under multiplication in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 It also shares the same identity as 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 since ring homomoprhisms by definition maps the multiplicative identity
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 to the multiplicative identity in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi}\colon R\slash\ker\varphi\to\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\varphi}(\overline{a})=\varphi(a)\label{eq:welldefinedgmodker-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a}\in R\slash\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 By the first isomorphism theorem for groups, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 is a well-defined group isomorphism.
 To see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
ring 
\emph default
isomorphism, it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 respects multiplication and that it maps the multiplicative identity in
 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 to the multiplicative identity in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

: let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a},\overline{b}\in R\slash\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{\varphi}(\overline{a}\overline{b}) & =\overline{\varphi}(\overline{ab})\\
 & =\varphi(ab)\\
 & =\varphi(a)\varphi(b)\\
 & =\overline{\varphi}(\overline{a})\overline{\varphi}(\overline{b}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Also 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi}(\overline{1})=\varphi(1)=1$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 gives a ring isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Second Isomorphism Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Second Isomorphism Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A+B=\{a+b\mid a\in A,\,b\in B\}$
\end_inset

 is a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A/A\cap B\cong(A+B)/B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are normal subroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 under additon, 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 under addition too.
 Multiplication is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(a+b)(a'+b')=aa'+ab'+ba'+bb'\in A+B
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,a'\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b,b'\in B$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B$
\end_inset

 is closed under multiplication.
 Left and right distributive laws hold because 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B$
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with the same addition and multiplication operations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A\cap B$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is an ideal, 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\in B$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\in A$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\in A\cap B$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Define a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A+B\to A/A\cap B$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a+b)=\overline{a}$
\end_inset

.
 This is well-defined since if 
\begin_inset Formula $a'+b'=a+b$
\end_inset

 is another representation, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(a'+b') & =\overline{a'}\\
 & =\overline{a+b-b'}\\
 & =\overline{a},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $b-b'\in A\cap B$
\end_inset

.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is clearly surjective, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=B$
\end_inset

.
 So by the first isomorphism theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $A/A\cap B\cong(A+B)/B$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Take 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A=12\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=15\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B=3\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B=60\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 So the second isomorphism theorem tells us 
\begin_inset Formula $12\mathbb{Z}/60\mathbb{Z}\cong3\mathbb{Z}/15\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Third Isomorphism Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I,J$
\end_inset

 be ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq J$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $J/I$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R/I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(R/I)/(J/I)\cong R/J$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:R/I\to R/J$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(\overline{a})=\overline{a}$
\end_inset

.
 This is well-defined since if 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{a+x}$
\end_inset

 is another representative, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(\overline{a+x}) & =\overline{a+x}\\
 & =\overline{a}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq J$
\end_inset

.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a surjective ring homomorphism with kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $J/I$
\end_inset

.
 So by the first isomorphism theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $(R/I)/(J/I)\cong R/J$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Show that the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+y^{2}=3z^{2}$
\end_inset

 has no solutions in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b,c)$
\end_inset

 is a solution.
 We can assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(a,b,c)=1$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+y^{2}-3z^{2}$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+y^{2}\equiv3z^{2}\mbox{ mod }n$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

.
 However when 
\begin_inset Formula $n=4$
\end_inset

, we run into a problem, since 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\equiv0\mbox{ mod }4$
\end_inset

 has no solutions where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Chinese Remainder Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 be ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 are 
\series bold
relatively prime 
\series default
to one another if 
\begin_inset Formula $I+J=R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In other words, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in J$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y=1$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=a\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J=b\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(a,b)=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1},\dots,I_{k}$
\end_inset

 be pairwise relatively prime 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime, then 
\begin_inset Formula $I\cap J=IJ$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1},\dots,I_{k}$
\end_inset

 are pairwise relatively prime (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{i}+I_{j}=R$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

), then 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}\cdots I_{k}=I_{1}\cap\cdots\cap I_{k}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 The inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $IJ\subset I\cap J$
\end_inset

 holds in every ring.
 For the reverse inclusion, note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
I\cap J & =(I\cap J)(I+J)\\
 & \subset IJ.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 We prove by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 The base case is (1).
 Now suppose the statement is true for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k-1\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1},\dots I_{k-1}$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime to 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{k}$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in I_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\in I_{k}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}+y_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i<k$
\end_inset

.
 Choose such 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in I_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\in I_{k}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i<k$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
1 & =(x_{1}+y_{1})\cdots(x_{k-1}+y_{k-1})\\
 & \in I_{1}\cdots I_{k-1}+I_{k}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}\cdots I_{k-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{k}$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime.
 Therefore using the base case and induction step, we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
I_{1}\cap\cdots\cap I_{k} & =(I_{1}\cdots I_{k-1})\cap I_{k}\\
 & =I_{1}\cdots I_{k}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (The Chinese Remainder Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1},\dots,I_{k}$
\end_inset

 be pairwise relatively prime ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R\slash I_{1}\cdots I_{k}\cong R\slash I_{1}\times\cdots\times R\slash I_{k}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon R\to R\slash I_{1}\times\cdots\times R\slash I_{k}$
\end_inset

 be the ring homomorphism given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(r)=(r+I_{1},\dots,r+I_{k})
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in R$
\end_inset

.
 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(r_{1}+I_{1},\dots,r_{k}+I_{k})\in R\slash I_{1}\times\cdots\times R\slash I_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1},\dots,I_{k}$
\end_inset

 are pairwise relatively prime, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i<j\leq k$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{ij}\in I_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{ji}\in I_{j}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{ij}+x_{ji}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r:=\sum_{j=1}^{k}r_{j}x_{1j}\cdots\widehat{x}_{jj}\cdots x_{kj}\in R,
\]

\end_inset

where the hat symbol means omit that element.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(r)=(r_{1}+I_{1},\dots,r_{k}+I_{k})$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{ij}\equiv1\text{ mod }I_{j}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 fixed and 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $r\text{ mod }I_{j}\equiv r_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next, observe that the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}\cdots I_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(r)=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $r+I_{j}=I_{j}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\dots,k$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in I_{1}\cap\cdots\cap I_{k}=I_{1}\cdots I_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 The theorem now follows from the first isomorphism theorem for rings.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Polynomial Rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important class of rings are the 
\series bold
polynomial rings
\series default
.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a ring, then we define the 
\series bold
polynomial ring over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-variables
\series default
, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $R[X_{1},\dots,X_{n}]$
\end_inset

, to be the set of all elements of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{n})\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}^{n}}a_{(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{n})}X_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}\cdots X_{n}^{\alpha_{n}}\label{eq:polynomialdef}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{n})}\in R$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{n})}=0$
\end_inset

 for all but finitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{n})\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We call the elements in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:polynomialdef})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\series bold
polynomials
\series default
.
 The elements 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{n})}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
coefficients
\series default
.
 A 
\series bold
monomial 
\series default
is a polynomial of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}\cdots X_{n}^{\alpha_{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 To simplify our notation, we usually denote a polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $R[X_{1},\dots,X_{n}]$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}a_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}X^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}=\sum_{(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{n})\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}^{n}}a_{(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{n})}X_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}\cdots X_{n}^{\alpha_{n}},
\]

\end_inset

where it is understood that bold greek letters like 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 denote a vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Addition in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[X_{1},\dots,X_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}a_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}X^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}+\sum_{\boldsymbol{\beta}}b_{\boldsymbol{\beta}}X^{\boldsymbol{\beta}}=\sum_{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}(a_{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}+b_{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})X^{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiplication in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[X_{1},\dots,X_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}a_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}X^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\sum_{\boldsymbol{\beta}}b_{\boldsymbol{\beta}}X^{\boldsymbol{\beta}}=\sum_{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\left(\sum_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}+\boldsymbol{\beta}=\boldsymbol{\gamma}}a_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}b_{\boldsymbol{\beta}}\right)X^{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}.
\]

\end_inset

One should check that addition and multiplication defined in this way really
 does turn 
\begin_inset Formula $R[X_{1},\dots,X_{n}]$
\end_inset

 into a ring.
 For instance, associativity of multiplication holds in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[X_{1},\dots,X_{n}]$
\end_inset

 because it holds in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\sum_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}a_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}X^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\sum_{\boldsymbol{\beta}}b_{\boldsymbol{\beta}}X^{\boldsymbol{\beta}}\right)\sum_{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}c_{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}X^{\boldsymbol{\gamma}} & =\sum_{\boldsymbol{\delta}}\left(\sum_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}+\boldsymbol{\beta}=\boldsymbol{\delta}}a_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}b_{\boldsymbol{\beta}}\right)X^{\boldsymbol{\delta}}\sum_{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}c_{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}X^{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\\
 & =\sum_{\boldsymbol{\kappa}}\left(\sum_{\boldsymbol{\delta}+\boldsymbol{\gamma}=\boldsymbol{\kappa}}\left(\sum_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}+\boldsymbol{\beta}=\boldsymbol{\delta}}a_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}b_{\boldsymbol{\beta}}\right)c_{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\right)X^{\boldsymbol{\kappa}}\\
 & =\sum_{\boldsymbol{\kappa}}\left(\sum_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}+\boldsymbol{\beta}+\boldsymbol{\gamma}=\boldsymbol{\kappa}}(a_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}b_{\boldsymbol{\beta}})c_{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\right)X^{\boldsymbol{\kappa}}\\
 & =\sum_{\boldsymbol{\kappa}}\left(\sum_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}+\boldsymbol{\beta}+\boldsymbol{\gamma}=\boldsymbol{\kappa}}\sum_{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}a_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}(b_{\boldsymbol{\beta}}c_{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})\right)X^{\boldsymbol{\kappa}}\\
 & =\sum_{\boldsymbol{\kappa}}\left(\sum_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}+\boldsymbol{\beta}+\boldsymbol{\gamma}=\boldsymbol{\kappa}}a_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}(b_{\boldsymbol{\beta}}c_{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})\right)X^{\boldsymbol{\kappa}}\\
 & =\sum_{\boldsymbol{\kappa}}\left(\sum_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}+\boldsymbol{\delta}=\boldsymbol{\kappa}}a_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\sum_{\boldsymbol{\beta}+\boldsymbol{\gamma}=\boldsymbol{\delta}}b_{\boldsymbol{\beta}}c_{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\right)X^{\boldsymbol{\kappa}}\\
 & =\sum_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}a_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}X^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\sum_{\boldsymbol{\delta}}\left(\sum_{\boldsymbol{\beta}+\boldsymbol{\gamma}=\boldsymbol{\delta}}b_{\boldsymbol{\beta}}c_{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\right)X^{\boldsymbol{\delta}}\\
 & =\sum_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}a_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}X^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\left(\sum_{\boldsymbol{\beta}}b_{\boldsymbol{\beta}}X^{\boldsymbol{\beta}}\sum_{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}c_{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}X^{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Here are two polynimals in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[X,Y]$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(X,Y)=3X^{2}Y+2Y\quad\text{and}\quad g(X,Y)=X^{2}Y-Y^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Let's add and multiply these two polynomials together.
 We get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(f+g)(X,Y) & :=f(X,Y)+g(X,Y)\\
 & =3X^{2}Y+2Y+X^{2}Y-Y^{2}\\
 & =4X^{2}Y+2Y-Y^{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Next, let's multiply them together.
 We get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(f\cdot g)(X,Y) & :=f(X,Y)g(X,Y)\\
 & =(3X^{2}Y+2Y)(X^{2}Y-Y^{2})\\
 & =3X^{4}Y^{2}-3X^{2}Y^{3}+2X^{2}Y^{2}-2Y^{3}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get a better understanding of polynomial rings, we first study polynomials
 rings in one variable, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $R[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Polynomial Ring over a Domain is a Domain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain.
 Then the polynomial ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R[X]$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in R[X]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $fg=0$
\end_inset

.
 Write them as 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\sum a_{k}X^{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\sum b_{m}X^{m}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k},b_{m}\in R$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k,m\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}=0=b_{m}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k,m\gg0$
\end_inset

.
 Then the polynomial identity 
\begin_inset Formula $fg=0$
\end_inset

 gives us the equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{k=0}^{n}a_{k}b_{n-k}=0\label{eq:polyringoverdomainisdomain}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 If both 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, then we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $f=X\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g=X\widetilde{g}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f},\widetilde{g}\in R[X]$
\end_inset

.
 In this case,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =fg\\
 & =X\widetilde{f}X\widetilde{g}\\
 & =X^{2}\widetilde{f}\widetilde{g}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}\widetilde{g}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{g}$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we may assume that one of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero.
 Without loss of generality, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 (which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $f=0$
\end_inset

).
 Indeed, we will prove this by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 For the base case 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

, the polynomial identity 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:polyringoverdomainisdomain})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 case gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}b_{0}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Now suppose we have shown 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq k<n$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the polynomial identity 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:polyringoverdomainisdomain})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 together with the induction assumption implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\sum_{k=0}^{n}a_{k}b_{n-k}\\
 & =a_{n}b_{0}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Again since 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a domain, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 by induction.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $f=0$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $R[X]$
\end_inset

 is a domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gauss' Lemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Gauss' Lemma) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a UFD with fraction field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in R[X]$
\end_inset

 has positive degree and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f=gh$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in R[X]$
\end_inset

 having positive degree.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f=c\cdot\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 for some nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in R$
\end_inset

 and some 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}\in R[X]$
\end_inset

, it suffices to treat 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, by factoring out the greatest common divisor of the coefficients
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 (which makes sense since the coefficient ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a UFD), we may assume that the coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 have gcd equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 We call such polynomials 
\series bold
primitive
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The key fact that we need is that a product of primitives is a primitive.
 To prove it, let 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in R[X]$
\end_inset

 be such that 
\begin_inset Formula $gh\in R[X]$
\end_inset

 is not primitive.
 We wish to prove that one of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is not primitive.
 The non-primitivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $gh$
\end_inset

 implies that some nonzero non-unit 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in R$
\end_inset

 divides all coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $gh$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is an irreducible factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 divides all coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $gh$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{R}=R\slash(\pi)$
\end_inset

, a domain since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is irreducible and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a UFD.
 Working in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{R}[X]$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}\overline{h}=\overline{gh}=0$
\end_inset

.
 But a polynomial ring over a domain is again a domain, so one of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{h}$
\end_inset

 vanishes.
 This says that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 divides all coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, so one of these is non-primitive, as desired.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Say our given non-trivial factorization is 
\begin_inset Formula $f=gh$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in K[X]$
\end_inset

 having positive degree.
 If we write the coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 as reduced form fractions with a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

least common denominator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and then consider the gcd of the numerators, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $g=qg_{0}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{0}\in R[X]$
\end_inset

 is primitive.
 Likewise, 
\begin_inset Formula $h=q'h_{0}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $q'\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{0}\in R[X]$
\end_inset

 is primitive.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(qq')g_{0}h_{0}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{0}h_{0}$
\end_inset

 both primitive.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $qq'=a/b$
\end_inset

 as a reduced-form fraction with 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 in the UFD 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $bf=ag_{0}h_{0}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Comparing gcd's of coefficients on both sides, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $a=bu$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in R^{\times}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $qq'=u\in R^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(ug_{0})(h_{0})$
\end_inset

 is a factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[X]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $ug_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{0}$
\end_inset

 having positive degree.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Gauss Lemma) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a UFD and let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be its field of fractions.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=A(x)B(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $A(x),B(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{deg}(A(x)),\mbox{deg}(B(x))\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 There is some 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $df(x)=a'(x)b'(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a'(x),b'(x)\in R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a UFD, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d=p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 being irreducible.
 Now since 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 is prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 is prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 too.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{m}f(x)=a'(x)b'(x)\qquad\mbox{in }R[x]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\mid a'(x)b'(x)$
\end_inset

 together with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 being a prime implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 divides one of 
\begin_inset Formula $a'(x)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b'(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Say 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $a'(x)$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $a'(x)=p_{1}a''(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a''(x)\in R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{n}f(x)=p_{1}a''(x)b'(x).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And since we are in an integral domain, we can cancel 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 on both sides.
 The proceeding inductively, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Polynomial Rings that are UFDs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 is irreducible when 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=g(x)h(x)$
\end_inset

 implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 is a unit or 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 Another way to think of this is that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible if it factors as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=g(x)h(x)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq\mbox{deg}(g(x))<\mbox{deg}(f(x))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq\mbox{deg}(h(x))<\mbox{deg}(f(x))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 is a UFD if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a UFD.
 To show this, we need Gauss' Lemma:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Gauss Lemma) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a UFD and let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be its field of fractions.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=A(x)B(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $A(x),B(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{deg}(A(x)),\mbox{deg}(B(x))\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 There is some 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $df(x)=a'(x)b'(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a'(x),b'(x)\in R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a UFD, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d=p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 being irreducible.
 Now since 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 is prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 is prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 too.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{m}f(x)=a'(x)b'(x)\qquad\mbox{in }R[x]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\mid a'(x)b'(x)$
\end_inset

 together with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 being a prime implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 divides one of 
\begin_inset Formula $a'(x)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b'(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Say 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $a'(x)$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $a'(x)=p_{1}a''(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a''(x)\in R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{n}f(x)=p_{1}a''(x)b'(x).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And since we are in an integral domain, we can cancel 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 on both sides.
 The proceeding inductively, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a UFD and let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be its field of fractions.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in R[x]$
\end_inset

 be such that the gcd of the coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Then by Gauss' Lemma, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=a(x)b(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a(x),b(x)\in R[x]\subset F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

, one of the factors, say 
\begin_inset Formula $a(x)$
\end_inset

, has to a constant; 
\begin_inset Formula $a(x)=r\in R$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=rb(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in R$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 divides all of the coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 is a UFD if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a UFD.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero nonunit element in 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 be the gcd of the coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=dp(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in R[x]$
\end_inset

 and such that the gcd of the coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a UFD, 
\begin_inset Formula $d=q_{1}q_{2}\cdots q_{t}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, so they are also prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 So it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is a finite product of irreducibles in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

 is a UFD, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=p_{1}'(x)\cdots p_{n}'(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}'(x)$
\end_inset

 irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 By Gauss' Lemma, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=p_{1}(x)\cdots p_{n}(x)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(x)=a_{i}p_{i}'(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}'(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(x)\mid p(x)$
\end_inset

, the gcd of the coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We need to show uniqueness.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 be such that the gcd of all coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=p_{1}(x)\cdots p_{n}(x)=\ell_{1}(x)\cdots\ell_{s}(x)$
\end_inset

 are two factorizations into irreducibles in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]\subseteq F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $n=s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(x)\sim\ell_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

 is a UFD.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}p_{i}(x)=a_{i}\ell_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i},b_{i}\in R$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 So gcd of LHS is the same as the gcd of the RHS which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}=b_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(x)\sim\ell_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero nonunit element in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in R[x]$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $r=p_{1}(x)\cdots p_{n}(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 be irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 But the the degree on the left side must be equal to the degree of the
 right hand side.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{deg}(p_{i}(x))=0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(x)=p_{i}\in R$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Uniqueness holds because 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 is a UFD and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Irreducibility Criteria
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{rootfactor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 has a factor of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 there is some 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=(ax+b)g(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in F$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=-ab^{-1}\in F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=(x-\alpha)g(x)+r(x)
\]

\end_inset

where either 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{deg}r(x)<1$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=r\in F$
\end_inset

 is a constant.
 And this is a contradiciton since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(\alpha) & =(\alpha-\alpha)g(\alpha)+r(\alpha)\\
 & =r,
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=(x-\alpha)g(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{rootdeg2}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 has a root 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in F$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=(x-\alpha)g(x)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=g(x)h(x)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x),h(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{deg}g(x)+\mbox{deg}h(x)=\mbox{deg}f(x)\leq3
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{rootfactor})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 must have a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{rovers}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=a_{n}x^{n}+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{1}x+a_{0}\in\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r/s\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(r,s)=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $r\mid a_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s\mid a_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $r/s$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =f\left(\frac{r}{s}\right)\\
 & =a_{n}\left(\frac{r}{s}\right)^{n}+a_{n-1}\left(\frac{r}{s}\right)^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{1}\left(\frac{r}{s}\right)+a_{0}\\
 & =\frac{a_{n}r^{n}+a_{n-1}sr^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{1}s^{n-1}r+a_{0}s^{n}}{s^{n}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r(a_{n}r^{n-1}+a_{n-1}sr^{n-2}+\cdots+a_{1}s^{n-1})=-a_{0}s^{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $r\mid a_{0}s^{n}$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime, 
\begin_inset Formula $r\mid a_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s(a_{n-1}r^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{1}s^{n-2}r+a_{0}s^{n-1})=-a_{n}r^{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $s\mid a_{n}$
\end_inset

 by the same reasoning as above.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{exampleroot}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{3}+x^{2}+1\in\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

.
 By Gauss' Lemma, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is reducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[x]$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{rootdeg2})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 has a root 
\begin_inset Formula $r/s\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{rovers})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s\mid1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r\mid1$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $r/s=\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 However 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\pm1)\neq0$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime.
 We show 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{3}-p\in\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Using the same reasoning as in the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{exampleroot})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, the only possible roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{3}-p$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

, however none of these are roots.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Eisenstein's Criterion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an in integral domain, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(T)=T^{n}+c_{n-1}T^{n-1}+\cdots+c_{0}
\]

\end_inset

be a monic polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[T]$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq1\leq n-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}\notin\mathfrak{p}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[T]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is reducible, say 
\begin_inset Formula $f=gh$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(T)=\sum_{k\geq0}a_{k}T^{k}\quad\text{and}\quad h(T)=\sum_{l\geq0}b_{l}T^{l}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k},b_{l}\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k\gg0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{l}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $l\gg0$
\end_inset

.
 The polynomial identity 
\begin_inset Formula $f=gh$
\end_inset

 gives us the system of equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{k=0}^{m}a_{k}b_{m-k}=c_{m}\label{eq:eisensteinpolyeq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq m\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 In the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $m=0$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}b_{0}=c_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}\in\mathfrak{p}\backslash\mathfrak{p}^{2}$
\end_inset

, we must have either 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, but not both! Without loss of generality, say 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, we will prove this by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq m<n$
\end_inset

.
 The base case 
\begin_inset Formula $m=0$
\end_inset

 is assumed above.
 Suppose that we have shown 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\leq m$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq m<n$
\end_inset

.
 Then the identity 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:eisensteinpolyeq})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $m+1$
\end_inset

 case implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \equiv c_{m+1}\,\mod\mathfrak{p}\\
 & \equiv\sum_{k=0}^{m+1}a_{k}b_{m-k}\,\mod\mathfrak{p}\\
 & \equiv a_{m+1}b_{0}\,\mod\mathfrak{p}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{m+1}b_{0}\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{m+1}\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus by induction, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 But this contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is monic! Indeed, the identity 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:eisensteinpolyeq})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 case together with the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{n}\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 However 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{n}=1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{5}-30x^{4}+9x^{3}-6x+3$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

 by Eisenstein's Criterion for 
\begin_inset Formula $p=3$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{4}+1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x+1)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x+1)=x^{4}+4x^{3}+6x^{2}+4x+2$
\end_inset

 is Eisenstein at 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x+1)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Goldbach Conjecture for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[X]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It turns out that we can use Eisenstein's Criterion to prove Goldbach's
 conjecture for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 The following proposition and proof were 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[X]$
\end_inset

 is the sum of two irreducible polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 be any polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[X]$
\end_inset

 and write it as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(X)=\sum_{k=0}^{n}a_{k}X^{k}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq k\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Choose any two distinct odd primes, say 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\gcd(p,q)=1$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{k},v_{k}\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{k}=u_{k}p+v_{k}q
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq k\leq n.$
\end_inset

 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(X)=(u_{0}+rq)p+\sum_{k=1}^{n}u_{k}pX^{k}+X^{n+1}\quad\text{and}\quad h(X)=(v_{0}-rp)q+\sum_{k=1}^{n}v_{k}qX^{k}-X^{n+1}.
\]

\end_inset

Clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g+h$
\end_inset

.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 almost satisfy Eisenstein's irreducibility criterion: all coefficients
 except the leading term are divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 (resp.
 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

).
 However, we want to ensure that the constant term is not divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}$
\end_inset

 (resp.
 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{2}$
\end_inset

).
 In other words, we need
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p\nmid u_{0}+rq\quad\text{and}\quad q\nmid v_{0}-rp.\label{eq:goldbachconjzx}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This can easily be acheived: as most one of the numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}-q,u_{0},u_{0}+q$
\end_inset

 is a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 because the gcd of two of them divides 
\begin_inset Formula $2q$
\end_inset

 and at most one of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{0}+p,v_{0},v_{0}-p$
\end_inset

 is a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 Hence at least one of the choices 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\{-1,0,1\}$
\end_inset

 leads to 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:goldbachconjzx})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 With this choice, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 are irreducible per Einstein.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Integral Domains
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 An element 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
zerodivisor 
\series default
if there exists a nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=0$
\end_inset

.
 If there does not exist a nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=0$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
nonzerodivisor
\series default
.
 If every nonzero element in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a nonzerodivisor, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
integral domain
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The ring of integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every field is an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is prime and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x},\overline{y}\in R\slash I$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}\overline{y}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $xy\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is prime, we either have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in I$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, either 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $xy\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}\overline{y}=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, we either have 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}=0$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, either 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A finite integral domain is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon R\to R$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(x)=ax
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is finite, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is bijective.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(b)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is a multiplicative inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Euclidean Domains
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An integral domain 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
Euclidean 
\series default
if there is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}\colon R\backslash\{0\}\to\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 has division with remainder with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

 we can find 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a=bq+r,\qquad r=0\text{ or }\mathrm{d}(r)<\mathrm{d}(b).\label{eq:euclideanfunction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We allow 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

 in this definition since in that case we can use 
\begin_inset Formula $q=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
 A function satisfying 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:euclideanfunction})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
Euclidean function
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Examples of Euclidean Domains
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean domain with respect to the Euclidean function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}\colon K\backslash\{0\}\to\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}(x)=0
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in K$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

, then we set 
\begin_inset Formula $q=ab^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The ring of integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean domain with respect to the Euclidean function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}\colon\mathbb{Z}\backslash\{0\}\to\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}(m)=|m|
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $|a|<|b|$
\end_inset

, then we set 
\begin_inset Formula $q=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r=a$
\end_inset

, so assume 
\begin_inset Formula $|a|>|b|$
\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality, assume both 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are positive.
 Then there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
bq\leq a<b(q+1).
\]

\end_inset

Choose such a 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $r=a-bq$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $bq=a$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

, otherwise
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|r| & =|a-bq|\\
 & <|b(q+1)-bq|\\
 & =|b(q+1-q)|\\
 & =|b|.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 be a Euclidean domain and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=bx+y
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then it may not be the case that either 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(y)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(y)<\mathrm{d}(b)$
\end_inset

.
 Being a Euclidean domain just means that there exists at least one such
 pair of elements 
\begin_inset Formula $q,r\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=bq+r
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(r)<\mathrm{d}(b)$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
10 & =3\cdot1+7,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $|7|\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|7|\not<|3|$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean Domain with respect to the Euclidean function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}\colon K[T]\backslash\{0\}\to\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}(f)=\deg f
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in K[T]\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in K[T]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 We can perform long division to get 
\begin_inset Formula $q,r\in K[T]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=gq+r
\]

\end_inset

where either 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg r<\deg g$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The Gaussian integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[i]$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean domain with respect to the Euclidean function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}\colon\mathbb{Z}[i]\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}(m+in)=|m+in|=m^{2}+n^{2}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m+in\in\mathbb{Z}[i]$
\end_inset

.
 To see how this works, let 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}=m_{1}+in_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{2}=m_{2}+in_{2}$
\end_inset

 be two Gaussian integers with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{2}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}/z_{2}$
\end_inset

 may not be a Gaussian integer, but it is a complex number.
 Recall that the Gaussian integers forms a lattice inside the complex plane.
 In particular, we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 to be a Gaussian integer which is as closed to 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}/z_{2}$
\end_inset

 as possible; that is if 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is any other Gaussian integer, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $|q-z_{1}/z_{2}|\leq|z-z_{1}/z_{2}|$
\end_inset

.
 Now with 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 chosen, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $r=z_{1}-z_{2}q$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, both 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 are Gaussian integers.
 We also have 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}=z_{2}q+r$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $|q-z_{1}/z_{2}|\leq1/\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 (here we are using the fact that the Gaussian integers forms a lattice
 inside of the complex plane).
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $r\neq0$
\end_inset

, then we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{d}(r) & =\mathrm{d}(z_{1}-z_{2}q)\\
 & =|z_{1}-z_{2}q|\\
 & =|z_{2}||z_{1}/z_{2}-q|\\
 & \leq|z_{2}|/\sqrt{2}\\
 & <|z_{2}|\\
 & =\mathrm{d}(z_{2}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Refining the Euclidean Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 be a Euclidean domain.
 We will introduce a new Euclidean function 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}\colon R\backslash\{0\}\to\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

, built out of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

, which satisfies the 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}$
\end_inset


\series bold
-inequality
\series default

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}(a)\leq\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}(ab)\label{eq:dinequality}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}$
\end_inset

 as follows: for nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, we set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}(a)=\min_{b\neq0}\mathrm{d}(ab).
\]

\end_inset

That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}(a)$
\end_inset

 is the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

-value on the nonzero multiples of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 (note that 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\neq0$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain).
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a=a\cdot1$
\end_inset

 is a nonzero multilpe of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}(a)\leq\mathrm{d}(a)
\]

\end_inset

for all nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}(a)=\mathrm{d}(ab_{0})$
\end_inset

 for some nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(ab_{0})=\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}(a)\leq\mathrm{d}(ab)$
\end_inset

 for all nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}(1)=\min_{b\neq0}\mathrm{d}(b)
\]

\end_inset

is the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

-value on 
\begin_inset Formula $R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,\widetilde{\mathrm{d}})$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean domain.
 Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the inequality 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:dinequality})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 admits division with remainder with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}$
\end_inset

.
 Pick 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}(b)=\mathrm{d}(bc)$
\end_inset

 for some nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Using division of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $bc$
\end_inset

 (which is nonzero) in 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 there are 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=(bc)q_{0}+r_{0},\qquad r_{0}=0\text{ or }\mathrm{d}(r_{0})<\mathrm{d}(bc).
\]

\end_inset

Set 
\begin_inset Formula $q=cq_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r=r_{0}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $a=bq+r$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 we are done, so assume 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}(r) & =\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}(r_{0})\\
 & \leq\mathrm{d}(r_{0})\\
 & <\mathrm{d}(bc)\\
 & =\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}(b).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=bq+r,\qquad r=0\text{ or }\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}(r)<\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}(b).
\]

\end_inset

Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,\widetilde{\mathrm{d}})$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the inequality 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:dinequality})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}(ab)=\mathrm{d}(abc)$
\end_inset

 for some nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $abc$
\end_inset

 is a nonzero multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}(a)\leq\mathrm{d}(abc)=\widetilde{\mathrm{d}}(ab).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us now briefly describe two other possible refinements one might want
 in a Euclidean function: namely uniqueness of the quotient and remainder
 it produces and multiplicativity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 we write 
\begin_inset Formula $a=bq+r$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq r<|b|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 are 
\emph on
uniqely 
\emph default
determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 There is also uniqueness of the quotient and remainder when we do division
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[T]$
\end_inset

 (relative to the degree function) and in a field (the remainder is always
 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

).
 Are there other Euclidean domains where the quotient and remainder are
 unique? Division in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[i]$
\end_inset

 does 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
have a unique quotient and remainder relative to the norm on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[i]$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, dividing 
\begin_inset Formula $1+8i$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $2-4i$
\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1+8i=(2-4i)(-1+i)-1+2i\quad\text{and}\quad1+8i=(2-4i)(-2+i)+1-2i,
\]

\end_inset

where both remainders have norm 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

, which is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}(2-4i)=20$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean domain where the quotient and remainder are unique, then
 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a field or 
\begin_inset Formula $R=F[T]$
\end_inset

 for a field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Units in Euclidean Domains
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In integral domains, there are three types of elements: units, irreducibles,
 and nonirreducibles.
 In this subsection, we want to characterize what 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 be a Euclidean domain where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

-inequality and let 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\inf(\mathrm{d}(R\backslash\{0\}))$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{\times}=\{a\in R\backslash\{0\}\mid\mathrm{d}(a)=n\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(a)=n$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $q,r\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=aq+r,
\]

\end_inset

where either 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(r)<n$
\end_inset

.
 We can't have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(r)<n$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the smallest integer value which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

 takes, so 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $1=aq$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=1$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(c)=n$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{d}(a) & \leq\mathrm{d}(ab)\\
 & =\mathrm{d}(1)\\
 & \leq\mathrm{d}(c)\\
 & =n.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(a)=n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Euclidean Algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
divides 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, written 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid b$
\end_inset

, if there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ac=b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
An element 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(a,b)$
\end_inset

 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $d'\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d'\mid a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d'\mid b$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid d'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We now describe the Euclidean algorithm.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 be a Euclidean domain and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean domain, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1},r_{1}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=bq_{1}+r_{1}
\]

\end_inset

where either 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(r_{1})<\mathrm{d}(b)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}=0$
\end_inset

, then the algorithm is terminated.
 Otherwise, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(r_{1})<\mathrm{d}(b)$
\end_inset

.
 We again use the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean domain to conclude that there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2},r_{2}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b=r_{1}q_{2}+r_{2}
\]

\end_inset

where either 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(r_{2})<\mathrm{d}(r_{1})$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}=0$
\end_inset

, then the algorithm is terminated.
 Otherwise, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(r_{2})<\mathrm{d}(r_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 Continuing in this manner, at the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th step, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i+1},r_{i+1}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{i-1}=r_{i}q_{i+1}+r_{i+1},
\]

\end_inset

where we have a stirictly decreasing sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}(b)>\mathrm{d}(r_{1})>\mathrm{d}(r_{2})>\cdots>\mathrm{d}(r_{i}).
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 is well-founded, this algorithm must terminate, say at the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th step (meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n+1}=0$
\end_inset

).
 Thus, at the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th step, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{n-1}=r_{n}q_{n+1}.
\]

\end_inset

In this case, we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the last nonzero remainder in the division algorithm for 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The last nonzero remainder in the division algorithm for 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(a,b)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Principal Ideal Domains
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
principal ideal domain (PID) 
\series default
if every ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
principal
\series default
.
 In other words, every ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 can be generated by one element.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field.
 Every ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x]\slash\langle x^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 is principal.
 However we do not consider this ring to be a principal ideal domain since
 it is not a domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a PID if and only if every prime ideal is principal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a PID, then every ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is principal, so every prime ideal is principal.
 Conversely, suppose every prime ideal is principal.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is not principal.
 Consider the partially order set 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Gamma,\subseteq)$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma=\{\text{ideals }\mathfrak{a}\mid I\subseteq\mathfrak{a}\subseteq R\text{ and }\mathfrak{a}\text{ not principal}\}
\]

\end_inset

and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

 is set inclusion.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is nonempty since 
\begin_inset Formula $I\in\Gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Also note that every totally ordered subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 has an upper bound.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda})_{\lambda\in\Lambda}$
\end_inset

 is a totally ordered subset, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is an upper bound of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda})$
\end_inset

: the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is an ideal which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda})$
\end_inset

 is totally ordered and each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 Also, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is principal, then there must exist some 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 which is principal (again since 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda})$
\end_inset

 is totally ordered), thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
principal.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}\in\Gamma.
\]

\end_inset

Thus using Zorn's Lemma, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 has a maximal element, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\Gamma$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal.
 To see this, assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is not a prime ideal.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mathfrak{p},a\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mathfrak{p},b\rangle$
\end_inset

 both properly contain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 By maximality of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, they must both be principal ideals, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mathfrak{p},a\rangle=\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mathfrak{p},b\rangle=\langle y\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathfrak{p} & \subseteq\langle\mathfrak{p},a\rangle\langle\mathfrak{p},b\rangle\\
 & =(\mathfrak{p}+\langle a\rangle)(\mathfrak{p}+\langle b\rangle)\\
 & =\mathfrak{p}+\langle a\rangle\mathfrak{p}+\mathfrak{p}\langle b\rangle+\langle ab\rangle\\
 & \subseteq\mathfrak{p}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathfrak{p} & =\langle\mathfrak{p},a\rangle\langle\mathfrak{p},b\rangle\\
 & =\langle x\rangle\langle y\rangle\\
 & =\langle xy\rangle.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This is a contradiction since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\Gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal.
 However by assumption 
\emph on
all 
\emph default
prime ideals are principal, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 being prime implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is principal.
 But this again contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\Gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Thus every ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 must be principal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Euclidean Domains are Principal Ideal Domains
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every Euclidean domain is a principal ideal domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a Euclidean domain with respect to the Euclidean function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}\colon R\backslash\{0\}\to\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq R$
\end_inset

 be an ideal.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=0$
\end_inset

, then we are done, so assume 
\begin_inset Formula $I\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(x)$
\end_inset

 is minimal; that is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in I$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(x)\leq\mathrm{d}(y)$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean domain, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=qx+r\label{eq:euclideanispid}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $q,r\in R$
\end_inset

 where either 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(r)<\mathrm{d}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $r\neq0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(r)<\mathrm{d}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Rewriting 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:euclideanispid})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r=y-qx
\]

\end_inset

shows us that 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in I$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in I$
\end_inset

.
 However, this contradicts our choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(x)$
\end_inset

 being minimal, since 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(r)<\mathrm{d}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

, and since clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x\rangle\subseteq I$
\end_inset

, we in fact have 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 So every ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is principal, which means 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a principal ideal domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[x]$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
a PID since 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle2,x\rangle$
\end_inset

 is not a principal ideal, so it can't be a Euclidean Domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Principal Ideal Domains are not Necessarily Euclidean Domains
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this subsection, we will show that the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[(1+\sqrt{-19})/2]$
\end_inset

 is a principal ideal domain which is not a Euclidean domain.
 To see why it's not a Euclidean domain, we will need the following propoistion:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,\mathrm{d})$
\end_inset

 be a Euclidean domain that is not a field, so there is a nonzero nonunit
 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 with least 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

-value among all nonunits.
 Then the quotient ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

 is represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and units.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Pick 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R$
\end_inset

.
 By division with remainder in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $x=aq+r$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(r)<\mathrm{d}(a)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r\neq0$
\end_inset

, then the inequality 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(r)<\mathrm{d}(a)$
\end_inset

 forces 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 to be a unit.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\equiv r\mod a$
\end_inset

, we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

 is represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and by units.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\mathbb{Z}[(1+\sqrt{-19})/2]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a principal ideal domain which is not a Euclidean domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is not a Euclidean domain.
 First note that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is not a field since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\subseteq R$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2\notin R$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore to prove 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is not Euclidean, we will show that for no nonzero nonunit 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

 represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and units.
 First we compute the norm of a typical element 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=x+y(1+\sqrt{-19})/2$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{N}(\alpha)=x^{2}+xy+5y^{2}=\left(x+\frac{y}{2}\right)^{2}+\frac{19y^{2}}{4}.\label{eq:computenormofalpha19}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This norm always takes values 
\begin_inset Formula $\geq0$
\end_inset

 (this is cleary from the second expression) and once 
\begin_inset Formula $y\neq0$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{N}(\alpha) & \geq\frac{19y^{2}}{4}\\
 & \geq\frac{19}{4}\\
 & >4.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In particular, the units are solutions to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}(\alpha)=1$
\end_inset

, which are 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R^{\times}=\{\pm1\}.
\]

\end_inset

The first few norm values are 
\begin_inset Formula $0,1,4,5,7,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $9$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, there is no element of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with norm 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 This and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{\times}\cup\{0\}$
\end_inset

 has size 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 are the key facts we will use.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 were Euclidean, then there would be a nonzero nonunit 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

 is represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and units, so 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

.
 Perhaps 
\begin_inset Formula $1\equiv-1\mod a$
\end_inset

, but we definitely have 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1\not\equiv0\mod a$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

 has size 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 (if 
\begin_inset Formula $1\equiv-1\mod a$
\end_inset

) or has size 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 (if 
\begin_inset Formula $1\not\equiv=1\mod a$
\end_inset

).
 We show this can't happen.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash a$
\end_inset

 has size 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $2\equiv0\mod a$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid2$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}(a)\mid4$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 There are no elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with norm 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, so the only nonunits with norm dividing 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 are elements with norm 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

.
 A check using 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:computenormofalpha19})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 shows the only such numbers are 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm2$
\end_inset

.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash\langle2\rangle=R\slash\langle-2\rangle$
\end_inset

 does not have size 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+\sqrt{-19})/2$
\end_inset

 are incongruent modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm2$
\end_inset

: the difference of two of these (different) numbers, divided by two, is
 never of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y(1+\sqrt{-19})/2$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

 has size 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid3$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}(a)\mid9$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 There is no element of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with norm 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 must have norm 
\begin_inset Formula $9$
\end_inset

 (it doesn't have norm 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 since it is not a unit).
 The only elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with norm 
\begin_inset Formula $9$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm3$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\pm3$
\end_inset

.
 The ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash\langle3\rangle=R\slash\langle-3\rangle$
\end_inset

 does not have size 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+\sqrt{-19})/2$
\end_inset

 are incongruent modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm3$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{\times}\cup\{0\}$
\end_inset

 has size 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 has no element 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

 has size 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 can't be a Euclidean domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Prime ideals in Principal Ideal Domain are Maximal Ideals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a principal ideal domain and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

 is not a maximal ideal.
 Choose a maximal ideal which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p\rangle\subseteq\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a principal ideal domain, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p\rangle\subseteq\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p=xa$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

 (we cannot have 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

 since this would imply 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a\rangle=\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

, a contradiction).
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x=py$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =p-xa\\
 & =p-pya\\
 & =p(1-ya).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\neq0$
\end_inset

, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $1=ya$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a unit; a contradiction! Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a principal ideal domain.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 is a principal ideal domain if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 is an Euclidean domain, and therefore a principal ideal domain.
 Conversely, assume 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 is a principal ideal domain.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]\slash\langle x\rangle\cong R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]$
\end_inset

 is a principal ideal domain, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal, and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Unique Factorization Domains
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A nonzero nonunit element 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
irreducible
\series default
 if whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $a=bc$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $b,c\in R$
\end_inset

, then either 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in R^{\times}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in R^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is not irreducible, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
reducible
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A nonzero nonunit element 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in R$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
prime 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

 is prime.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Two nonzero elements 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

 are said to be 
\series bold
associate 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $b=au$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in R^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 We denote this by 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Equivalent Definitions of Irreducibility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero nonunit element in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 The following are equivalent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is irreducible;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal among the proper principal ideals;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $a=bc$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a unit multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $a=bc$
\end_inset

, then either 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a\rangle=\langle b\rangle$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a\rangle=\langle c\rangle$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us first show 1 implies 2.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a\rangle\subseteq\langle b\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some nonzero nonunit 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle b\rangle$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $bc=a$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is irreducible and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is a nonunit, 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 must be a unit.
 But then this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $b=ac^{-1}$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a\rangle=\langle b\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal among the proper principal ideals.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we show 2 implies 3.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a=bc$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $b,c\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 must be nonzero since 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is nonzero.
 If either 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is a unit, then we are done, so we may assume that both 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 are nonunits as well.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a\rangle\subseteq\langle b\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a\rangle\subseteq\langle c\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

 is maximal among the proper principal ideals, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a\rangle=\langle b\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a\rangle=\langle c\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a=bx$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a=cy$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In general commutative rings, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(1)\implies(2)\implies(3)\implies(4)$
\end_inset

, and none of these implications reverse.
 For more general commutative rings, 
\begin_inset Formula $(1)$
\end_inset

 is the definition of an irreducible element, 
\begin_inset Formula $(2)$
\end_inset

 is the definition of a strongly irreducible element, 
\begin_inset Formula $(3)$
\end_inset

 is the definition of an 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-irreducible element, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(4)$
\end_inset

 is the definition of a very strongly irreducible element.
 Our focus however is on integral domains, so we will worry about these
 generalizations.
 Thus whenever we talk about irreducible or reducible elements, we will
 always assume that we are in an integral domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Primes are Irreducible
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{primeisirreducible}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain.
 Then every prime is irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime element in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $p=ab$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is prime, either 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid a$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid b$
\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality, assume 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid a$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a=px$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(px)b$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p(1-xb)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\neq0$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $1-xb=0$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 must be a unit.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Irreducibles are Prime in a Principal Ideal Domain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The converse to 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{primeisirreducible})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
always true.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Take 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\mathbb{Z}[\sqrt{-5}]$
\end_inset

.
 We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[\sqrt{-5}]$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 is not prime.
 Recall the norm 
\begin_inset Formula $N:\mathbb{Z}[\sqrt{-5}]\to\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $N(a+b\sqrt{-5})=a^{2}+5b^{2}$
\end_inset

, is multiplicative.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $3=\alpha\beta$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta\in\mathbb{Z}[\sqrt{-5}]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $N(3)=N(\alpha)N(\beta)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $9=N(\alpha)N(\beta)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\alpha)=9$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\beta)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\beta)=9$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\alpha)=1$
\end_inset

.
 So assume 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\alpha)=N(\beta)=3$
\end_inset

.
 But this is impossible since there are no integers 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}+5b^{2}=3$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 is not prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[\sqrt{-5}]$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid(2+\sqrt{-5})(2-\sqrt{-5})$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $3\not\mid(2+\sqrt{-5})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $3\not\mid(2-\sqrt{-5})$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a PID.
 A nonzero element is prime if and only if it is irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 From 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{primeisirreducible})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we know that being prime implies being irreducible.
 So it suffices to check the converse.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible element in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle r\rangle\subset\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 for some maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a PID, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\langle m\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle r\rangle$
\end_inset

, there is some 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $r=mq$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is irreducible and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is not a unit, 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 must be a unit, so 
\begin_inset Formula $qu=1$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m=ru$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle r\rangle$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\langle r\rangle$
\end_inset

.
  
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Irreducibles are not Necessarily Prime in General
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, irreducibles are not necessarily prime.
 Indeed, consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[X^{2},X^{3}]$
\end_inset

.
 In this ring, both 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{3}$
\end_inset

 are irreducible.
 On the other hand, notice that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(X^{3})(X^{3})=X^{6}=(X^{2})(X^{2})(X^{2}).
\]

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{2}$
\end_inset

 divides the product 
\begin_inset Formula $(X^{3})(X^{3})$
\end_inset

 but it does not divide any term in that product.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For another example, consider the ring 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{R}+X\mathbb{C}[X]=\{a_{0}+a_{1}X+a_{2}X+\cdots+a_{n}X^{n}\mid n\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0},a_{0}\in\mathbb{R},a_{1},\dots,a_{n}\in\mathbb{C}\}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in this ring but not prime.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For a final example, consider the ring of all algebraic integers:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{\mathbb{Z}}=\{z\in\mathbb{C}\mid z\text{ is a root of a monic polynomial in }\mathbb{Z}[X]\}.
\]

\end_inset

This domain has 
\emph on
no 
\emph default
irreducibles.
 To see this, note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\overline{\mathbb{Z}}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{z}\in\overline{\mathbb{Z}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z=\sqrt{z}\sqrt{z}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{z}\notin\overline{\mathbb{Z}}^{\times}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $z\notin\overline{\mathbb{Z}}^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Definition of Unique Factorization Domain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
unique factorization domain (UFD)
\series default
 if every nonzero nonunit element 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 satisfies the following two properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
an irreducible factorization exists: we can express 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 as a product of irreducible elements, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a=p_{1}\cdots p_{m}\label{eq:irrfactdef}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1},\dots,p_{m}$
\end_inset

 are irreducible elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we call 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:irrfactdef})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 an 
\series bold
irreducible factorization 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and we say 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
length 
\series default
of this irreducible factorization.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
irreducible factorizations are unique: If we have two irreducible factorizations
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{1}\cdots p_{m}=a=q_{1}\cdots q_{n}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1},\dots,p_{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1},\dots,q_{n}$
\end_inset

 are irreducible elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n$
\end_inset

 and (perhaps after relabeling the irreducible elements), we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}\sim q_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 has a 
\series bold
unique irreducible factorization
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Irreducible Factorizations Exists in Noetherian Rings 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this subsubsection, we will show that irreducible factorizations of nonzero
 nonunits exists in a large class of rings.
 These rings are called Noetherian rings.
 Let us recall the definition of this ring:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
Noetherian ring 
\series default
if it satisfies the ascending chain property: if 
\begin_inset Formula $(I_{n})$
\end_inset

 is an ascending sequence of ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 (where ascending means 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}\subseteq I_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

), then it must 
\series bold
terminate
\series default
, that is, there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}=I_{N}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 One can show that the ascending chain property is equivalent to the property
 that every ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated.
 In particular, principal ideal domains are Noetherian rings.
 We will use this fact in a moment.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian domain and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero nonunit in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 has an irreducible factorization.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is irreducible, then we are done, so assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is reducible.
 We assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 cannot be factored into irreducible.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is reducible, there is a factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 into nonzero nonunits, say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=a_{1}b_{1}.
\]

\end_inset

If both 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}$
\end_inset

 can be factored into irreducibles, then so can 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, so at least one of them cannot be factored into irreducible elements,
 say 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 is reducible, and thus there is factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 into nonzero nonunits, say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{1}=a_{2}b_{2}.
\]

\end_inset

By the same reasoning above, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

 cannot be factored into irreducibles.
 Proceeding inductively, we construct sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(b_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 where each 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

 is reducible and each
\series bold
 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a nonzero nonunit, furthermore we have the factorization
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n}=a_{n+1}b_{n+1}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we have an ascending chain of ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $(\langle a_{n}\rangle)$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a_{n}\rangle\subseteq\langle a_{n+1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=a_{n+1}b_{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, this ascending chain must terminate, say at 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a_{N}\rangle=\langle a_{N+1}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 This implies there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{N}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{N}c_{N}=a_{N+1}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =a_{N}-a_{N+1}b_{N+1}\\
 & =a_{N}-a_{N}c_{N}b_{N+1}\\
 & =a_{N}(1-c_{N}b_{N+1}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{N+1}c_{N}=1$
\end_inset

 (as 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{N}\neq0$
\end_inset

), which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{N+1}$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 This is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Principal Ideal Domains are Unique Factorization Domains
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this subsubsection, we will show that every principal ideal domain is
 a unique factorization domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a principal ideal domain.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a unique factorization domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 be nonzero nonunit in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a Noetherian, an irreducible factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 exists, so it suffices to check that such an irreducible factorization
 is unique.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{1}\cdots p_{m}=a=q_{1}\cdots q_{n}\label{eq:irrfact}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

be two irreducible factorizations of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 By relabeling if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $m\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 We will prove by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq1$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n$
\end_inset

 and (perhaps after relabeling) we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}\sim q_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 For base case 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{1}=a=q_{1}\cdots q_{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first step will be to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

.
 To prove this, we assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $n>1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a principal ideal domain, every irreducible is a prime.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\mid q_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 By relabeling necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\mid q_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In terms of ideals, this means 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle q_{1}\rangle\subseteq\langle p_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Since both 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle q_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 are both maximal ideals, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle q_{1}\rangle=\langle p_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=xp_{1}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =p_{1}-q_{1}q_{2}\cdots q_{n}\\
 & =p_{1}-xp_{1}q_{2}\cdots q_{n}\\
 & =p_{1}(1-xq_{2}\cdots q_{n}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Again 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 an integral domain implies 
\begin_inset Formula $xq_{2}\cdots q_{n}=1$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}\cdots q_{n}\in R^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction as each 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2},\dots,q_{n}$
\end_inset

 are irreducible! Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

, and clearly in this case, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\sim q_{1}$
\end_inset

 (as 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=q_{1}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $m>1$
\end_inset

 and we have shown that if 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 has an irreducible factorization of length 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k<$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, then it has a unique irreducible factorization.
 Again, let 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:irrfact})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 be two irreducible factorizations of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 where we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $m\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Arguing as above, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 is prime, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}\cdots q_{n}\in\langle p_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}\in\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 By rebaling if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}\in\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle q_{1}\rangle\subseteq\langle p_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

, and since both 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle q_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

 are maximal ideals, we must in fact have 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle q_{1}\rangle=\langle p_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=p_{1}x$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{m}-q_{1}q_{2}\cdots q_{n}\\
 & =p_{1}p_{2}\cdots p_{m}-p_{1}xq_{2}\cdots q_{n}\\
 & =p_{1}(p_{2}\cdots p_{m}-xq_{2}\cdots q_{n}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, this implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{2}\cdots p_{m}=xq_{2}\cdots q_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $xq_{2}$
\end_inset

 is an irreducible element, and thus we may apply induction step to get
 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n$
\end_inset

 and (perhaps after relabeling) 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}\sim q_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $2\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Since already we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\sim q_{1}$
\end_inset

, we are done.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Irreducibles are Prime in a Unique Factorization Domain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a unique factorization domain and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible element in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is not prime.
 Thus there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R\backslash\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are necessarily nonzero nonunits.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $xp=ab$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=q_{1}\cdots q_{k}\quad\text{and}\quad b=q_{k+1}\cdots q_{m}
\]

\end_inset

be the unique irreducible factorizations of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 respetively (here we have 
\begin_inset Formula $m>k$
\end_inset

).
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
xp=q_{1}\cdots q_{m}.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a unique factorization domain, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $p\sim q_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 By relabeling if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\sim q_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, since 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}\mid a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\sim q_{1}$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid a$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a Unique Factorization Domain, then 
\begin_inset Formula $R[T]$
\end_inset

 is a Unique Factorization Domain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this subsubsection, we will show that if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a unique factorization domain, then 
\begin_inset Formula $R[T]$
\end_inset

 is also a unique factorization domain (this is actually an if and only
 if statement, but the converse is clear, so we don't state that).
 We first note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a field, then 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

 is a unique factorization domain.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

 is a principal ideal domain, and thus a unique factorization domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a unique factorization domain.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R[T]$
\end_inset

 is a unique factorization domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a(T)$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero nonunit in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[T]$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be the fraction field of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 First note that 
\begin_inset Formula $R[T]$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a(T)$
\end_inset

 has an irreducible factorization.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{1}(T)\cdots p_{m}(T)=a(T)=q_{1}(T)\cdots q_{n}(T)
\]

\end_inset

are two irreducible factorizations of 
\begin_inset Formula $a(T)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[T]$
\end_inset

.
 By Gauss' Lemma, each 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}(T)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

 is a unique factorization domain, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n$
\end_inset

 and (perhaps after relabeling) 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(T)\sim q_{i}(T)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(T)=x_{i}q_{i}(T)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in K[T]^{\times}=K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that since 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(T),q_{i}(T)\in R[T]$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =p_{1}(T)\cdots p_{m}(T)-q_{1}(T)\cdots q_{m}(T)\\
 & =p_{1}(T)\cdots p_{m}(T)-x_{1}\cdots x_{m}p_{1}(T)\cdots p_{m}(T)\\
 & =p_{1}(T)\cdots p_{m}(T)(1-x_{1}\cdots x_{m})\\
 & =a(T)(1-x_{1}\cdots x_{m}),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and since 
\begin_inset Formula $a(T)\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R[T]$
\end_inset

 is a domain, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $1=x_{1}\cdots x_{n}$
\end_inset

, which implies each 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(T)\sim q_{i}(T)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[T]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Valuations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definitions Corresponding to Valuations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defnvaluationring}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Gamma,\geq)$
\end_inset

 be a totally ordered abelian group.
 We extend the ordering and group law on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 to the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\cup\{\infty\}$
\end_inset

 by the rules 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty\geq\gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty+\gamma=\infty=\gamma+\infty$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in\Gamma$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\series bold
valuation on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is a map 
\begin_inset Formula $v\colon K\to\Gamma\cup\{\infty\}$
\end_inset

 which satisfies the following properties for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in K$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $v(a)=\infty$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $v(ab)=v(a)+v(b)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $v(a+b)\geq\min(v(a),v(b))$
\end_inset

 with equality if 
\begin_inset Formula $v(a)\neq v(b)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The second property says that 
\begin_inset Formula $v|_{K^{\times}}$
\end_inset

 is a group homomorphism.
 One can interpret the valuation as the order of the leading-order term.
 Thus the third property corresponds to the order of a sum being the order
 of the larger term, unless the two terms have the same order, in which
 case they may cancel, in which case the sum may have smaller order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Usually we define a valuation on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 by first definining it on 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\times}$
\end_inset

 and showing that the second and third properties hold for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we may extend it to all of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $v(0)=\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we may write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

let 
\begin_inset Formula $v\colon K^{\times}\to\Gamma$
\end_inset

 be a valuation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with the understanding that 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is defined on all of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $v(0)=\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Also, when we write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

let 
\begin_inset Formula $v\colon K^{\times}\to\Gamma$
\end_inset

 be a valuation on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, then it is understood that 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is a totally ordered abelian group.
 There are several objects from a given valuation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $v\colon K^{\times}\to\Gamma$
\end_inset

 be a valuation on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
value group of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is the subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{v}=v(K^{\times})$
\end_inset

.
 Usually 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is surjective, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{v}=\Gamma$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
valuation ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is the subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{v}=\{a\in K\mid v(a)\geq0\}$
\end_inset

.
 To see that this is in fact a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $v(1)=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $v|_{K^{\times}}$
\end_inset

 is a group homomorphism, so 
\begin_inset Formula $1\in R_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Also if 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R_{v}$
\end_inset

, then properties 2 and 3 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Definition~(
\backslash
ref{defnvaluationring})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 shows 
\begin_inset Formula $a+b\in R_{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in R_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
maximal ideal associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is the maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{v}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{v}=\{a\in K\mid v(a)>0\}$
\end_inset

.
 To see that this is in fact a maximal ideal, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R_{v}\backslash\mathfrak{m}_{v}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $v(a)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =v(1)\\
 & =v(aa^{-1})\\
 & =v(a)+v(a^{-1})\\
 & =v(a^{-1}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}\in R_{v}$
\end_inset

, which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 Note that we've also shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{v}^{\times}=\{a\in K\mid v(a)=0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Also note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{v}$
\end_inset

 is the unique maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{v}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
residue field associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is the field 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{v}=R_{v}\slash\mathfrak{m}_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Equivalence of Valuations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}\colon K^{\times}\to\Gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}\colon K^{\times}\to\Gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

 be two valuations on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
equivalent 
\series default
to 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}\sim v_{2}$
\end_inset

, if there is an order preserving group isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\Gamma_{1}\to\Gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{2}(a)=\varphi(v_{1}(a))
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 It is straightforward to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is in fact an equivalence relation.
 Given a valuation 
\begin_inset Formula $v\colon K\to\Gamma$
\end_inset

, we shall denote its equivalence class by 
\begin_inset Formula $[v]$
\end_inset

.
 It is also straightforward to check that two valuations on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 are equivalent if and only if they have the same valuation ring.
 An equivalence class of valuations is called a 
\series bold
place
\series default
 
\series bold
of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Ostrowski's theorem gives a complete classification of places of the field
 of rational numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

: these are precisely the equivalence classes of valuations for the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic completions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Examples and Nonexamples of Valuations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}(X)$
\end_inset

 of rational polynomials over the complex numbers in the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose we define 
\begin_inset Formula $v\colon\mathbb{C}(X)^{\times}\to\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v(f/g)=\deg f-\deg g
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g\in\mathbb{C}(X)^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is well-defined and that it is a group homomorphism.
 However 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is not a valuation since otherwise we'd have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
-2 & =v\left(\frac{1}{1-X^{2}}\right)\\
 & =v\left(\frac{1}{1-X}+\frac{1}{1+X}\right)\\
 & \geq\min\left\{ v\left(\frac{1}{1-X}\right),v\left(\frac{1}{1+X}\right)\right\} \\
 & =\min\left\{ -1,-1\right\} \\
 & =-1,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

On the other hand, suppose we define 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\pi}\colon\mathbb{C}(X)^{\times}\to\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 as follows: if 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g\in\mathbb{C}(X)^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 then we can express it as 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g=\pi^{n}(\widetilde{f}/\widetilde{g})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is an irreducible polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}[X]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f},\widetilde{g}\in\mathbb{C}[X]\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is not a factor of neither 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 nor 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{g}$
\end_inset

, then we set 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\pi}(f/g)=n$
\end_inset

.
 Again one can check that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\pi}$
\end_inset

 is a well-defined group homomorphism.
 Additionally, it also satisfies the third criterion in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Definition~(
\backslash
ref{defnvaluationring})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\pi}$
\end_inset

 is a valuation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}(X)^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the field 
\begin_inset Formula $K((X))$
\end_inset

 of formal power series over a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K((X))=\left\{ \sum_{n>-\infty}^{\infty}a_{n}X^{n}\mid a_{n}\in K\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

Define 
\begin_inset Formula $v\colon K((X))^{\times}\to\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 as follows: given 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)\in K((X))^{\times}$
\end_inset

, express it as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(X)=\sum_{n=N}^{\infty}a_{n}X^{n}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{N}\neq0$
\end_inset

, and set 
\begin_inset Formula $v(f)=N$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is in fact a valuation.
 Indeed, the only nontrivial thing to check is that  
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Valuation Rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $v\colon K\to\Gamma$
\end_inset

 be a valuation on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to check that the valuation ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{v}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the following property that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

, either 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R_{v}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}\in R_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Integral domains which satisfy this property have a name:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain and let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 denote its fraction field.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
valuation ring 
\series default
if it satisfies the property that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

, either 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}\in A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{v}$
\end_inset

 is a valuation ring.
 In the next proposition, we show that there is a converse to this.
 Namely, any valuation ring is the valuation ring of a valuation! This is
 why we call such a ring a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

valuation ring
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propvaluationdomaincharacterization}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a domain and let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be its fraction field.
 The following conditions are equivalent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For all nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

, either 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid b$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b\mid a$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a valuation domain;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There is a valuation 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{x\in K\mid\pi(x)\geq0\}\cup\{0\}.$
\end_inset

 This valuation is called the 
\series bold
standard valuation 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (1
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

2): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a/b$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then either 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid b$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b\mid a$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $b\mid a$
\end_inset

, then we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $a=bc$
\end_inset

 for some nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in A$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x & =a/b\\
 & =bc/b\\
 & =c,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid b$
\end_inset

, then we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $b=ad$
\end_inset

 for some nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in A$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x^{-1} & =b/a\\
 & =ad/a\\
 & =d,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}\in A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

3): Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\times}\slash A^{\times}$
\end_inset

 is an abelian group.
 We can turn it into a totally ordered abelian group by defining a total
 ordering on 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\times}\slash A^{\times}$
\end_inset

 as follows: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x},\overline{y}\in K^{\times}\slash A^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we say
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{x}\geq\overline{y}\text{ if and only if }xy^{-1}\in A.\label{eq:welldefinedtotalordering}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Let us check that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedtotalordering})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well-defined.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $xa$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $yb$
\end_inset

 are two different representatives of the cosets 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}$
\end_inset

 respectively, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(xa)(yb)^{-1} & =(xa)(y^{-1}b^{-1})\\
 & =(xy^{-1})(ab^{-1})\\
 & \in A
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{xa}\geq\overline{yb}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedtotalordering})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well-defined.
 Next, observe that the relation given in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedtotalordering})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is antisymmetric: if 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}\geq\overline{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}\geq\overline{x}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $xy^{-1}\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $yx^{-1}\in A$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $xy^{-1}\in A^{\times}$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{x} & =\overline{x(yy^{-1})}\\
 & =\overline{(xy^{-1})y}\\
 & =\overline{y}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It is also transitive: if 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}\geq\overline{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}\geq\overline{z}$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
xz^{-1} & =x(y^{-1}y)z^{-1}\\
 & =(xy^{-1})(yz^{-1})\\
 & \in A
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}\geq\overline{z}$
\end_inset

).
 It is also a total relation since either 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}\geq\overline{y}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}\geq\overline{x}$
\end_inset

 (since either 
\begin_inset Formula $xy^{-1}\in A$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $yx^{-1}\in A$
\end_inset

).
 Thus 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedtotalordering})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us a total ordering on 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\times}\slash A^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon K^{\times}\to\Gamma$
\end_inset

 to be the natural quotient map.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is a surjective homomorphism.
 We also have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(x+y)\geq\min\{\pi(x),\pi(y)\}\text{ with equality if }\pi(x)\neq\pi(y).
\]

\end_inset

Indeed, assume without loss of generality that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(y)\geq\pi(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(x+y)x^{-1}=1+yx^{-1}\in A$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(x+y)\geq\pi(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Now assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(x)\neq\pi(y)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $yx^{-1}\not\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}(x+y)=1+yx^{-1}\notin A$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x(x+y)^{-1}\in A$
\end_inset

 (by 2).
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(x)\geq\pi(x+y)$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(x)=\pi(x+y)$
\end_inset

 by antisymmetry of 
\begin_inset Formula $\geq$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, we observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A^{\times}=\{x\in K\mid\pi(x)=0\}
\]

\end_inset

by construction.
 Moreover, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\{x\in K\mid\pi(x)\geq0\}\cup\{0\},
\]

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(x)\geq0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(x)\geq\pi(1)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

1): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Gamma,\geq)$
\end_inset

 be a totally ordered abelian group and let 
\begin_inset Formula $v\colon K^{\times}\to\Gamma$
\end_inset

 be such a valuation.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, and without loss of generality, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $v(b)\geq v(a)$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
v(ba^{-1}) & =v(b)-v(a)\\
 & \geq0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $ba^{-1}\in A$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid b$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $v\colon K^{\times}\to\Gamma$
\end_inset

 be a valuation on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is surjective so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma=\Gamma_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{v}$
\end_inset

 be the valuation ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon K^{\times}\to K^{\times}\slash R_{v}^{\times}$
\end_inset

 be the standard valuation of 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a valuation domain with fraction field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon K^{\times}\to K^{\times}\slash R^{\times}$
\end_inset

 be the standard valuation of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A=A_{\pi}=\{x\in K\mid\pi(x)\geq0\}\cup\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon K^{\times}\slash R_{v}^{\times}\to\Gamma$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(\overline{x})=v(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is well-defined since 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{v}^{\times}=\{a\in K\mid v(a)=0\}$
\end_inset

.
 It is straightforward to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an order preserving group isomoprhism which satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\pi=v$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 The converse statement was proved in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propvaluationdomaincharacterization})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Every Valuation Ring is Integrally Closed
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propvaluationringintclosed}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every Valuation Ring is Integrally Closed.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a valuation ring with fraction field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

 be integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha^{n}+a_{n-1}\alpha^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}=0
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0},\dots,a_{n-1}\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\notin A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{-1}\in A$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a valuation ring.
 Multiplying the equation above by 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{-(n-1)}\in A$
\end_inset

 and moving all but the first term on the LHS to the RHS yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha=-a_{n-1}-\cdots-a_{0}\alpha^{-n-1}\in A,
\]

\end_inset

contradicting our assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\notin A$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is integrally closed.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Discrete Valuation Rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
discrete valuation ring 
\series default
if it is a principal ideal domain that has a unique non-zero prime ideal
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 The field 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
residue field
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In a principal ideal domain, the non-zero prime ideals are the ideals of
 the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi A$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is an irreducible element.
 The definition above comes down to saying that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has one and only one irreducible element, up to multiplication by an invertible
 element; such an element is called a 
\series bold
uniformizing element 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (or 
\series bold
uniformizer
\series default
).
 The non-zero ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{n}A$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

 is any element of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, then one can write 
\begin_inset Formula $a=u\pi^{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 The integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
valuation 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(a)$
\end_inset

; it does not depend on the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be the field of fractions of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is any element of 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\times}$
\end_inset

, one can again write 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $u\pi^{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 this time, and set 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(\gamma)=n$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 gives rise to a valuation on 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
valuation 
\series default
on a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a group homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\times}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in K$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v(x+y)\geq\min(v(x),v(y)).
\]

\end_inset

We may extend 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 to a map 
\begin_inset Formula $K\to\mathbb{R}\cup\{\infty\}$
\end_inset

 by defining 
\begin_inset Formula $v(0):=\infty$
\end_inset

.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $0<c<1$
\end_inset

, defining
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|x|_{v}:=c^{v(x)}
\]

\end_inset

yields a nonarchimedean absolute value.
 The image of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
value group 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
discrete valuation 
\series default
if its value group is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 The set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A:=\{x\in K\mid v(x)\geq0\}
\]

\end_inset

is called the 
\series bold
valutation ring 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 (with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

).
 A 
\series bold
discrete valuation ring 
\series default
(DVR) is an integral domain that is the valuation ring of its fraction field
 with respect to a discrete valuation.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It is easy to verify that every valuation ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is in fact a ring, and even an integral domain (if 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are nonzero, then 
\begin_inset Formula $v(xy)=v(x)+v(y)\neq\infty$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $xy\neq0$
\end_inset

), with 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 as its fraction field.
 Notice that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $v(1/x)=v(1)-v(x)--v(x)$
\end_inset

, so at least one of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1/x$
\end_inset

 has nonnegative valuation and lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 is invertible (in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

) if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $v(x)=0$
\end_inset

, hence the unit group of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A^{\times}=\{x\in K\mid v(x)=0\}.
\]

\end_inset

We can partition the nonzero elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 according to the sign of their valuation.
 Elements with valuation zero are units in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, elements with positive valuation are nonunits in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and elements with negative valuation do not lie in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, but their multiplicative inverses are nonunits in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 This leads to a more general notion of a valuation ring:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
valuation ring 
\series default
is an integral domain 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with fraction field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 with the property that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

, either 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}\in A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us now suppose that the integral domain 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the valuation ring of its fraction field with respect to some discrete
 valuation 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 (which we shall see is uniquely determined).
 Any element 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\in A$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\pi)=1$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
uniformizer
\series default
.
 Uniformizers exist, since 
\begin_inset Formula $v(A)=\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

.
 If we fix a uniformizer 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, then every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

 can be written uniquely as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=u\pi^{n}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n=v(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u=x/\pi^{n}\in A^{\times}$
\end_inset

 and uniquely determined.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a unique factorization domain (UFD), and in fact 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a principal ideal domain (PID).
 Indeed, every nonzero ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is equal to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\pi^{n})=\{a\in A\mid v(a)\geq n\},
\]

\end_inset

for some integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Characterizations of Discrete Valuation Rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a discrete valuation ring if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a Noetherian local ring and its maximal ideal is generated by a non-nilpoten
t element.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It is clear that a discrete valuation ring has the stated properties.
 Conversely, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has these properties.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 be a generator of the maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 be the ideal of the ring formed by the elements 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\pi^{n}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 sufficiently large.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated.
 Thus there exists a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\pi^{N}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We will now show that the intersection of the powers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}^{n}$
\end_inset

 are zero (this is in fact true in any Noetherian local ring).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty}\mathfrak{m}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, write 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a_{n}\pi^{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\in A$
\end_inset

.
 We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 sufficiently large, which will imply 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =x-x\\
 & =a_{n}\pi^{n}-a_{n+1}\pi^{n+1}\\
 & =(a_{n}-a_{n+1}\pi)\pi^{n}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In particular we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}-\pi a_{n+1}\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathfrak{a}+Aa_{n})$
\end_inset

 of ideals is increasing.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathfrak{a}+Aa_{n})$
\end_inset

 must stabilize, say at 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}+Aa_{n}=\mathfrak{a}+Aa_{n+1}$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n+1}\in\mathfrak{a}+Aa_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n}-\pi a_{n+1}=y\quad\text{and}\quad a_{n+1}=z+aa_{n}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y,z\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Then note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(1-\pi a)a_{n+1} & =a_{n+1}-a\pi a_{n+1}\\
 & =z+aa_{n}-a(a_{n}-y)\\
 & =z+ay\\
 & \in\mathfrak{a}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\pi a$
\end_inset

 is a unit since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is local, thus it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n+1}\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 sufficiently large, and taking 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1\geq N$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\pi^{n+1}a_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 is zero, which proves
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty}\mathfrak{m}^{n}=0.
\]

\end_inset

By hypothesis none of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is zero.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a nonzero element of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 can therefore be written in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{n}u$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 invertible.
 This writing is clearly unique; it shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 Furthermore, if one sets 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\nu(a)$
\end_inset

, one checks easily that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 extends to a discrete valuation of the field of fractions of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 as its valuation ring.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian integral domain.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a discrete valuation ring if and only it is integrally closed and has
 a unique nonzero prime ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a discrete valuation ring.
 By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has a unique nonzero prime ideal.
 Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a valuation ring.
 All valuation rings are integrally closed by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propvaluationringintclosed})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we show the converse.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is integrally closed and has a unique nonzero prime ideal, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a local ring.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}=A:_{K}\mathfrak{m}=\{x\in K\mid x\mathfrak{m}\subseteq A\}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathfrak{m}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, then it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}\subset y^{-1}A$
\end_inset

, and as 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, this shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 is a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module (we call 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
fractional ideal 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

).
 Now observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and so must be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\subseteq A$
\end_inset

 we also have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\subseteq\mathfrak{m}\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{m}\subseteq\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}\mathfrak{m}\subseteq A.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is maximal, this means either 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}\mathfrak{m}=A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 First we will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 being integrally closed implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{\widetilde{m}}=A$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\mathfrak{m}\subset\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}_{n}$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,x,\dots,x^{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathfrak{a}_{n})$
\end_inset

 is an ascending sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-submodules of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}_{n}=\mathfrak{a}_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 large, so 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\in\mathfrak{a}_{n-1}$
\end_inset

.
 One can write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{n}=a_{0}+a_{1}x+\cdots+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}
\]

\end_inset

where each 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in A$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is integrally closed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Thus, assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 being integrally closed forces 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}=A$
\end_inset

.
 Now we will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 having a unique nonzero prime ideal will imply 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}\neq A$
\end_inset

, which will give us our desired contradiction.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

, and consider the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{x}$
\end_inset

 of fractions of the type 
\begin_inset Formula $a/x^{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has a unique nonzero prime ideal, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{x}=K$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{x}\neq K$
\end_inset

, then there would exist a nonzero prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{x}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{x}=A\cap\mathfrak{p}_{x}$
\end_inset

 would be a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 which would not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\mathfrak{p}_{x}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is unique.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Thus every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 can be written in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $a/x^{n}$
\end_inset

; let us apply this to 
\begin_inset Formula $1/b$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 We get 
\begin_inset Formula $1/b=a/x^{n}$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}=ab\in\langle b\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 has a power belonging to the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle b\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated, we can find an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 raised to the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle b\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 We choose 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 to be the smallest integer such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}^{N}\subseteq\langle b\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathfrak{m}^{N-1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\notin\langle b\rangle$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}y\subseteq\langle b\rangle$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $y/b\in\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y/z\notin A$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}\neq A$
\end_inset

, and we have our contradiction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}=A$
\end_inset

.
 We will now show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a principal ideal.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}=A$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}y_{i}=1
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\in\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 The products 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}y_{i}$
\end_inset

 all belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

; at least one of them, say 
\begin_inset Formula $xy$
\end_inset

, does not belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

, there is an invertible element 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 Replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $xu^{-1}$
\end_inset

, one obtains a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $xy=1$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $x(yz)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $yz\in A$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is indeed a principal ideal, generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propdedekinddef}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian integral domain.
 The following two properties are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is a discrete valuation ring for every nonzero prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is integrally closed and of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First let us show 1 implies 2.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is a discrete valuation ring for every nonzero prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p},\mathfrak{p}'$
\end_inset

 are prime ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\subset\mathfrak{p}'$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}'}$
\end_inset

 contains the prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}A_{\mathfrak{p}'}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular we must have either 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}A_{\mathfrak{p}'}=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}A_{\mathfrak{p}'}=\mathfrak{p}'A_{\mathfrak{p}'}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}'A_{\mathfrak{p}'}$
\end_inset

 is unique.
 This implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $0=\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=\mathfrak{p}'$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed if, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}A_{\mathfrak{p}'}=\mathfrak{p}'A_{\mathfrak{p}'}$
\end_inset

, then for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathfrak{p}'$
\end_inset

, we would have 
\begin_inset Formula $x/1=z/y$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\notin\mathfrak{p}'$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $xy=z$
\end_inset

 which would imply 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\dim A\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

On the other hand, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in K$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 for each prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 for all prime ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, write 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=a/b$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b:a=\{d\in A\mid da=bc\text{ for some }c\in A\}
\]

\end_inset

is not contained in any prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, since 
\begin_inset Formula $a/b\in A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $a/b=c/d$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $d\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, and clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in b:a$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $b:a=A$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a=bc$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in A$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=c\in A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we will show 2 implies 1.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is integrally closed and of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq1$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 has a unique nonzero prime ideal, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

, so it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is integrally closed.
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is integrally closed and of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 This follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propintegralclosureandlocalization})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A Noetherian integral domain which has the two equivalent properties of
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propdedekinddef})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
Dedekind domain
\series default
.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Dedekind domain.
 Then every nonzero fractional ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is invertible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 be a fractional ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\mathfrak{a}}=A:_{K}\mathfrak{a}=\{\gamma\in K\mid\gamma\mathfrak{a}\subseteq A\}.
\]

\end_inset

Then observe that for each prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\widetilde{\mathfrak{a}}\mathfrak{a})_{\mathfrak{p}} & =\widetilde{\mathfrak{a}}_{\mathfrak{p}}\mathfrak{a}_{\mathfrak{p}}\\
 & =(A_{\mathfrak{p}}:_{K}\mathfrak{a}_{\mathfrak{p}})\mathfrak{a}_{\mathfrak{p}}\\
 & =A_{\mathfrak{p}},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is invertible in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathfrak{a}}\mathfrak{a}=A$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is invertible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Domination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field.
 We define a preordered set 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{D}_{K},\geq_{\mathrm{d}})$
\end_inset

 as follows: the underlying set is defined to be
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{D}_{K}:=\{A\mid A\text{ is a local domain such that }A\subseteq K\}.
\]

\end_inset

The preorder 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq_{\mathrm{d}}$
\end_inset

 is defined as follows: let 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\in\mathcal{D}_{K}$
\end_inset

.
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula $B\geq_{\mathrm{d}}A$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $B\supseteq A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{A}=A\cap\mathfrak{m}_{B}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we also say 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
dominates 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

More generally, if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 (so necessarily a domain), then we define a preordered set 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{D}_{K\slash R},\geq_{\mathrm{d}})$
\end_inset

 as follows: the underlying set is defined to be
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{D}_{K\slash R}:=\{A\mid A\text{ is a local domain such that }R\subseteq A\subseteq K\}.
\]

\end_inset

The preorder 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq_{\mathrm{d}}$
\end_inset

 is defined as above.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{D}_{K\slash R}$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
centered 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{D}_{K}$
\end_inset

.
 A maximal element in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{D}_{K\slash A},\geq_{\mathrm{d}})$
\end_inset

 exists.
 Furthemore, any such maximal element is a valuation ring with 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 as its fraction field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We appeal to Zorn's Lemma.
 First note that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{D}_{K\slash A},\geq_{\mathrm{d}})$
\end_inset

 is nonempty since 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in(\mathcal{D}_{K\slash A},\geq_{\mathrm{d}})$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(A_{\lambda})_{\lambda\in\Lambda}$
\end_inset

 be a totally ordered collection of local subrings of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}\geq_{\mathrm{d}}A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\geq\lambda$
\end_inset

, which means 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}\supseteq A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\lambda}=A_{\lambda}\cap\mathfrak{m}_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\geq\lambda$
\end_inset

).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is a local subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 which dominates all of the 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, it is straightforward to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{m}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 To see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{m}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is the unique maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

, we will show that its complement consists of units.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{m}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

, there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{m}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\mathfrak{m}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $(A_{\lambda},\mathfrak{m}_{\lambda})$
\end_inset

 is a local ring.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\lambda}\subseteq\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{m}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is the unique maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus every totally ordered subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{D}_{K\slash A},\geq_{\mathrm{d}})$
\end_inset

 has an upper bound.
 It follows from Zorn's Lemma that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{D}_{K\slash A},\geq_{\mathrm{d}})$
\end_inset

 has a maximal element.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we prove the latter part of the proposition.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(B,\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

 be a maximal element in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{D}_{K\slash A},\geq_{\mathrm{d}})$
\end_inset

.
 First we show 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 as its fraction field.
 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is not the fraction field of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

 which is not in the fraction field of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is transcendental over 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $B[x]_{(x,\mathfrak{m})}\in(\mathcal{D}_{K\slash A},\geq_{\mathrm{d}})$
\end_inset

, which contradicts maximality of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, then for some 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

, the element 
\begin_inset Formula $bx$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, the subring 
\begin_inset Formula $B'\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $bx$
\end_inset

 is finite over 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, there exists a prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}'\subseteq B'$
\end_inset

 lying over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $B'_{\mathfrak{m}'}$
\end_inset

 dominates 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $B=B'_{\mathfrak{m}'}$
\end_inset

 by maximality of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, and then 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is in the fraction field of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally, we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is a valuation ring.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

 and assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin B$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

 denote the subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is maximal in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{D}_{K\slash A},\geq_{\mathrm{d}})$
\end_inset

, there is no prime of 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

 lying over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is maximal we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{m}B')=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}B'=B'$
\end_inset

, hence we can write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=\sum_{i=0}^{d}t_{i}x^{i}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1-t_{0})(x^{-1})^{d}-\sum t_{i}(x^{-1})^{d-i}=0.
\]

\end_inset

In particular we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the subring 
\begin_inset Formula $B''$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is finite over 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and we see that there exists a prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}''\subseteq B''$
\end_inset

 lying over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 By maximality of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $B=(B'')_{\mathfrak{m}''}$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}\in B$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Absolute Values
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An 
\series bold
absolute value 
\series default
on a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a map 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|\colon K\to\mathbb{R}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in K$
\end_inset

 the following hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $|x|=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $|xy|=|x||y|$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $|x+y|\leq|x|+|y|$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the stronger condition 
\begin_inset Formula $|x+y|\leq\text{max}(|x|,|y|)$
\end_inset

 also holds, then the absolute value is 
\series bold
nonarchimedean
\series default
; otherwise it is 
\series bold
archimedean
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The second property tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|_{|K^{\times}}$
\end_inset

 is a group homomorphism.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

 is a root of unity, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $|\zeta|=1$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(x,y)=|x-y|$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 the structure of a metric space, and the resulting topology is the discrete
 topology if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 We shall call 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
trivial 
\series default
absolute value if 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 The usual absolute value on the set of real numbers is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|_{\mathbb{R}}$
\end_inset

.
 We denote
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{B}_{\varepsilon}^{|\cdot|}(x)=\{y\in K\mid|x-y|<\varepsilon\}
\]

\end_inset

to be the open ball of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with respect to the metric induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

.
 If the absolute value is clear from context, then we supress 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 and the subscript and just write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{\varepsilon}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, we denote
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{B}_{\varepsilon}^{|\cdot|}[x]=\{y\in K\mid|x-y|\leq\varepsilon\}
\]

\end_inset

to be the closed ball of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with respect to the metric induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

.
 It is straightforward to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{\varepsilon}^{|\cdot|}[x]$
\end_inset

 is the closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{\varepsilon}^{|\cdot|}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Topological Equivalence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 be an absolute value on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in(0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|^{e}$
\end_inset

 is another absolute value on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|^{e}$
\end_inset

 induce the same topology.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|^{e}=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 Also for 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in K$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|xy|^{e} & =(|x||y|)^{e}\\
 & =|x|^{e}|y|^{e},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and similarly
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|x+y|^{e} & \leq(|x|+|y|)^{e}\\
 & \leq|x|^{e}+|y|^{e},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we needed to use the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $-^{e}$
\end_inset

 is monotone increasing to the get the first inequality and where we needed
 to use the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $0<e\leq1$
\end_inset

 to get the second inequality.
 To see that they induce the same topology, observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{B}_{\varepsilon}^{|\cdot|}(x) & =\{y\in K\mid|x-y|<\varepsilon\}\\
 & =\{y\in K\mid|x-y|^{e}<\varepsilon^{e}\}\\
 & =\mathrm{B}_{\varepsilon^{e}}^{|\cdot|^{e}}(x).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It is straightforward to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|_{\mathbb{R}}^{e}$
\end_inset

 does not satisfy the triangle inequality whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $e>1$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, we shall see many examples of non-trivial absolute values
 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|^{e}$
\end_inset

 is an absolute value for all 
\begin_inset Formula $e>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremequivalentabs}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|'$
\end_inset

 be two absolute values on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 that induce the same topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $e>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|'=|\cdot|^{e}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since the trivial absolute value is the unique one giving rise to the discrete
 topology, we may assume that the topology is non-discrete and hence that
 both absolute values are non-trivial.
 Pick 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $0<|c|<1$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $(c^{n})$
\end_inset

 converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 with respect to the common topology, so 
\begin_inset Formula $|c^{n}|'\to0$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $0<|c|'<1$
\end_inset

.
 There is a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $e>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|c|'=|c|^{e}$
\end_inset

.
 By switching the roles of 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|'$
\end_inset

 and replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $1/e$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $0<e\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|^{e}$
\end_inset

 is an absolute value and our goal is to prove that it is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|^{e}$
\end_inset

 defines the same topology as 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

, we may replace 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|^{e}$
\end_inset

 to reduce to the case 
\begin_inset Formula $e=1$
\end_inset

.
 That is, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $0<|c|=|c|'<1$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Under this condition, we want to prove 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|=|x|'$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

, and we may certainly restrict attention to 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|'\neq|x|$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 By replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $1/x$
\end_inset

 if neccessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|<|x|'\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 We can find an 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0<|x^{m}|<|c^{n}|=|c^{n}|'<|x^{m}|'\leq1.
\]

\end_inset

By replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{n}$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1<|x|<|c|=|c|'<|x|'\leq1.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $|x/c|<1<|x/c|'$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $((x/c)^{n})$
\end_inset

 converges to zero with respect to the metric topology of 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 but not with respect to the metric topology of 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|'$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction since the two topologies are assumed to coincide.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Non-Archimedean Absolute Values
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An absolute value 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 on a field is 
\series bold
non-archimedean 
\series default
if its restriction to the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is bounded, and otherwise (that is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is unbounded for the metric structure) we say 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
archimedean
\series default
.
 The non-archimedean property is inherited by any absolute value of the
 form 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|^{e}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $e>0$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremequivalentabs})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 implies that this condition is intrinsic to the underlying topology associated
 to the absolute value.
 Obviously the trivial absolute value is non-archimedean, and any absolute
 value on a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 with positive characteristic must be non-archimedean (as the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 consists of 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and the set 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{p}^{\times}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(p-1$
\end_inset

)th roots of unity in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

).
 Of course, the usual absolute value on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is archimedean.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The 
\series bold
non-archimedean triangle inequality 
\series default
(also called the 
\series bold
ultrametric triangle inequality
\series default
) is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|x+y|\leq\max(|x|,|y|).
\]

\end_inset

This is clearly much stronger than the usual triangle inequality, and it
 forces 
\begin_inset Formula $|k|\leq1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 is forced to be non-archimedean in such cases.
 Interestingly, the stronger form of the triangle inequality is also necessary
 fo 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 to be non-archimedean, and so the following theorem is often taken as the
 definition of a non-archimedean absolute value.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An absolute value 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 on a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is non-archimedean if and only if it satisfies the non-archimedean triangle
 inequality.
 In particular, any absolute value on a field with positive characteristic
 must satisfy the non-archimedean triangle inequality.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The sufficiency has already been noted, so the only issue is necessity.
 Consider the binomial theorem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x+y)^{n}=\sum_{j=0}^{n}{n \choose j}x^{n-j}y^{j}
\]

\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Applying the absolute value to both sides and using the hypothesis that
 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 is bounded on the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, say with 
\begin_inset Formula $|k|\leq C$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|x+y|^{n} & \leq\sum_{j=0}^{n}C|x|^{n-j}|y|\\
 & \leq(n+1)C\max(|x|,|y|)^{n}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Extracting the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th roots gives 
\begin_inset Formula $|x+y|\leq((n+1)C)^{1/n}\max(|x|,|y|)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

 clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $((n+1)C)^{1/n}\to1$
\end_inset

, so we obtain the non-archimedean triangle inequality.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 is a non-archimedean absolute value on a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, then so is 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|^{e}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $e>0$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|^{e}$
\end_inset

 is an absolute value for all 
\begin_inset Formula $e>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By the theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $|x+y|\leq\max(|x|,|y|)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Raising both sides to the 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

th power gives the same for 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|^{e}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $e>0$
\end_inset

, so in particular 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|^{e}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the triangle inequality.
 The rest follows immediately.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Here is an important refinement of the non-archimedean triangle inequality.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 is non-archimedean.
 We claim that the inequality 
\begin_inset Formula $|x+y|\leq\max(|x|,|y|)$
\end_inset

 is an equality if 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|\neq|y|$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|<|y|$
\end_inset

.
 We then want to prove 
\begin_inset Formula $|x+y|=|y|$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose not, so 
\begin_inset Formula $|x+y|<|y|$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|,|x+y|<|y|$
\end_inset

, so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|y| & =|(y+x)-x|\\
 & \leq\max(|y+x|,|-x|)\\
 & =\max(|x+y|,|y|)\\
 & <|y|,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

a contradiction.
 This has drastic consequences for the topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a,a'\in K$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $|a-a'|\leq r$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $|x-a|\leq r$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $|x-a'|\leq r$
\end_inset

.
 Hence any point in the disc 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}[a]$
\end_inset

 serves as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

center
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 More drastically, whereas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}[a]$
\end_inset

 is a trivially closed set in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, it is in fact also open! Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $|x_{0}-a|\leq r$
\end_inset

 then the non-archimedean triangle inequality implies that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|x-x_{0}|<r\implies|x-a|\leq r.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}[a]$
\end_inset

 contains an open disc around any of its points.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is totally disconnected.
 That is, its only non-empty connected subsets are one-point sets.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Noetherian Rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propequivalentdefnoetherian}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
 The following conditions are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every ascending chain of ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 stabilizes: if 
\begin_inset Formula $(I_{n})$
\end_inset

 is ascending chain of ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}\subseteq I_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{N}=I_{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose every chain of ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 stabilizes and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is not finitely generated.
 Choose any 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is not finitely generated, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle x_{1}\rangle\subset I
\]

\end_inset

where the inclusion is proper.
 Next we choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}\in I\backslash\langle x_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Again, since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is not finitely generated, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle x_{1}\rangle\subset\langle x_{1},x_{2}\rangle\subset I
\]

\end_inset

where each inclusion is proper.
 Proceeding inductively on 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq3$
\end_inset

, we choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\in I\backslash\langle x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is not finitely generated, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle x_{1}\rangle\subset\langle x_{1},x_{2}\rangle\subset\cdots\subset\langle x_{1},x_{2},\dots,x_{n}\rangle\subset I
\]

\end_inset

where each inclusion is proper.
 Continuing in this manner, we construct an ascending chain of ideals 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\langle x_{1},x_{2}\dots,x_{n}\rangle)_{n\in\mathbb{N}}
\]

\end_inset

which never stabilizes since 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x_{1},x_{2},\dots,x_{n}\rangle$
\end_inset

 is properly contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x_{1},x_{2},\dots,x_{n},x_{n+1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 This contradicts the hypothesis that every chain of ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 stabilizes.
 Thus every ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now let us show the converse.
 Suppose every ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(I_{n})$
\end_inset

 be an ascending chain of ideals.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}I_{n}$
\end_inset

 is an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $(I_{n})$
\end_inset

 is totally ordered, thus it must be finitely generated, say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}I_{n}=\langle x_{1},\dots,x_{m}\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in I_{n_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\max_{1\leq i\leq m}\{n_{i}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in I_{N}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $(I_{n})$
\end_inset

 is totally ordered.
 It follows that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
I_{N} & \subseteq I_{n}\\
 & \subseteq\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}I_{n}\\
 & =\langle x_{1},\dots,x_{m}\rangle\\
 & \subseteq I_{N}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In particular we have 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{N}=I_{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

.
 Thus every chain of ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 stabilizes.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 satisfies any of the equivalent definitions in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{propequivalentdefnoetherian})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
Noetherian
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Hilbert Basis Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R[X]$
\end_inset

 is a Noetherian ring.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[X]$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}=\{f\in I\mid\deg f=n\}$
\end_inset

 and we define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{a}_{n}=\{a_{n}\in R\mid a_{n}=\mathrm{LT}(f)\text{ for some }f\in I_{n}\}\cup\{0\}.
\]

\end_inset

 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\in\mathfrak{a}_{n}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 if there exists a polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in I$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 whose lead term in 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}_{n}$
\end_inset

 is an ideal.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n},b_{n}\in\mathfrak{a}_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

, then if we choose 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in I_{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=\mathrm{LT}(f)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}=\mathrm{LT}(g)$
\end_inset

, then we see that either 
\begin_inset Formula $aa_{n}+bb_{n}=0$
\end_inset

 or
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
aa_{n}+bb_{n} & =\mathrm{LT}(af+bg),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $aa_{n}+bb_{n}\in\mathfrak{a}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Also note that the sequence of ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathfrak{a}_{n})$
\end_inset

 is ascending.
 This is because if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\in\mathfrak{a}_{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=\mathrm{LT}(f)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in I_{n}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=\mathrm{LT}(xf)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $xf\in I_{n+1}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\in\mathfrak{a}_{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, the ascending chain 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathfrak{a}_{n})$
\end_inset

 of ideals must stabilize, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}_{n}=\mathfrak{a}_{N}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Also since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}_{N}$
\end_inset

 must be finitely generated, say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{a}_{N}=\langle a_{N,1},a_{N,2},\dots,a_{N,s}\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{s}\in I_{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{LT}(f_{r})=a_{N,r}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq r\leq s$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I=\langle1,x,,\dots,x^{N},f_{1},\dots,f_{s}\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

To see this, let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in I$
\end_inset

.
 We will prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $1,x,\dots,x^{N},f_{1},\dots,f_{s}$
\end_inset

 using induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg g$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly if 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg g\leq N$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $1,x,\dots,x^{N}$
\end_inset

.
 This establishes the base case.
 Now denote 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\deg g$
\end_inset

 and assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $n>N$
\end_inset

 and that we can express polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in I$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $<n$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $1,x,\dots,x^{N},f_{1},\dots,f_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(x)=a_{n}x^{n}+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\in\mathfrak{a}_{n}=\mathfrak{a}_{N}$
\end_inset

, we can express it as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n}=c_{1}a_{N,1}+c_{2}a_{N,2}+\cdots+c_{s}a_{N,s}
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2},\dots,c_{s}\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Now we set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h=g-c_{1}f_{1}-c_{2}f_{2}-\cdots-c_{s}f_{s}.
\]

\end_inset

Then note that 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg h<n$
\end_inset

.
 By the induction hypothesis, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\langle1,x,,\dots,x^{N},f_{1},\dots,f_{s}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 However this also implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\langle1,x,,\dots,x^{N},f_{1},\dots,f_{s}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Definition of a Field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
field 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a commutative ring with identity such that every nonzero element in
 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In particular, a field is an integral domain.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in K$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =a^{-1}\cdot0\\
 & =a^{-1}ab\\
 & =b.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 In fact, any finite integral domain is automatically a field:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Finite Rings are Integral Domains if and only if they are Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a finite ring.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 One direction is clear, for the other direction, let 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero element in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, the multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{m}_{a}\colon R\to R$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{m}_{a}(b)=ab
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in R$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is finite and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{m}_{a}$
\end_inset

 is injective, the multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 map must also be surjective.
 Thus there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in R$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
1 & =\mathrm{m}_{a}(b)\\
 & =ab.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Integral Domains with Positive Characteristic must have Prime Characteristic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propintdomposcharprime}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{char}\,R>0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{char}\,R$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us denote 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\mathrm{char}\,R$
\end_inset

.
 We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is a prime.
 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is not a prime.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $1<k,m<n$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =n\cdot1_{R}\\
 & =(km)\cdot1_{R}\\
 & =(k\cdot1_{R})(m\cdot1_{R}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\mathrm{char}\,R$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $(k\cdot1_{R})\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(m\cdot1_{R})\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 But this contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{corcharoffinfieldisprime}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every finite field has prime characteristic.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every finite ring has positive characteristic and every field is an integral
 domain.
 Thus the corollary follows immediately from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{propintdomposcharprime})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Finite Subgroup of Multiplicative Group of Field is Cyclic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmaeveryorderdividesmaximal}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a finite abelian group.
 Then the order of every element must divide the maximal order.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 From the fundamental theorem of finite abelian groups, we have an isomorphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\cong\mathbb{Z}_{k_{1}}\oplus\cdots\oplus\mathbb{Z}_{k_{n}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}\mid\cdots\mid k_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},\dots,e_{n}$
\end_inset

 denote the standard 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}^{n}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{e}_{i}$
\end_inset

 denote the corresponding coset in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{k_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{i}\mid k_{n}$
\end_inset

 we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}$
\end_inset

 kills each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{k_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}$
\end_inset

 kills all of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, the order of every element must divide 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}$
\end_inset

, which is in fact the maximal order as 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}=\mathrm{ord}(\overline{e}_{i_{n}})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmaatmostnroots}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The number of roots of a polynomial over a field is at most the degree
 of the polynomial.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 By replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 with a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 splits into linear factors over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(T)=(T-\alpha_{1})\cdots(T-\alpha_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1},\dots\alpha_{n}\in K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\deg f(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(\alpha)=0 & \iff(\alpha-\alpha_{1})\cdots(\alpha-\alpha_{n})=0\\
 & \iff\alpha-\alpha_{i}=0\text{ for some }i\\
 & \iff\alpha=\alpha_{i}\text{ for some }i,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we obtained the second line from the first line from the fact that
 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 has 
\emph on
at most 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 roots.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propfinitesubgroupofmultgroupoffieldiscyclic}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a finite subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is cyclic.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n=|G|$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 be the maximal order among all elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n$
\end_inset

.
 By Lagrange's Theorem, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $m\mid n$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $m\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaeveryorderdividesmaximal})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that every order of every element must divide the maximal order.
 In particular, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{m}=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in G$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore all numbers in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 are roots of the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{m}-1$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaatmostnroots})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, the number of roots of a polynomial over a field is at most the degree
 of the polynomial, so 
\begin_inset Formula $n\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Combining both inequalities gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Finite Fields have Prime Power Order
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremfinitefieldshaveprimepowerorder}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a finite field.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 has prime power order.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a finite field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Corollary~(
\backslash
ref{corcharoffinfieldisprime})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 tells us that the characteristic of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is prime, denote it by 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\mathrm{char}\,F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\slash(p)$
\end_inset

 embeds as a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we can view 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 as a finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\slash(p)$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\dim_{\mathbb{Z}\slash(p)}(F)$
\end_inset

 and picking a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\slash(p)$
\end_inset

, elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 can be written uniquely as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}e_{1}+\cdots+c_{n}e_{n}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}\in\mathbb{Z}(p)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Each coefficient has 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 choices, so 
\begin_inset Formula $|F|=p^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Classification of Finite Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every finite field is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

 for some prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and some monic irreducible 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a finite field.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremfinitefieldshaveprimepowerorder})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 has order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 for some prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and there is a field embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}\hookrightarrow F$
\end_inset

.
 The group 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{\times}$
\end_inset

 is cyclic by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propfinitesubgroupofmultgroupoffieldiscyclic})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 be a generator of 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Evaluation at 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)\mapsto f(\gamma)$
\end_inset

, is a ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{ev}_{\gamma}\colon\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\to F$
\end_inset

 that fixes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Since every number in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 or a power of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{ev}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is onto (
\begin_inset Formula $0=\mathrm{ev}_{\gamma}(0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{r}=\mathrm{ev}_{\gamma}(X^{r})$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $r\geq0$
\end_inset

).
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash\ker\mathrm{ev}_{\gamma}\cong F.
\]

\end_inset

The kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{ev}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

, so it must be 
\begin_inset Formula $(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

 for some monic irreducible 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Polynomials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Roots and Irreducibles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 A number 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{proprootdivide}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 be a nonconstant polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $X-\alpha$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X-\alpha$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(X)=(X-\alpha)g(X)\label{eq:root}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)\in K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 in both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:root})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 is Euclidean domain and 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg f(X)\geq1$
\end_inset

, there exists nonzero a nonzero polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $q(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 and a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(X)=(X-\alpha)q(X)+r\label{euclideandivroot}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 in both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{euclideandivroot})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)=(X-\alpha)q(X)$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $X-\alpha$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For most fields 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, there are polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 without a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 (for instance consider 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[X]$
\end_inset

).
 If we are willing to enlarge the field, then we can discover some roots.
 This is due to Kronecker, by the following argument.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremrootinlargerfield}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 be nonconstant in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 There is a field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 containing a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Choose an irreducible polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\mid f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is an extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

 too.
 Therefore it suffices to find a field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 has a root.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $L=K[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 Inside of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 as a subfield: the congruence classes represented by constants.
 There is a also a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, namely the class of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}$
\end_inset

 for the congruence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, the congruence 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\equiv0\text{ mod }\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 becomes the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\overline{X})=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

By repeating the construction in the proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremrootinlargerfield})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 several times, we can always create a field with a full set of roots for
 our polynomial.
 We state this as a corollary, and give a proof by induction on the degree.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)=c_{m}X^{m}+\cdots+c_{0}$
\end_inset

 be in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 with degree 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 There is a field 
\begin_inset Formula $L\supset K$
\end_inset

 such that in 
\begin_inset Formula $L[X]$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(X)=c_{m}(X-\alpha_{1})\cdots(X-\alpha_{m}).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We induct on the degree 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 The case 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

 is clear, using 
\begin_inset Formula $L=K$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremrootinlargerfield})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, there is a field 
\begin_inset Formula $L\supset K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then in 
\begin_inset Formula $L[X]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(X)=(X-\alpha_{1})g(X),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg g(X)=m-1$
\end_inset

.
 The leading coefficient of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

 is also 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

 has smaller degree than 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

, by induction on the degree there is a field 
\begin_inset Formula $E\supset L$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

 decomposes into linear factors in 
\begin_inset Formula $E[X]$
\end_inset

, so we get the desired factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $E[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{correlprimecommonroot}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

 be nonconstant in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 They are relatively prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 if and only if they do not have a common root in any extension field of
 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(X)u(X)+g(X)v(X)=1\label{relprime1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $u(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 If there were an 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in a field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 which is a common root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

, then substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{relprime1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 makes the left side 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 while the right side 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

 have no common root in any field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now assume 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

 are not relatively prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Say 
\begin_inset Formula $h(X)\in K[X]$
\end_inset

 is a (nonconstant) common factor.
 There is a field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $h(X)$
\end_inset

 has a root, and this root will be a common root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Although adjoining one root of an irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

 to the rational numbers does not always produce the other roots in the
 same field (such as with 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{3}-2$
\end_inset

), the situation in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 is much simpler.
 We will see later that for an irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

, a larger field which contains one root must contain 
\emph on
all 
\emph default
the roots.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Divisibility and Roots in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It turns out that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{proprootdivide})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 can be improved as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 be irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 be a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 in some larger field, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(X)=\pi(X)g(X)\label{eq:root-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)\in K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 in both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:root-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 have a common root, so by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Corollary~(
\backslash
ref{correlprimecommonroot})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 they have a common factor in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible, this means 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Take 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)=X^{2}-2$
\end_inset

.
 It has a root 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $h(X)\in\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $h(\sqrt{2})=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $(X^{2}-2)\mid h(X)$
\end_inset

.
 This equivalence breaks down if we allow 
\begin_inset Formula $h(X)$
\end_inset

 to come from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[X]$
\end_inset

: try 
\begin_inset Formula $h(X)=X-\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremdivisioniniffdivisioninL}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be a field extension and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

 be in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)\mid g(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)\mid g(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It is clear the divisibility in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 implies divisibility in the larger 
\begin_inset Formula $L[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)\mid g(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(X)=f(X)h(X)
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $h(X)\in L[X]$
\end_inset

.
 By the division algorithm in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(X)=f(X)q(X)+r(X),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r(X)$
\end_inset

 are in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r(X)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg r<\deg f$
\end_inset

.
 Comparing these two formulas for 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

, the uniqueness of the division algorithm in 
\begin_inset Formula $L[X]$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $q(X)=h(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r(X)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)=f(X)q(X)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)\mid g(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Raising to the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th Power in Characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{injectiveintdomainfin}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring with prime characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Pick any 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(a+b)^{p}=a^{p}+b^{p}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
When 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a domain, 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{p}=b^{p}$
\end_inset

 implies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

1.
 By the binomial theorem,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(a+b)^{p}=a^{p}+\sum_{k=1}^{p-1}{p \choose k}a^{p-k}b^{k}+b^{p}.
\]

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k\leq p-1$
\end_inset

, the integer 
\begin_inset Formula ${p \choose k}$
\end_inset

 is a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, so the intermediate terms are 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a domain and 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{p}=b^{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $0=a^{p}-b^{p}=(a-b)^{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a domain, 
\begin_inset Formula $a-b=0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $a=b$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmafixedfieldfrob}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field containing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in F$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{p}=c$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every element 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{p}=c$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, solutions to this equation are roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p}-X$
\end_inset

, which has at most 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 roots in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 The elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 already fulfill this upper bound, so there are no further roots in characterist
ic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)\in\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)^{p^{r}}=f(X^{p^{r}})$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $r\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a field of characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 other than 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

, this is not always true in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Writing
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(X)=c_{m}X^{m}+c_{m-1}X^{m-1}+\cdots+c_{0},
\]

\end_inset

we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(X)^{p} & =(c_{m}X^{m}+c_{m-1}X^{m-1}+\cdots+c_{0})^{p}\\
 & =c_{m}^{p}X^{pm}+c_{m-1}^{p}X^{p(m-1)}+\cdots+c_{0}^{p}\\
 & =c_{m}X^{pm}+c_{m-1}X^{p(m-1)}+\cdots+c_{0}\\
 & =f(X^{p})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{p}=c$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Applying this 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 times gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)^{p^{r}}=f(X^{p^{r}})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and is not 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 contains an element 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 which is not in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{p}\neq c$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmafixedfieldfrob})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, so the constant polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)=c$
\end_inset

 does not satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)^{p}=f(X^{p})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)\in\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 be nonconstant, with degree 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\supseteq\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 be a field over which 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 decomposes into linear factors.
 It is possible that some of the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 are multiple roots.
 As long as that does not happen, the following corollary says something
 about the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th power of the roots.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 When 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)\in\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 has distinct roots, raising all roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 to the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th power permutes the roots:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{\alpha_{1}^{p},\dots,\alpha_{m}^{p}\}=\{\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{m}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\{\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{m}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X^{p})=f(X)^{p}$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th power of each root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is again a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore raising to the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th power defines a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon S\to S$
\end_inset

.
 This function is injective since the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th power map is injective, which implies the function is surjective since
 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Roots of Irreducibles in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All the roots of an irreducible polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

 are not generally expressible in terms of a particular root, with 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{3}-2$
\end_inset

 being a typical example.
 (The field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt[3]{2})$
\end_inset

 contains only one root to this polynomial, not all 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 roots.) However, the situation is markedly simpler over finite fields.
 In this section we will make explicit the relations among the roots of
 an irreducible polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 In short, we can obtain all roots from any one root by repeatedly taking
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th powers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 be a monic irreducible polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Then the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a field of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The cosets mod 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 are represented by remainders
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{0}+c_{1}X+\cdots+c_{n-1}X^{n-1},\qquad c_{i}\in\mathbb{F}_{p}
\]

\end_inset

and there are 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 of these.
 Since the modulus 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible, the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremirreduciblefinfieldpower}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 be irreducible of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\mid(X^{p^{d}}-X)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\mid(X^{p^{n}}-X)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This divisibility in 1 is the same as the congruence 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{d}}\equiv X\mod\pi(X)$
\end_inset

, or equivalently the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}^{p^{d}}=\overline{X}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

.
 Such an equation follows immediately from the Lemmas above, using the field
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To prove 
\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 in 2, write 
\begin_inset Formula $n=kd$
\end_inset

.
 Starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $X\equiv X^{p^{d}}\,\mod\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 and applying the 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}$
\end_inset

th power to both sides 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 times, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
X & \equiv X^{p^{d}}\mod\pi(X)\\
 & \equiv X^{p^{2d}}\mod\pi(X)\\
 & \vdots\\
 & \equiv X^{p^{kd}}\mod\pi(X)\\
 & =X^{p^{n}}\mod\pi(X).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\mid(X^{p^{n}}-X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we prove 
\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 in 2.
 We assume 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X^{p^{n}}\equiv X\mod\pi(X)
\]

\end_inset

and we want to show 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid n$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $n=dq+r$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq r<d$
\end_inset

.
 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
X & \equiv X^{p^{n}}\mod\pi(X)\\
 & \equiv(X^{p^{dq}})^{p^{r}}\mod\pi(X)\\
 & \equiv X^{p^{r}}\mod\pi(X)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This tells us that one particular element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

, the class of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, is equal to its own 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}$
\end_inset

th power.
 More generally, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)\in\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(X)^{p^{r}} & \equiv f(X^{p^{r}})\mod\pi(X)\\
 & \equiv f(X)\mod\pi(X).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

 the congruence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is equal to its own 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}$
\end_inset

th power.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is a general polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

, we have proved every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

 is its own 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}$
\end_inset

th power (in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider now the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{p^{r}}-T$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

, this is a polynomial with degree 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}>1$
\end_inset

, and we have found 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}$
\end_inset

 different roots of this polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

 (namely, every element of this field is a root).
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}\leq p^{r}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $d\leq r$
\end_inset

.
 But, recalling where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 came from, 
\begin_inset Formula $r<d$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction, so 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
 This proves 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorempixcontainsallroots}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 be irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 with degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F\supseteq\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 be a field which 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 has a root, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 has roots 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\alpha^{p},\alpha^{p^{2}},\dots,\alpha^{p^{d-1}}$
\end_inset

.
 These 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 roots are distinct; more precisely, when 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 are nonnegative, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{i}}=\alpha^{p^{j}}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $i\equiv j\mod d$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)^{p}=\pi(X^{p})$
\end_inset

, we see 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p}$
\end_inset

 is also a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

, and likewise, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{2}},\alpha^{p^{3}}$
\end_inset

, and so on by iteration.
 Once we reach 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{d}}$
\end_inset

 we have cycled back to the start: 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{d}}=\alpha$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremirreduciblefinfieldpower})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we will show for 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\geq0$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{i}}=\alpha^{p^{j}}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $i\equiv j\mod d$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{d}}=\alpha$
\end_inset

, the implication 
\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 is straightforward.
 To argue in the other direction, we may suppose without loss of generality
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $i\leq j$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $j=i+k$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha^{p^{i}}=\alpha^{p^{i+k}}=(\alpha^{p^{k}})^{p^{i}}.
\]

\end_inset

Applying 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{injectiveintdomainfin})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to this equality 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 times, with 
\begin_inset Formula $A=F$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\alpha^{p^{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{k}}-X$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\mid(X^{p^{k}}-X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 We conclude 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid k$
\end_inset

 by the previous Theorem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 has at most 
\begin_inset Formula $d=\deg\pi$
\end_inset

 roots in any field, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theorempixcontainsallroots})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 tells us 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\alpha^{p},\dots,\alpha^{p^{d-1}}$
\end_inset

 are a complete set of roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 and these roots are distinct.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{3}+X+1$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{2}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 In the field 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\mathbb{F}_{2}[t]\slash(t^{3}+t+1)$
\end_inset

, one root of the polynomial is 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The other roots are 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}^{4}$
\end_inset

.
 If we wish to write the third root without going beyond the second power
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}$
\end_inset

, note 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{4}\equiv t^{2}+t\,\,\mod t^{3}+t+1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{3}+X+1$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t},\overline{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}^{2}+\overline{t}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Finding Irreducibles in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A nice application of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremirreduciblefinfieldpower})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the next result, which is due to Gauss.
 It describes all irreducible polynomials of a given degree in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 as factors of a certain polynomial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X^{p^{n}}-X=\prod_{d\mid n}\prod_{\substack{\deg\pi=d\\
\pi\text{ monic}
}
}\pi(X),\label{eq:gaussirredformulaoverp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 From 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremirreduciblefinfieldpower})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, the irreducible factors of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 are the irreducibles with degree dividing 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 What remains is to show that each monic irreducible factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

 appears only once in the factorization.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 We want to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)^{2}$
\end_inset

 does not divide 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

There is a field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 has a root, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 We will work in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\mid(X^{p^{n}}-X)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X^{p^{n}}-X=\pi(X)k(X),
\]

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{n}}=\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Then in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
X^{p^{n}}-X & =X^{p^{n}}-X-0\\
 & =X^{p^{n}}-X-(\alpha^{p^{n}}-\alpha)\\
 & =(X-\alpha)^{p^{n}}-(X-\alpha)\\
 & =(X-\alpha)((X-\alpha)^{p^{n}-1}-1).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The second factor in the last expression does not vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $(X-\alpha)^{2}$
\end_inset

 does not divide 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)^{2}$
\end_inset

 does not divide 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We factor 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{2^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{2}[X]$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1,2,3,4$
\end_inset

.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
X^{2}-X & =X(X+1)\\
X^{4}-X & =X(X+1)(X^{2}+X+1)\\
X^{8}-X & =X(X+1)(X^{3}+X+1)(X^{3}+X^{2}+1)\\
X^{16}-X & =X(X+1)(X^{2}+X+1)(X^{4}+X+1)(X^{4}+X^{3}+1)(X^{4}+X^{3}+X^{2}+X+1)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}_{p}(n)$
\end_inset

 be the number of monic irreducibles of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}_{p}(1)=p$
\end_inset

.
 On the right side of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:gaussirredformulaoverp})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 dividing 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 there are 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}_{p}(d)$
\end_inset

 different monic irreducible factors of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 Taking degrees of both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:gaussirredformulaoverp})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p^{n}=\sum_{d\mid n}d\mathrm{N}_{p}(d)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Looking at this formula over all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 lets us invert it to get a formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}_{p}(n)$
\end_inset

.
 For example
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{N}_{p}(2)=\frac{p^{2}-p}{2},\quad\mathrm{N}_{p}(3)=\frac{p^{3}-p}{3},\quad\text{and}\quad\mathrm{N}_{p}(12)=\frac{p^{12}-p^{6}-p^{4}+p^{2}}{12}.
\]

\end_inset

A general formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}_{p}(n)$
\end_inset

 can be written down using the Möbius inversion formula.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cyclotomic Polynomials and Roots of Unity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 be a positive integer.
 An 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset


\series bold
th root of unity 
\series default
in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a solution to 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{n}=1$
\end_inset

, or equivalently, it is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{n}-1$
\end_inset

.
 There are at most 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 different 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th roots of unity in a field since 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{n}-1$
\end_inset

 has at most 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 roots in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\series bold
root of unity 
\series default
is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th root of unity for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The only roots of unity in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

, while in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 there are 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 different 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th roots of unity for each 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{n}:=e^{2\pi ik/n}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq k\leq n-1$
\end_inset

 and they form a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 In characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 there is no 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th root of unity besides 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

: if 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p}=1$
\end_inset

 in characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $0=X^{p}-1=(X-1)^{p}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th roots of unity in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 forms a cyclic group.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 denote the set of all of all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th roots of unity in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\times}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 is not an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th root of unity.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is nonempty since 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th root of unity.
 Furthermore, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta\in S$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\alpha\beta^{-1})^{n} & =\alpha^{n}\beta^{-n}\\
 & =1\cdot1\\
 & =1.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is finite since it contains at most 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 elements, and thus it follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propfinitesubgroupofmultgroupoffieldiscyclic})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is cyclic.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We say an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th root of unity is 
\series bold
primitive 
\series default
if it has order 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Cyclotomic Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, an extension of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\zeta)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 is a root of unity, is called a 
\series bold
cyclotomic 
\series default
extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 The important algebraic fact we will explore is that cyclotomic extensions
 of every field have an abelian Galois group; we will look especially at
 cyclotomic extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 and finite fields.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Irreducibility of the Cyclotomic Polynomials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fix 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{n}\slash\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{n}-1$
\end_inset

.
 Define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Phi_{n}(X)=\prod(X-\zeta)\in K_{n}[X],
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 runs over all primitive 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th roots of unity in 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{n}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 all generators of the intrinsic order 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 cyclic group of solutions to 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{n}-1=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{n}$
\end_inset

).
 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{n}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th cyclotomic polynomial
\series default
.
 It is clear from the intrinsic nature of primitive 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th roots of unity that the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Gal}(K_{n}\slash\mathbb{Q})$
\end_inset

 permutes these around.
 Hence, even without knowing if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Gal}(K_{n}\slash\mathbb{Q})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

big
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, it is clear that the monic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

 is invariant under the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Gal}(K_{n}\slash\mathbb{Q})$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, by Galois theory the coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{n}$
\end_inset

 must lie in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

! Its degree is clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $|(\mathbb{Z}\slash n\mathbb{Z})^{\times}|$
\end_inset

.
 The main aim is therefore to prove
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Gauss) The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{n}\in\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By construction, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{n}\in\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

 is monic, and over the extension field 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{n}$
\end_inset

 we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{n}$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{n}-1$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{n}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{n}\in\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{n}-1\in\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

, it follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremdivisioniniffdivisioninL})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{n}$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{n}-1$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 By Gauss' Lemma, since 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{n}-1\in\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

 has integral coefficients, any monic factorization in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

 is necessarily in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 That is, if we write 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{n}-1=\Phi_{n}h$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

, then since 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is visibily monic (as 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{n}-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{n}$
\end_inset

 are monic) it follows that both 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 must lie in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[X]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{n}$
\end_inset

 is not irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

, so there is a factorization 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{n}=fg$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 of positive degree.
 We may also suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 By Gauss' Lemma applied to the monic factorization 
\begin_inset Formula $fg=\Phi_{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{n}\in\mathbb{Z}[X]$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathbb{Z}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 We seek to derive a contradiction.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{n}[X]$
\end_inset

 we have the monic factorization 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{n}=\prod(X-\zeta)$
\end_inset

 where the product runs over all primitive 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th roots of unity in 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 both have positive degree, there must exist distinct primitive 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th roots of unity 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta'$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X-\zeta$
\end_inset

 is a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X-\zeta'$
\end_inset

 is a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 , that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\zeta)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\zeta')=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We can write 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta'=\zeta^{r}$
\end_inset

 for a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in(\mathbb{Z}\slash n\mathbb{Z})^{\times}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta'$
\end_inset

 are primitive 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th roots of unity.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta\neq\zeta'$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $r\neq1$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a positive integer representing this residue class 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, and denote it by 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $r>1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gcd(r,n)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the prime factorization 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\prod p_{j}$
\end_inset

 with primes 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}$
\end_inset

 not necessarily pairwise distinct.
 To go from 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta'=\zeta^{r}$
\end_inset

 we successively raise to exponents 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1},$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}$
\end_inset

, etc.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\zeta)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\zeta')=0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\zeta')\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\zeta)\neq0$
\end_inset

 (as the factorization 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{n}=fg$
\end_inset

 and separability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{n}$
\end_inset

 forces 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 to have no common roots), there must exist a least 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta^{p_{1}\cdots p_{j-1}}$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and its 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}$
\end_inset

th power is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, there is a primitive 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th root of unity 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{0}$
\end_inset

 and prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p\nmid n$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\zeta_{0})=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\zeta_{0}^{p})=0$
\end_inset

.
 We shall deduce a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is irreducible over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

, it must be the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\zeta_{0}^{p})=0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X^{p})\in\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{0}$
\end_inset

 as a root.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mid g(X^{p})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 We can therefore write 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X^{p})=fq$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 necessarily monic.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X^{p})$
\end_inset

 has coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, Gauss' Lemma once again ensures that 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathbb{Z}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X^{p})=fq$
\end_inset

 takes place in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Now reduce mod 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

! In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{f}\overline{q}=\overline{g}(X^{p})=\overline{g}(X)^{p},
\]

\end_inset

the final equality using the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{p}=a$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Monoicity of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 with positive degree ensures that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f},\overline{g}\in\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 have positive degree.
 From the divisibility relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}\mid\overline{g}^{p}$
\end_inset

 we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}$
\end_inset

 must have a nontrivial irreducible factor in common.
 Hence, the product 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}\overline{g}$
\end_inset

 has a nontrivial irreducible factor appearing with multiplicity more than
 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 But in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $fg=\Phi_{n}\mid(X^{n}-1)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{n}-1\in\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 has a nontrivial square factor and hence is not separable.
 But this is absurd, since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 doesn't divide 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and hence the derivative test ensures that 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{n}-1\in\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 is separable! Contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Finite Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 be a monic irreducible polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Then the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a field of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The cosets mod 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 are represented by remainders
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{0}+c_{1}X+\cdots+c_{n-1}X^{n-1},\qquad c_{i}\in\mathbb{F}_{p}
\]

\end_inset

and there are 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 of these.
 Since the modulus 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible, the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We will see that every finite field is isomorphic to a field of the form
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

, so these polynomial constructions gives us working models over any finite
 field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a finite field.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\times}$
\end_inset

 is cyclic.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $q=|K|$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $|K^{\times}|=q-1$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 be the maximal order among all elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $m=q-1$
\end_inset

.
 By Lagrange's Theorem, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $m\mid q-1$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $m\leq q-1$
\end_inset

.
 It is a theorem from group theory that every order of every element must
 divide the maximal order.
 In particular, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{m}=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore all numbers in 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\times}$
\end_inset

 are roots of the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{m}-1$
\end_inset

.
 The number of roots of a polynomial over a field is at most the degree
 of the polynomial, so 
\begin_inset Formula $q-1\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Combining both inequalities gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $m=q-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Finite Rings are Integral Domains if and only if they are Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a finite ring.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 One direction is clear, for the other direction, let 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero element in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, the multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{m}_{a}\colon R\to R$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{m}_{a}(b)=ab
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in R$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is finite and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{m}_{a}$
\end_inset

 is injective, the multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 map must also be surjective.
 Thus there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in R$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
1 & =\mathrm{m}_{a}(b)\\
 & =ab.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Integral Domains with Positive Characteristic must have Prime Characteristic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propintdomposcharprime}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{char}\,R>0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{char}\,R$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us denote 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\mathrm{char}\,R$
\end_inset

.
 We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is a prime.
 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is not a prime.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $1<k,m<n$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =n\cdot1_{R}\\
 & =(km)\cdot1_{R}\\
 & =(k\cdot1_{R})(m\cdot1_{R}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\mathrm{char}\,R$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $(k\cdot1_{R})\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(m\cdot1_{R})\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 But this contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{corcharoffinfieldisprime}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every finite field has prime characteristic.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every finite ring has positive characteristic and every field is an integral
 domain.
 Thus the corollary follows immediately from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{propintdomposcharprime})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Finite Subgroup of Multiplicative Group of Field is Cyclic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmaeveryorderdividesmaximal}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a finite abelian group.
 Then the order of every element must divide the maximal order.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 From the fundamental theorem of finite abelian groups, we have an isomorphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\cong\mathbb{Z}_{k_{1}}\oplus\cdots\oplus\mathbb{Z}_{k_{n}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}\mid\cdots\mid k_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},\dots,e_{n}$
\end_inset

 denote the standard 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}^{n}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{e}_{i}$
\end_inset

 denote the corresponding coset in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{k_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{i}\mid k_{n}$
\end_inset

 we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}$
\end_inset

 kills each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{k_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}$
\end_inset

 kills all of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, the order of every element must divide 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}$
\end_inset

, which is in fact the maximal order as 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}=\mathrm{ord}(\overline{e}_{i_{n}})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmaatmostnroots}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The number of roots of a polynomial over a field is at most the degree
 of the polynomial.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 By replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 with a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 splits into linear factors over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(T)=(T-\alpha_{1})\cdots(T-\alpha_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1},\dots\alpha_{n}\in K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\deg f(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(\alpha)=0 & \iff(\alpha-\alpha_{1})\cdots(\alpha-\alpha_{n})=0\\
 & \iff\alpha-\alpha_{i}=0\text{ for some }i\\
 & \iff\alpha=\alpha_{i}\text{ for some }i,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we obtained the second line from the first line from the fact that
 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 has 
\emph on
at most 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 roots.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propfinitesubgroupofmultgroupoffieldiscyclic}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a finite subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is cyclic.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n=|G|$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 be the maximal order among all elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n$
\end_inset

.
 By Lagrange's Theorem, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $m\mid n$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $m\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaeveryorderdividesmaximal})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that every order of every element must divide the maximal order.
 In particular, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{m}=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in G$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore all numbers in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 are roots of the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{m}-1$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaatmostnroots})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, the number of roots of a polynomial over a field is at most the degree
 of the polynomial, so 
\begin_inset Formula $n\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Combining both inequalities gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Finite Fields have Prime Power Order
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremfinitefieldshaveprimepowerorder}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a finite field.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 has prime power order.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a finite field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Corollary~(
\backslash
ref{corcharoffinfieldisprime})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 tells us that the characteristic of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is prime, denote it by 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\mathrm{char}\,F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\slash(p)$
\end_inset

 embeds as a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we can view 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 as a finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\slash(p)$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\dim_{\mathbb{Z}\slash(p)}(F)$
\end_inset

 and picking a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\slash(p)$
\end_inset

, elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 can be written uniquely as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}e_{1}+\cdots+c_{n}e_{n}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}\in\mathbb{Z}(p)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Each coefficient has 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 choices, so 
\begin_inset Formula $|F|=p^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Classification of Finite Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremclassificationoffinfields}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every finite field is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and some monic irreducible 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a finite field.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremfinitefieldshaveprimepowerorder})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 has order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 for some prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and there is a field embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}\hookrightarrow F$
\end_inset

.
 The group 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{\times}$
\end_inset

 is cyclic by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propfinitesubgroupofmultgroupoffieldiscyclic})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 be a generator of 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Evaluation at 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)\mapsto f(\gamma)$
\end_inset

, is a ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{ev}_{\gamma}\colon\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\to F$
\end_inset

 that fixes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Since every number in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 or a power of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{ev}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is onto (
\begin_inset Formula $0=\mathrm{ev}_{\gamma}(0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{r}=\mathrm{ev}_{\gamma}(X^{r})$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $r\geq0$
\end_inset

).
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash\ker\mathrm{ev}_{\gamma}\cong F.
\]

\end_inset

This implies the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{ev}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

, so it must be 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some monic irreducible 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Fields of size 
\begin_inset Formula $9$
\end_inset

 are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

 need 
\begin_inset Formula $p=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg\pi=2$
\end_inset

.
 The monic irreducible quadratics in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{3}[X]$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+x+2$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+2x+2$
\end_inset

.
 In
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{F}_{3}[X]\slash\langle X^{2}+1\rangle,\quad\mathbb{F}_{3}[X]\slash\langle X^{2}+X+2\rangle,\quad\mathbb{F}_{3}[X]\slash\langle X^{2}+2x+2\rangle,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}$
\end_inset

 is not a generator of the nonzero elements in the first field but is a
 generator of the nonzero elements in the second and third fields.
 So although 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{3}[X]\slash\langle X^{2}+1\rangle$
\end_inset

 is the simplest choice among the three examples, it's not the one that
 would come out of the proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremclassificationoffinfields})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 when we look for a model of fields of order 
\begin_inset Formula $9$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{3}[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Finite Fields as Splitting Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can describe any finite field as a splitting field of a polynomial depending
 only on the size of the field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Field of Prime Power 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a Splitting Fields over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmasplittingfieldoffinfield}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A field of prime power order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a splitting field over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 contains a subfield isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Explicitly, the subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is a field of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Every 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in F$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{p^{n}}=t$
\end_inset

: if 
\begin_inset Formula $t\neq0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{p^{n}-1}=1$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{\times}=F\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 is a multiplicative group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}-1$
\end_inset

, and then multiplying through by 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{p^{n}}=t$
\end_inset

, which is also true when 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

.
 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

 has every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 as a root, so 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

 over the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Existence of Field of Order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremfieldoforderptonexists}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For every prime power 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

, a field of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 exists.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Taking our cue from the statement of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmasplittingfieldoffinfield})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 over which 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

 splits completely.
 Inside 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

 form the set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=\{t\in F\mid t^{p^{n}}=t\}.
\]

\end_inset

This set has size 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 since the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

 is separable over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}(X^{p^{n}}-X) & =p^{n}X^{p^{n}}-1\\
 & =-1
\end{align*}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

 has no roots in common with its derivative.
 It splits completely over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

, so it has 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 roots in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 It contains 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and is easily closed under multiplication and (for nonzero solutions) inversion.
 It remains to show 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is an additive group.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(a+b)^{p}=a^{p}+b^{p}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in F$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th power map 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mapsto t^{p}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is additive.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mapsto t^{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

 is also additive since it's the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-fold composite of 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mapsto t^{p}$
\end_inset

 with itself and the composition of homomorphisms is a homomorphism.
 The fixed points of an additive map are a group under addition, so 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a group under addition.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a field of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For every prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, there is a monic irreducible of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

, and moreover 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 can be chosen so that every nonzero element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is congruent to a power of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremfieldoforderptonexists})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, a field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 exists.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(Theorem~
\backslash
ref{theoremclassificationoffinfields})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, the existence of an abstract field of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 implies the existence of a monic irreducible 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and from the proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremclassificationoffinfields})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}$
\end_inset

 generates the nonzero elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

 since the isomorphism identifies 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}$
\end_inset

 with a generator of 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It's worth appreciating the order in logic behind 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremfieldoforderptonexists})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and its corollary: to show we can construct a field of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg\pi=n$
\end_inset

, the way we showed a 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 exists is by 
\emph on
first 
\emph default
constructing an abstract field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 (using the splitting field construction) and then prove 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 can be made isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 There is no simple formula for an irreducible of every degree in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 (just like there is no simple formula for every prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

!).
 For example, binomial polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{n}-a$
\end_inset

 are reducible when 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid n$
\end_inset

.
 Trinomials 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{n}+aX^{k}+b$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{F}_{p}^{\times}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0<k<n$
\end_inset

 are often irreducible, but in some degrees there are no irreducible trinomials:
 none in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{2}[X]$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $13$
\end_inset

, in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{3}[X]$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $49$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $57$
\end_inset

, in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{5}[X]$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $35$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $70$
\end_inset

, or in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{7}[X]$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $124$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $163$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Irreducibles in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 of Degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 Must Divide 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

 and are Separable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

 has order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{p^{n}}=t$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}\equiv X\mod\pi(X)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

 is separable in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

, so its factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is also separable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Finite Fields of the Same Size are Isomorphic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremfinitefieldisosamesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Any finite field of the same size are isomorphic.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A finite field has prime power size, say 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

, and by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmasplittingfieldoffinfield})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, it is a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Any two splitting fields of a fixed polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 are isomorphic, so any two fields of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 are isomorphic: they are splitting fields of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The analogous theorem for finite groups and finite rings is false: having
 the same size does not usually imply isomorphism.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\slash4\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\slash2\mathbb{Z}\times\mathbb{Z}\slash2\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 both have order 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 and they are nonisomorphic as additive groups and also as commutative rings.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime and let 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 be a positive integer.
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

 for a finite field of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremfinitefieldisosamesize})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, our choice of a finite field of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 is well-defined up to an isomorphism which fixes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 As we shall soon see, there will be 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 such isomorphisms, and they will form the cyclic group 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\slash n\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Classification of Subfields of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

 has order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid n$
\end_inset

, and there is one such subfield for each 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}\subseteq F\subseteq\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $d=[F:\mathbb{F}_{p}]$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}:\mathbb{F}_{p}]=n$
\end_inset

.
 We will describe 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 in a way that only depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $|F|=p^{d}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{\times}$
\end_inset

 has order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}-1$
\end_inset

, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in F^{\times}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{p^{d}}=t$
\end_inset

, and that holds even for 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

.
 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{d}}-X$
\end_inset

 has at most 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}$
\end_inset

 roots in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}$
\end_inset

 different roots of it, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=\{t\in\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}\mid t^{p^{d}}=t\}.
\]

\end_inset

This shows that there is at most one subfield of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

, since the right side is completely determined as a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

 from knowing 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To prove for each 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 dividing 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 there is a subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

 with order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}$
\end_inset

, we turn things around and consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\{t\in\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}\mid t^{p^{d}}=t\}$
\end_inset

.
 It is a field by the same proof that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a field in the proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremfieldoforderptonexists})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 To show its size is 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}$
\end_inset

 we want to show 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{d}}-X$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}$
\end_inset

 roots in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 We'll do this in two ways.
 First, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d\mid n & \implies(p^{d}-1)\mid(p^{n}-1)\\
 & \implies X^{p^{d}-1}-1\mid X^{p^{n}-1}-1\\
 & \implies X^{p^{d}}-X\mid X^{p^{n}}-X,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so since 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

 splits with distinct roots in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}[X]$
\end_inset

 so does its factor 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{d}}-X$
\end_inset

.
 Second, 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid n\implies(p^{d}-1)\mid(p^{n}-1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}^{\times}$
\end_inset

 is cyclic of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}-1$
\end_inset

, so it contains 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}-1$
\end_inset

 solutions to 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{p^{d}-1}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Along with 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}$
\end_inset

 solutions in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{p^{d}}=t$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In the diagram below are the subfields of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{8}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{12}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


