\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 One field of order 
\begin_inset Formula $16=2^{4}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{2}[X]\slash\langle X^{4}+X+1\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 All elements satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{16}=t$
\end_inset

.
 The solutions to 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{2}=t$
\end_inset

 are the subfield 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

 of order 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 and the solutions to 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{4}=t$
\end_inset

 are the subfield 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,1,X^{2}+X,X^{2}+X+1\}$
\end_inset

 of order 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Describing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

-Conjugates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two elements in a finite field are called 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
conjugate 
\series default
if they share the same minimal polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 We will show, after some lemmas about polynomials over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

, that all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

-conjugates can be obtained from each other by successively taking 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th powers.
 This is in contrast to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

: all the roots of an irreducible polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

 are not generally expressible in terms of a particular root, with 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{3}-2$
\end_inset

 being a typical example.
 (The field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt[3]{2})$
\end_inset

 contains only one root to this polynomial, not all 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 roots.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Irreduciple Polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremirreduciblefinfieldpower}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 be irreducible of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\mid(X^{p^{d}}-X)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\mid(X^{p^{n}}-X)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This divisibility in 1 is the same as the congruence 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{d}}\equiv X\mod\pi(X)$
\end_inset

, or equivalently the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}^{p^{d}}=\overline{X}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

.
 Such an equation follows immediately from the Lemmas above, using the field
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To prove 
\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 in 2, write 
\begin_inset Formula $n=kd$
\end_inset

.
 Starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $X\equiv X^{p^{d}}\,\mod\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 and applying the 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}$
\end_inset

th power to both sides 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 times, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
X & \equiv X^{p^{d}}\mod\pi(X)\\
 & \equiv X^{p^{2d}}\mod\pi(X)\\
 & \vdots\\
 & \equiv X^{p^{kd}}\mod\pi(X)\\
 & =X^{p^{n}}\mod\pi(X).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\mid(X^{p^{n}}-X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we prove 
\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 in 2.
 We assume 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X^{p^{n}}\equiv X\mod\pi(X)
\]

\end_inset

and we want to show 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid n$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $n=dq+r$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq r<d$
\end_inset

.
 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
X & \equiv X^{p^{n}}\mod\pi(X)\\
 & \equiv(X^{p^{dq}})^{p^{r}}\mod\pi(X)\\
 & \equiv X^{p^{r}}\mod\pi(X)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This tells us that one particular element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

, the class of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, is equal to its own 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}$
\end_inset

th power.
 More generally, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)\in\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(X)^{p^{r}} & \equiv f(X^{p^{r}})\mod\pi(X)\\
 & \equiv f(X)\mod\pi(X).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

 the congruence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is equal to its own 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}$
\end_inset

th power.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is a general polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

, we have proved every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

 is its own 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}$
\end_inset

th power (in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider now the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{p^{r}}-T$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

, this is a polynomial with degree 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}>1$
\end_inset

, and we have found 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}$
\end_inset

 different roots of this polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

 (namely, every element of this field is a root).
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}\leq p^{r}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $d\leq r$
\end_inset

.
 But, recalling where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 came from, 
\begin_inset Formula $r<d$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction, so 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
 This proves 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Roots of an Irreducible 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 are all Powers of a Root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorempixcontainsallroots}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 be irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 with degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F\supseteq\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 be a field which 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 has a root, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 has roots 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\alpha^{p},\alpha^{p^{2}},\dots,\alpha^{p^{d-1}}$
\end_inset

.
 These 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 roots are distinct; more precisely, when 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 are nonnegative, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{i}}=\alpha^{p^{j}}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $i\equiv j\mod d$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)^{p}=\pi(X^{p})$
\end_inset

, we see 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p}$
\end_inset

 is also a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

, and likewise, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{2}},\alpha^{p^{3}}$
\end_inset

, and so on by iteration.
 Once we reach 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{d}}$
\end_inset

 we have cycled back to the start: 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{d}}=\alpha$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremirreduciblefinfieldpower})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we will show for 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\geq0$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{i}}=\alpha^{p^{j}}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $i\equiv j\mod d$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{d}}=\alpha$
\end_inset

, the implication 
\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 is straightforward.
 To argue in the other direction, we may suppose without loss of generality
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $i\leq j$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $j=i+k$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha^{p^{i}}=\alpha^{p^{i+k}}=(\alpha^{p^{k}})^{p^{i}}.
\]

\end_inset

Applying 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{injectiveintdomainfin})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to this equality 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 times, with 
\begin_inset Formula $A=F$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\alpha^{p^{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{k}}-X$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\mid(X^{p^{k}}-X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 We conclude 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid k$
\end_inset

 by the previous Theorem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 has at most 
\begin_inset Formula $d=\deg\pi$
\end_inset

 roots in any field, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theorempixcontainsallroots})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 tells us 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\alpha^{p},\dots,\alpha^{p^{d-1}}$
\end_inset

 are a complete set of roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 and these roots are distinct.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{3}+X+1$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{2}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 In the field 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\mathbb{F}_{2}[X]\slash(X^{3}+X+1)$
\end_inset

, one root of the polynomial is 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}$
\end_inset

.
 The other roots are 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}^{4}$
\end_inset

.
 If we wish to write the third root without going beyond the second power
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}$
\end_inset

, note 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{4}\equiv X^{2}+X\mod X^{3}+X+1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{3}+X+1$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X},\overline{X}^{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}^{2}+\overline{X}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Galois Groups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

 is the splitting field over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

, which is separable, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}\slash\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 is Galois.
 It is a fundamental feature that the Galois group is cyclic, with a canonical
 generator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Gal}(\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}\slash\mathbb{F})$
\end_inset

 is Cyclic with Canonical Generator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th power map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}\colon t\mapsto t^{p}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

 generates 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Gal}(\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}\slash\mathbb{F}_{p})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Any 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{p}=a$
\end_inset

, so the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}\colon\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}\to\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

 fixes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 pointwise.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}$
\end_inset

 is a field homomorphism and it is injective, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}$
\end_inset

 is surjective since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}\in\mathrm{Gal}(\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}\slash\mathbb{F}_{p})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The size of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Gal}(\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}\slash\mathbb{F}_{p})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}:\mathbb{F}_{p}]=n$
\end_inset

.
 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}$
\end_inset

 has order 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 in this group, so it generates the Galois group.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $r\geq1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}^{r}(t)=t^{p^{r}}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}^{r}$
\end_inset

 is the identity then 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{p^{r}}=t$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

, which can be rewritten as 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{p^{r}}-t=0$
\end_inset

.
 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{r}}-X$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $r\geq1$
\end_inset

), so it has at most 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}$
\end_inset

 roots in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}\leq p^{r}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $n\leq r$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}$
\end_inset

 has order at least 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Gal}(\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}\slash\mathbb{F}_{p})$
\end_inset

, a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}$
\end_inset

 generates the Galois group: every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Gal}(\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}\slash\mathbb{F}_{p})$
\end_inset

 is an iterate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Field Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 be a fields.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $L\supseteq K$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
field extension
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 We denote such a field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

.
 A field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
extension field 
\series default
of a field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

.
 We denote such a field extension by 
\begin_inset Formula $K\slash F$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 We denote the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

-vector space by 
\begin_inset Formula $[K:F]$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, if 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is a field with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F\subseteq E\subseteq K,
\]

\end_inset

we say 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
intermediate 
\series default
extension field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}\mathbb{Q}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}\mathbb{F}_{p}=p$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The characteristic of a field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is either 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 or a prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}F=0$
\end_inset

 then we are done, so assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}F=m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is not prime.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m=ab$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b>1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m\cdot1_{F}=(a\cdot1_{F})(b\cdot1_{F})=0$
\end_inset

 implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $(a\cdot1_{F})=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $(b\cdot1_{F})=0$
\end_inset

.
 In either case, we get a contradiction since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}F\leq a,b<m$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field and define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathbb{Z}\to F$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(n)=n\cdot1_{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a ring homomorphism.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/\mbox{Ker}\varphi\cong\varphi(\mathbb{Z})\subseteq F$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a PID, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\mbox{ch}F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $m=p$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1)=0$
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction, so 
\begin_inset Formula $m=p$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=p\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}\cong\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}\subseteq F$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}F=0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\cong\varphi(\mathbb{Z})\subseteq F$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 contains an isomorphic copy of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 In either case, we call this the 
\series bold
prime subfield 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Field Extension) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be fields.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
field extension 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subset K$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $K/F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 is a field extension, then 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a vector space over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
degree 
\series default
of the extension 
\begin_inset Formula $K/F$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $[K:F]$
\end_inset

, is the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathbb{R}:\mathbb{R}]=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathbb{C}:\mathbb{R}]=2$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 is an irreducible polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, can we find a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 such that the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=0$
\end_inset

 has a solution in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

? Yes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 containing (an isomorphic copy of) 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 has a root 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Identifying 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 with this isomorphic copy which is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, we'll regard 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 as a field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

, which is a PID, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $K:=F[x]/\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:F[x]\to F[x]/\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

 be the canonical projection map given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(a(x))=\overline{a(x)}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:=\pi_{_{\mid F}}$
\end_inset

 gives a ring homomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]/\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a field and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1)\neq0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Finally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:=\overline{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p(\alpha) & =p(\overline{x})\\
 & =\overline{p(x)}\\
 & =\overline{0}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field, 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K:=F[x]/\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:=\bar{x}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\mbox{deg}p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,\alpha,\dots,\alpha^{n-1}\}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

-basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $[K:F]=n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g(x)}\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a field, 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean Domain, so there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x),r(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=q(x)p(x)+r(x)$
\end_inset

 with either 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{deg}r(x)\leq n-1$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g(x)}=\bar{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=c_{0}+c_{1}x+\cdots+c_{\ell}x^{\ell}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\leq n-1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{g(x)} & =\overline{q(x)p(x)+r(x)}\\
 & =\overline{r(x)}\\
 & =\overline{c_{0}+c_{1}x+\cdots+c_{\ell}x^{\ell}}\\
 & =c_{0}+c_{1}\alpha+\cdots+c_{\ell}\alpha^{\ell}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)\in\mbox{Span}\{1,\alpha,\dots,\alpha^{n-1}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,\alpha,\dots,\alpha^{n-1}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0},b_{1},\dots,b_{n-1}\in F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}+b_{1}\alpha+\cdots+b_{n-1}\alpha^{n-1}=\bar{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}+b_{1}x+\cdots+b_{n-1}x^{n-1}=p(x)q(x)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 But the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, so we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x)=0$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Algebraic Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be a field extension.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
An element 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
algebraic 
\series default
over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 if there exists a nonzero polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 is not algebraic, then we say it is 
\series bold
transcendental
\series default
 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
algebraic extension
\series default
 if every 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
transcendental extension 
\series default
if there exists at least one 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 which is transcendental over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
algebraically closed 
\series default
if every irreducible polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $L[X]$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $L[X]$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
algebraic closure 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed and 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is an algebraic extension.

\series bold
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The number 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\pi)=0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=T-\pi$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, it is a nontrivial theorem that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is transcendental over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The imaginary number 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(i)=0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=T^{2}+1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K/F$
\end_inset

 be a field extension.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, then there is a unique monic irreducible polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as a root, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\mid f(x)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial of minimal degree having 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as a root.
 We can assume, without loss of generality, that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is monic.
 We show that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose not.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=a(x)b(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a(x),b(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq\mbox{deg}a(x)<\mbox{deg}p(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq\mbox{deg}b(x)<\mbox{deg}p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $0=p(\alpha)=a(\alpha)b(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $a(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 But this contradicts the minimality of the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Next, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean Domain, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x),r(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=q(x)p(x)+r(x)$
\end_inset

 where either 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{deg}r(x)<\mbox{deg}p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $r(\alpha)=f(\alpha)-q(\alpha)p(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 But this contradicts the minimality of the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that if 
\begin_inset Formula $K/F$
\end_inset

 is a field extension, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq F(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 In this case, the degree of the extension 
\begin_inset Formula $[F(\alpha):F]$
\end_inset

 is the degree of the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K\subseteq L$
\end_inset

 are field extensions, then 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:F]=[L:K][K:F]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $[K:F]=\ell$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]=m$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{m}\}$
\end_inset

 be a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\beta_{1},\dots,\beta_{\ell}\}$
\end_inset

 be a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\alpha_{1}\beta_{1},\dots,\alpha_{m}\beta_{\ell}\}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=x^{3}+3x-1$
\end_inset

 is irreducible over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\pm1)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 But there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let's show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}\notin\mathbb{Q}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}\in\mathbb{Q}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\subseteq\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})\subseteq\mathbb{Q}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $3=[\mathbb{Q}(\alpha):\mathbb{Q}]=[\mathbb{Q}(\alpha):\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})][\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2}):\mathbb{Q}]=[\mathbb{Q}(\alpha):\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})]\cdot2$
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 be a field extension and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell})=F(\alpha_{1})(\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell})=\cdots=F(\alpha_{1})(\alpha_{2})\cdots(\alpha_{\ell}).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 be a field extension.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}\in K$
\end_inset

 are all algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq F(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell})$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}=\mbox{deg}m_{\alpha_{i},F}$
\end_inset

.
 We have a sequence of field extensions
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F\subseteq F(\alpha_{1})\subseteq F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2})\subseteq\cdots\subseteq F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}):F] & =[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}):F(\alpha_{1})][F(\alpha_{1}):F]\\
 & =[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}):F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2})][F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2}):F(\alpha_{1})][F(\alpha_{1}):F]\\
 & =[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}):F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots\alpha_{\ell-1})]\cdots[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2}):F(\alpha_{1})][F(\alpha_{1}):F]\\
 & \leq n_{\ell}\cdots n_{2}n_{1}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 be a field extension.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 is finite if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $K=F(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Constructing Algebraic Closures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field.
 The purpose of this subsection is to construct an algebraic closure of
 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Let us first introduce some notation.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $k,n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th elementary symmetric polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},\dots,X_{n}$
\end_inset


\series default
, denoted 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $e_{k}(X_{1},\dots,X_{n})$
\end_inset


\series default
, is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{k}(X_{1},\dots,X_{n})=\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if }k=0\\
\sum_{1\leq i_{1}<\cdots<i_{k}\leq n}X_{i_{1}}\cdots X_{i_{k}} & \text{if }k\leq n\\
0 & \text{if }k>n
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each nonconstant monic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(X)=X^{n_{f}}+c_{f,1}X^{n_{f}-1}+\cdots+c_{f,k}X^{n_{f}-k}+\cdots+c_{f,n_{f}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{f}$
\end_inset

 is the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{f,k}\in K$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k\leq n_{f}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{f,1},\dots,t_{f,n_{f}}$
\end_inset

 be independent variables.
 Throughout this section, whenever we write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $t_{f,k}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, it is understood that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a nonconstant monic polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k\leq n_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 For each nonconstant monic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, choose a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{f,1},\dots,\alpha_{f,n_{f}}$
\end_inset

 be the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 in this splitting field.
 Finally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[\{t_{f,k}\}]$
\end_inset

 be the polynomial ring generated over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 by indepedent variables doubly indexed by every nonconstant monic 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in K[X]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k\leq n_{f}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be the ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 generated by the coefficients of all the difference polynomials
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(X)-\prod_{i=1}^{n_{f}}(X-t_{f,k})\in A[X].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle\{u_{f,k}\}\rangle$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{f,k}:=c_{f,k}-(-1)^{k}e_{k}(t_{f,1},\dots,t_{f,n_{f}})
\]

\end_inset

for each nonconstant monic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k\leq n_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{f,k}(\alpha_{f,1},\dots,\alpha_{f,n_{f}})=0
\]

\end_inset

for all nonconstant monic polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, we can factor 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha_{f,1}\dots,\alpha_{f,n_{f}})$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(X-\alpha_{f,1})\cdots(X-\alpha_{f,n_{f}})-f(X)=X^{n_{f}}+c_{f,1}X^{n_{f}-1}+\cdots+c_{f,n_{f}}.\label{eq:factoraldjklfsd}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Expanding the righthand side of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:factoraldjklfsd})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and comparing coefficients gives us the desired result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is proper.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is not proper, so 
\begin_inset Formula $1\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 as a finite sum
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
1=\sum_{i=1}^{m}v_{i}u_{f_{i},k_{i}}\label{eq:bothsidesofalgejklsdfs}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}\in A$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Evaluating 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{f_{i},k_{i}}=\alpha_{f_{i},k_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

 to both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:bothsidesofalgejklsdfs})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $1=0$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal, Zorn's Lemma guarantees that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is contained in some maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The quotient ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a field and the natural composite homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K\to A\to A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 of rings lets us view the field 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 as an extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 since ring homomorphisms out of fields are always injective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The field 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is an algebraic closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For each indeterminate 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{f,k}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}_{f,k}$
\end_inset

 denote its coset in 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that for each nonconstant monic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(X) & =X^{n_{f}}+\sum_{k=1}^{n_{f}}c_{f,k}X^{n_{f}-k}\\
 & \equiv X^{n_{f}}+\sum_{k=1}^{n_{f}}(-1)^{k}e_{k}(t_{f_{,},1},\dots,t_{f,n_{f}})X^{n_{f}-k}\,\,\mod\mathfrak{m}\\
 & =\prod_{k=1}^{n_{f}}(X-\overline{t}_{f,k}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{f,1},\dots,u_{f,n_{f}}\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $(A\slash\mathfrak{m})[X]$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}_{f,k}$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

, we see that each 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}_{f,k}$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is an algebraic extension field of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is generated by the 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}_{f,k}$
\end_inset

's (as 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is generated by the 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{f,k}$
\end_inset

's) and that every nonconstant monic in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 splits completely.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We will now show 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed, and thus it is an algebraic closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $F=A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 It suffices to show every monic irreducible 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 We have already seen that any nonconstant monic polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

, so let's show 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is a factor of some monic polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 There is a root 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 in some extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 That implies some monic 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as a root.
 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\mid f(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Uniqueness of Algebraic Closures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout this subsection, let 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 be a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}\slash k$
\end_inset

 be a choice of an algebraic closure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash k$
\end_inset

 be an algebraic extension and let 
\begin_inset Formula $L'\slash L$
\end_inset

 be another algebraic extension.
 There is a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $i\colon L\hookrightarrow\overline{k}$
\end_inset

, and once 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is picked there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $L'\hookrightarrow\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 extending 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since an embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $i\colon L\hookrightarrow\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 realizes the algebraically closed 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 as an algebraic extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 (and hence as an algebraic closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

), by renaming the base field as 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 it suffices to just prove the first part: any algebraic extension admits
 an embedding into a specified algebraic closure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 to be the set of pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(k',i)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $k'\subseteq L$
\end_inset

 is an intermediate extension over 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i\colon k'\hookrightarrow\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-embedding.
 Using the inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{0}\colon k\hookrightarrow\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 that comes along with the data of how 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 is realized as an algebraic closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $(k,i_{0})\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is nonempty.
 We wish to apply Zorn's Lemma, where we define a partial ordering on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 by the condition that 
\begin_inset Formula $(k',i')\leq(k'',i'')$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $k'\subseteq k''$
\end_inset

 inside of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i''|_{k'}=i'$
\end_inset

.
 It is a simple exercise in gluing set maps to see that the hypothesis of
 Zorn's Lemma is satisfied, so there exists a maximal element 
\begin_inset Formula $(K,i)\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We just have to show 
\begin_inset Formula $K=L$
\end_inset

.
 Pick 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in L$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 (as it is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}\in K[T]$
\end_inset

 is the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $K(x)\cong K[T]\slash f_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $i\colon K\hookrightarrow\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 realizes 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 as an algebraic closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}\in K[T]$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Pick such a root, say 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, and then we define 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]\to\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 by using 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 on the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and sending 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 This map kills 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

, and hence factors through the quotient to define a map of fields 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]\slash f_{x}\hookrightarrow\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 extending 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Composing this with the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K(x)\cong K[T]\slash f_{x}$
\end_inset

 therefore defines an element 
\begin_inset Formula $(K(x),i')\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

 which dominates 
\begin_inset Formula $(K,i)$
\end_inset

.
 By maximality, this forces 
\begin_inset Formula $(K(x),i')=(K,i)$
\end_inset

, or in other words 
\begin_inset Formula $K(x)=K$
\end_inset

 as subfields of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 This holds for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in L$
\end_inset

 and says exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $L=K$
\end_inset

, as desired.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

 be two algebraic closures of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{1}\cong\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By the lemma, applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\overline{k}_{1}$
\end_inset

 (algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}=\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

 (an algebraically closed field equipped with a structure of algebraic extension
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

), there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $i\colon\overline{k}_{1}\hookrightarrow\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed, it follows that the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 realizes 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

 as an algebraic extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 But an algebraically closed field (such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{1}$
\end_inset

) admits no non-trivial algebraic extensions, so the map 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is forced to be an isomorphism.
 More concretely, any 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a root of an irreducible monic 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in k[T]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\prod(T-r_{j})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{1}[T]$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed, so applying 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $i(r_{j})$
\end_inset

's exhaust the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $y=i(r_{j})$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, so indeed 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Beware that the isomorphism in the theorem is nearly always highly non-unique
 (it can be composed with any 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-automorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

, of which there are many in general).
 Thus, one should 
\emph on
never 
\emph default
write 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{1}=\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

; 
\emph on
always 
\emph default
keep track of the choice of isomorphism.
 In particular, always speak of 
\emph on
an 
\emph default
algebraic closure rather than 
\emph on
the 
\emph default
algebraic closure; there is no 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

preferred
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 algebraic closure except in cases when there are no non-trivial automorphisms
 over 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 (which happens for fields which have the property of being 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

separably closed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Splitting Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

 is nonconstant, there is a field extension 
\begin_inset Formula $K'\slash K$
\end_inset

 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 picks up a root, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=(T-\alpha)g(T)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(T)\in K'[T]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg g=\deg f-1$
\end_inset

.
 By applying the same process to 
\begin_inset Formula $g(T)$
\end_inset

 and continuing in this way finitely many times, we reach an extension 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 splits into linear factors: in 
\begin_inset Formula $L[T]$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(T)=c(T-\alpha_{1})\cdots(T-\alpha_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

We call the field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{n})$
\end_inset

 that is generated by the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 The idea is that in a splitting field we can find a full set of roots of
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\emph on
no smaller field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 
\emph default
has that property.
 Let's look at some examples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}+3T-2$
\end_inset

 does not split over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

, but it does split over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{17})$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T^{2}+3T-2=\left(T-\frac{-3+\sqrt{17}}{2}\right)\left(T-\frac{-3-\sqrt{17}}{2}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{17})$
\end_inset

 is the smallest field which contains the roots 
\begin_inset Formula $(-3+\sqrt{17})/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(-3-\sqrt{17})/2$
\end_inset

, it must be a splitting field for 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}+3T-2$
\end_inset

.
 The polynomial also splits over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is not a splitting field for 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}+3T-2$
\end_inset

 .
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}(i,-i)=\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}-2$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})$
\end_inset

, since we pick up two roots 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 in the field generated by just one of the roots.
 A splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}-2$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}-2$
\end_inset

 splits into linear factors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}[T]$
\end_inset

, a factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{4}-2$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $(T-\sqrt[4]{2})(T+\sqrt[4]{2})(T-i\sqrt[4]{2})(T+i\sqrt[4]{2})$
\end_inset

.
 A splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{4}-2$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt[4]{2},i\sqrt[4]{2})=\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt[4]{2},i).
\]

\end_inset

In the second description one of the field generators is not a root of the
 original polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{4}-2$
\end_inset

.
 This is a simpler way of writing the splitting field.
 A splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{4}-2$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}(\sqrt[4]{2},i\sqrt[4]{2})=\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

These examples illustrate that, as with irreducibility, the choice of base
 field is an important part of determining the splitting field.
 Over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{4}-2$
\end_inset

 has a splitting field that is an extension of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

, while over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 the splitting field of the same polynomial is an extension (of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

!) of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremsplittingfield}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 be nonconstant in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

 are splitting fields of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]=[L':K]$
\end_inset

, there is a field isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

 fixing all of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, and the number of such isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

 is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{4}-2$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 and is isomorphism to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt[4]{2},i)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $(T^{2}-2)(T^{2}-3)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 and is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2},\sqrt{3})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Homomorphisms on Polynomial Coefficients
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To prove 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremsplittingfield})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we will use an inductive argument involving homomorphisms between polynomial
 rings.
 Any field homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon F\to F'$
\end_inset

 extends to a ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon F[T]\to F'[T]$
\end_inset

 as follows: for 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=\sum_{i=0}^{n}c_{i}T^{i}\in F[T]$
\end_inset

, set 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)=\sum_{i=0}^{n}\sigma(c_{i})T^{i}\in F'[T]$
\end_inset

.
 We call this map 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to the coefficients.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=c_{n}T^{n}+c_{n-1}T^{n-1}+\cdots+c_{1}T+c_{0}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}\in F$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in F$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma(f(\alpha)) & =\sigma(c_{n}\alpha^{n}+c_{n-1}\alpha^{n-1}+\cdots+c_{1}\alpha+c_{0})\\
 & =\sigma(c_{n})\sigma(\alpha)^{n}+\sigma(c_{n-1})\sigma(\alpha)^{n-1}+\cdots+\sigma(c_{1})\sigma(\alpha)+\sigma(c_{0})\\
 & =(\sigma f)(\sigma(\alpha)).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\sigma f)(\sigma(\alpha)) & =\sigma(f(\alpha))\\
 & =\sigma(0)\\
 & =0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 sends any root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 to a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Proof of the Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rather than prove 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremsplittingfield})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 directly, we formula a more general theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon K\to K'$
\end_inset

 be an isomorphism of fields, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 be a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

 be a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K'$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]=[L':K']$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 extends to an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

 and the number of such extensions is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[r,dashed] & L' 
\backslash

\backslash
 K  
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash]  & K' 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We argue by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $K'[T]$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $L'=K'$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $[L':K']=1$
\end_inset

.
 The only extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 in this case is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, so the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $1=[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]>1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is generated as a field over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 by the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 has a root 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 that is not in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Fix this 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 for the rest of the proof.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 be the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)\mid f(T)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 If there's an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}\colon L\to L'$
\end_inset

 extending 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\sigma\pi)(\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha)) & =(\widetilde{\sigma}\pi)(\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha))\\
 & =\widetilde{\sigma}(\pi(\alpha))\\
 & =\widetilde{\sigma}(0)\\
 & =0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the first equality comes from 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 having coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}=\sigma$
\end_inset

 on those coefficients).
 Therefore the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 - to be determined - must come from roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we show 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon K\to K'$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism, applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to coefficients is a ring isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]\to K'[T]$
\end_inset

 (the inverse applies 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{-1}$
\end_inset

 to coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $K'[T]$
\end_inset

), so 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)\mid f(T)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)\mid(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 is monic irreducible, 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

 is monic irreducible (ring isomorphisms preserve irreducibility).
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $L'[T]$
\end_inset

 by the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

, its factor 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $L'[T]$
\end_inset

.
 Pick a root 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'\in L'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $d=\deg\pi(T)=\deg(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $d>1$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $d=[K(\alpha):K]>1$
\end_inset

).
 This information is in the diagram below, and there are at most 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 choices for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

.
 The minimal polynomials of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K'$
\end_inset

 (resp.) are 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[r, dashed] & L' 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K(
\backslash
alpha ) 
\backslash
arrow[r,dashed] 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] & K' (
\backslash
alpha ') 
\backslash
arrow[u, dash] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

d
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & K' 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

d
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,swap]  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

There is a 
\emph on
unique 
\emph default
extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon K\to K'$
\end_inset

 to a field isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)\to K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\mapsto\alpha'$
\end_inset

.
 First we show uniqueness.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'\colon K(\alpha)\to K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

 extends 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'(\alpha)=\alpha'$
\end_inset

 , then the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 is determined everywhere on 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)=K[\alpha]$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma'\left(\sum_{i=0}^{m}c_{i}\alpha^{i}\right) & =\sum_{i=0}^{m}\sigma'(c_{i})(\sigma'(\alpha))^{i}\\
 & =\sum_{i=0}^{m}\sigma(c_{i})\alpha'^{i}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In other words, a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 goes to the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $K'$
\end_inset

-polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is applied to the coefficients.
 Thus there is at most one 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 extending 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'(\alpha)=\alpha'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To prove 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 exists, we will build an isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

 with the desired behavior on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Any element of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 It can be like this for more than one polynomial: perhaps 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=g(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 In that case 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)\equiv g(T)\text{ mod }\pi(T)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=g(T)+\pi(T)h(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to coefficients on both sides, which is a ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]\to K'[T]$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)=(\sigma g)(T)+(\sigma\pi)(T)(\sigma h)(T)$
\end_inset

, and setting 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\alpha'$
\end_inset

 kills off the second term, leaving us with 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(\alpha')=(\sigma g)(\alpha')$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore it is 
\emph on
well-defined 
\emph default
to set 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'\colon K(\alpha)\to K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)\mapsto(\sigma f)(\alpha')$
\end_inset

.
 This function is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and sends 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

.
 Since applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to coefficients is a ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]\to K'[T]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 is a field homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)\to K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 are written as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $xy=f(\alpha)g(\alpha)=(fg)(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 (evaluation at 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is multiplicative) so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma'(xy) & =\sigma(fg)(\alpha')\\
 & =((\sigma f)(\sigma g))(\alpha')\\
 & =(\sigma f)(\alpha')(\sigma g)(\alpha')\\
 & =\sigma'(x)\sigma'(y).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Using 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{-1}\colon K'\to K$
\end_inset

 to go the other way shows 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 is a field isomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Place 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 in the field diagram below
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[r, dashed] & L' 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K(
\backslash
alpha ) 
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma '
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] & K' (
\backslash
alpha ') 
\backslash
arrow[u, dash] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

d
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & K' 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

d
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,swap]  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we can finally induct on degrees of splitting fields.
 Take as new base fields 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

, which are isomorphic by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, it's also a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 over the larger field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

 is a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K'$
\end_inset

 and thus also over the larger field 
\begin_inset Formula $K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 has its coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'=\sigma$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma'f)(T)=(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

.
 So the top square in the above diagram is like the square in the theorem
 itself, except the splitting field degrees dropped: since 
\begin_inset Formula $d>1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[L:K(\alpha)]=\frac{[L:K]}{d}<[L:K].
\]

\end_inset

By induction, 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K(\alpha)]=[L':K'(\alpha')]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 has an extension to a field isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 extends 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 itself has an extension to an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[L:K] & =[L:K(\alpha)]d\\
 & =[L':K'(\alpha')]d\\
 & =[L':K'].
\end{align*}

\end_inset

(If the proof started with 
\begin_inset Formula $K'=K$
\end_inset

, it would usually be false that 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)=K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremsplittingfield})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is not directly accessible to our inductive proof.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It remains to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 has at most 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]$
\end_inset

 extensions to an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

.
 First we show every isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}\colon L\to L'$
\end_inset

 extending 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the extension of some intermediate isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 with a subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

.
 From the start of the proof, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 must be a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha':=\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}|_{K}=\sigma$
\end_inset

, the restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}|_{K(\alpha)}$
\end_inset

 is a field homomorphism that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and sends 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}|_{K(\alpha)}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $K'(\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha))=K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a lift of the intermediate field isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma':=\widetilde{\sigma}|_{K(\alpha)}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[r, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\backslash
widetilde{
\backslash
sigma }
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] & L' 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K(
\backslash
alpha ) 
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma '
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] & K' (
\backslash
alpha ') 
\backslash
arrow[u, dash] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

d
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & K' 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

d
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,swap]  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

By induction on degrees of splitting fields, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 lifts to at most 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K(\alpha)]$
\end_inset

 isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 is determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, which is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

, the number of maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg(\sigma\pi)(T)=d$
\end_inset

.
 The number of isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

 that lift 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the number of homomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'\colon K(\alpha)\to L'$
\end_inset

 lifting 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 times the number of extensions of each 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 to an isomoprhism 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

, and that total is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $d[L:K(\alpha)]=[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Separability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defnseparability}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field.
 We have the following definitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
separable 
\series default
when it has distinct roots in a splitting field over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 That is, each root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 has multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 has a multiple root, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
inseparable
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
purely inseparable 
\series default
if it has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{d}}-c$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $d\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in K$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 be an algebraic number over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
separable over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 
\series default
when its minimal polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is inseperable over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
inseperable over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is a field extension, then the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $T-\alpha$
\end_inset

, which is clearly separable.
 Thus we really do need the qualifier 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in this definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
purely inseperable 
\series default
if its minimal polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is purely inseparable.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be an algebraic field extension.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
separable 
\series default
field extension if every 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 is separable over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
inseparable 
\series default
field extension if there exists one 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 which is inseparable over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
purely inseparable 
\series default
if every 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 is purely inseperable.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]$
\end_inset

, the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}-T$
\end_inset

 is separable since its roots are 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{3}-2$
\end_inset

 is separable since there are 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 different cube roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 in the complex numbers.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{3}[T]$
\end_inset

 the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{3}-2$
\end_inset

 is inseparable because
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T^{3}-2=(T+1)^{3}
\]

\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{3}[T]$
\end_inset

, so it has a triple root.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Separable Polynomials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Definition~(
\backslash
ref{defnseparability})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, checking a polynomial is separable requires building a splitting field
 to check the roots are distinct.
 It turns out however that there is a criterion for deciding a polynomial
 is separable (that is, having no multiple roots) without having to work
 in a splitting field.
 Indeed, we can use differentiation in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

 to describe the separability condition without leaving 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Criterion for Nonzero Polynomial to be Separable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{firstcriterionseparability}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A nonzero polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

 is separable if and only if it is relatively prime to its derivative in
 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is separable, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 be any root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 (in some extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

).
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(T)=(T-\alpha)h(T)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $h(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $h(\alpha)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f'(\alpha) & =h(\alpha)+(\alpha-\alpha)h'(\alpha)\\
 & =h(\alpha)\\
 & \neq0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is not a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)$
\end_inset

 have no common roots, so they have no common factors in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

: they are relatively prime.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is not separable, so by definition it has a repeated root (in a splitting
 field over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

).
 This root is also a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, when 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=(T-\alpha)^{2}g(T)$
\end_inset

, the product rule shows
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f'(T)=(T-\alpha)^{2}g'(T)+2(T-\alpha)g(T),
\]

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)$
\end_inset

 have 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as a common root, they are both divisible by the minimal polynomial of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)$
\end_inset

 are not relatively prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 Taking the contrapositive, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 has no repeated root so it is separable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

When we are given a specific 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

, whether or not 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime can be checked by Euclid's algorithm for polynomials.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{3}[T]$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=T^{6}+T^{5}+T^{4}+2T^{3}+2T^{2}+T+2$
\end_inset

.
 Using Euclid's algorithm in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{3}[T]$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(T) & =f'(T)(2T^{2}+T)+(2T^{2}+2)\\
f'(T) & =(2T^{2}+2)(T^{2}+2T+2),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $(f(T),f'(T))=2T^{2}+2$
\end_inset

.
 The greatest common divisor is nonconstant, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is inseparable.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=(T^{2}+1)^{2}(T^{2}+T+2)$
\end_inset

.
 Notice we were able to detect that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 has a repeated root 
\emph on
before 
\emph default
we gave its factorization.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=T^{n}-a$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 The derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $nT^{n-1}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(f(T),f'(T))=f(T)$
\end_inset

 is nonconstant, so 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{n}-a$
\end_inset

 is inseparable.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n\neq0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(T^{n}-a,nT^{n-1})=1$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 doesn't divide 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{n}-a$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{n}-a$
\end_inset

 is separable in over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $n\neq0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Criterion for Irreducible Polynomial to be Separable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For any field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, an irreducible polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is separable if and only if its derivative if not 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, when 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 every irreducible over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is separable and when 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, an irreducible over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is separable if and only if it is not a polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 be irreducible over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Separability is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $(\pi(T),\pi'(T))=1$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{firstcriterionseparability})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(T)$
\end_inset

 are not relatively prime, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)\mid\pi'(T)$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 Taking the derivative drops degrees, so having 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(T)$
\end_inset

 be divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 forces 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(T)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(T)=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\pi(T),\pi'(T))=\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 is nonconstant, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 is inseparable by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{firstcriterionseparability})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Thus separability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(T)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, every irreducible over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has nonzero derivative since any nonconstant polynomial has nonzero derivative.
 So all irreducibles over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 are separable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 If there is an irreducible 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 that is not separable, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(T)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(T)=T^{n}+c_{n-1}T^{n-1}+\cdots+c_{1}T+c_{0},
\]

\end_inset

the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(T)=0$
\end_inset

 means 
\begin_inset Formula $ic_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid i$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}\neq0$
\end_inset

, so the only nonzero terms in 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 occur in degrees divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\deg\pi$
\end_inset

 is a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $n=pm$
\end_inset

.
 Write each exponent of a nonzero term in 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 as a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(T)=T^{pm}+c_{p(m-1)}T^{p(m-1)}+\cdots+c_{p}T^{p}+c_{0}=g(T^{p})
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)\in K[T^{p}]$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)=g(T^{p})$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{p}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(T)=g'(T^{p})pT^{p-1}=0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 is inseparable if it is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\mathbb{F}_{3}(u)$
\end_inset

 be a rational function field over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{7}+u^{2}T^{5}+u\in K[T]$
\end_inset

 is irreducible by Eisenstein's criterion.
 It is also separable since it is irreducible and its derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{6}+2u^{2}T^{4}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Multiplicities for Inseparable Irreducible Polynomials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a polynomial is inseparable, at least one of its roots has multiplicity
 greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 The multiplicities of all the roots need not agree.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{2}(X-1)^{3}=0$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 as a root with multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 as a root with multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 This polynomial is reducible, so it is a dull example.
 When an inseparable polynomial is 
\emph on
irreducible
\emph default
, which can only happen in positive characteristic, it is natural to ask
 how the multiplicities of different roots are related to each other.
 In fact, the multiplicities are all the same:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\in K[X]$
\end_inset

 be irreducible, where 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p>0$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)=\widetilde{\pi}(X^{p^{m}})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq0$
\end_inset

 is as large as possible.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\pi}(X)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible and separable in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, and each root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 has multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg\pi=p^{m}\deg\widetilde{\pi}$
\end_inset

, there is a largest possible 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 that can be used.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)=\widetilde{\pi}(X^{p^{m}})$
\end_inset

, any nontrivial factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\pi}(X)$
\end_inset

 gives one for 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\pi}(X)=f(X)g(X)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)=f(X^{p^{m}})g(X^{p^{m}})$
\end_inset

), so 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\pi}(X)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 By the maximality of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, we se that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\pi}(X)$
\end_inset

 is not a polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p}$
\end_inset

, which means its derivative is not 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, so it must be separable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\pi}(X)$
\end_inset

 in a splitting field over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\pi}(X)=c(X-\alpha_{1})\cdots(X-\alpha_{d}),
\]

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

's are distinct since 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\pi}(X)$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi(X) & =\widetilde{\pi}(X)\\
 & =c(X^{p^{m}}-\alpha_{1})\cdots(X^{p^{m}}-\alpha_{d}),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}=\gamma_{i}^{p^{m}}$
\end_inset

 in a large enough field.
 Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th power map is injective in characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, distinctness of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

's implies distinctness of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

's.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi(X) & =c(X^{p^{m}}-\alpha_{1})\cdots(X^{p^{m}}-\alpha_{d})\\
 & =c(X^{p^{m}}-\gamma_{1}^{p^{m}})\cdots(X^{p^{m}}-\gamma_{d}^{p^{m}}),\\
 & =c(X-\gamma_{1})^{p^{m}}\cdots(X-\gamma_{d})^{p^{m}},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which shows the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 (the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

's) are the 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{m}$
\end_inset

th roots of the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\pi}(X)$
\end_inset

 (the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

's), and each root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 has multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Separable Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be a finite extension of fields with 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]=n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon K\to F$
\end_inset

 a field embedding.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
label{diagram}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[dd, dash, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

n
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,swap] 
\backslash
arrow[dr,dashed]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

& F 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K 
\backslash
arrow[ur,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

, swap]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to an embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to F$
\end_inset

 is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is inseparable then the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to an embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to F$
\end_inset

 is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is separable then there is a field 
\begin_inset Formula $F'\supseteq F$
\end_inset

 such that the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to an embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to F'$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 We argue by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $n=[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $L=K$
\end_inset

 and the result is clear.
 Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $n>1$
\end_inset

.
 Pick 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\notin K$
\end_inset

.
 Our field diagram looks like the following.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
label{diagram}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[d, dash]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K(
\backslash
alpha ) & F 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] 
\backslash
arrow[ur,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

, swap]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To bound the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to an embedding of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, we first bound the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to an embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\colon K(\alpha)\to F$
\end_inset

 and then bound the number of extensions of any such 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 to an embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to F$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
label{diagram}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[d, dash]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K(
\backslash
alpha ) 
\backslash
arrow[r, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\backslash
tau 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & F 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] 
\backslash
arrow[ur,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

, swap]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the proof that two splitting fields of a polynomial are isomorphic,
 the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

's extending 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the number of roots in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(X)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 The number of these roots is 
\emph on
at most 
\emph default
the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(X)$
\end_inset

, which equals 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg\pi=[K(\alpha):K]$
\end_inset

.
 This upper bound could be strict for two reasons: 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(X)$
\end_inset

 might not split in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

 or it could split but be inseparable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Once we have extended 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to some 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, we count how many ways 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 extends to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 As in the proof that splitting fields are isomorphic, the trick is to consider
 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 as the new base field, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 playing the role of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\notin K$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[L:K(\alpha)]<[L:K],
\]

\end_inset

so by induction on the field degree the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\colon K(\alpha)\to F$
\end_inset

 to an embedding of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K(\alpha)]$
\end_inset

.
 Multiplying the upper bounds on the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 and the number of further extensions up to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is at most
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[L:K(\alpha)][K(\alpha):K]=[L:K],
\]

\end_inset

so by induction we're done.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is inseparable, some 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 is inseparable over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Running through the first part of the proof of (1) with this 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, its minimal polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 is inseparable, so 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(X)$
\end_inset

 is inseparable in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

.
 This inseparability forces the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 to be 
\emph on
less 
\emph default
than 
\begin_inset Formula $[K(\alpha):K]=\deg\pi$
\end_inset

.
 By (1), the number of extensions up to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 of any field embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)\to F$
\end_inset

 is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K(\alpha)]$
\end_inset

, so the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is strictly less than
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[L:K(\alpha)][K(\alpha):K]=[L:K].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $L=K(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{r})$
\end_inset

 with each 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 separable over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 We want to construct a field 
\begin_inset Formula $F'\supseteq F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon K\to F$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]$
\end_inset

 extensions to embeddings of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $F'$
\end_inset

.
 We will argue in a similar way to (1), but replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 with some larger 
\begin_inset Formula $F'$
\end_inset

 will let the upper bound on the number of embeddings in the proof of (1)
 be reached.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Transitivity of Separable Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K\subseteq L$
\end_inset

 be an extension of fields and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash F$
\end_inset

 is algebraic.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash F$
\end_inset

 is separable if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K\slash F$
\end_inset

 are separable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash F$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $K\slash F$
\end_inset

 is separable since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, so it remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)$
\end_inset

 be the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,F}(X)$
\end_inset

 be the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}\mid\pi_{\alpha,F}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)g(X)=\pi_{\alpha,F}(X)\label{eq:diffbothsidesof}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)\in K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Now differentiate both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:diffbothsidesof})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\alpha$
\end_inset

 to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{\alpha,K}'(\alpha)g(\alpha)=\pi_{\alpha,F}'(\alpha).
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,F}'(\alpha)\neq0$
\end_inset

 since otherwise this would imply 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,F}\mid\pi_{\alpha,F}'$
\end_inset

 which would contradict separability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\alpha)\neq0$
\end_inset

 since otherwise this would imply 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}\mid g$
\end_inset

 which would imply 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}^{2}\mid\pi_{\alpha,F}$
\end_inset

 which would again contradict separability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K\slash F$
\end_inset

 are both separable.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)$
\end_inset

 be the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,F}(X)$
\end_inset

 be the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is separable over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $K\slash F$
\end_inset

 is a separable extension, thus we may assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\notin K$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}\mid\pi_{\alpha,F}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)g_{1}(X)=\pi_{\alpha,F}(X)\label{eq:diffbothsidesof-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(X)\in K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Now differentiate both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:diffbothsidesof})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\alpha$
\end_inset

 to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{\alpha,K}'(\alpha)g_{1}(\alpha)=\pi_{\alpha,F}'(\alpha).
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}'(\alpha)\neq0$
\end_inset

 since otherwise this would imply 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}\mid\pi_{\alpha,K}'$
\end_inset

 which would contradict separability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}\mid g$
\end_inset

 which would imply 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}^{2}\mid\pi_{\alpha,F}$
\end_inset

 which would again contradict separability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)$
\end_inset

 be its minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,F}(X)$
\end_inset

 be its minimal polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

, then the result is clear, so assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\notin K$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}(\alpha)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 We wish to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,F}$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}\mid\pi_{\alpha,F}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}f=\pi_{\alpha,F}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)\in F[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Also, note that since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}$
\end_inset

 is separable and irreducible, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi_{\alpha,F}'(X) & =\pi_{\alpha,K}'(X)f(X)+\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)f'(X)\\
 & =\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)f'(X)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(\alpha)\neq0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg f'<\deg\pi_{\alpha,F}$
\end_inset

, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,F}'(\alpha)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'_{\alpha,F}(X)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,F}$
\end_inset

 is separable which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Classification of Finite Separable Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be a finite extension and write 
\begin_inset Formula $L=K(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{r})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is separable if and only if each 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 is separable over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Primitive Element Theorem) Any finite separable extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\gamma)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, all of its finite extensions are separable, so the primitive element theorem
 says any finite extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\gamma)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Trace and Norm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definition of Trace, Norm, and Characteristic Polynomial
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be a finite field extension.
 We associate each element 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-linear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}\colon L\to L$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, that is,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}(x)=\alpha x
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in L$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}=(e_{1},\dots,e_{n})$
\end_inset

 is an ordered 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 The matrix representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}$
\end_inset

 will be denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]_{\mathbf{e}}$
\end_inset

.
 If the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}$
\end_inset

 is clear from context, then will will simplify this notation to just 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}'=(e_{1}',\dots,e_{n}')$
\end_inset

 is another ordered 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a change of basis matrix from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}'$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}'=\mathbf{e}C$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]_{\mathbf{e}'}=C^{-1}[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]_{\mathbf{e}}C.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular, the trace and norm of the matrix represenation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 does not depend on the basis.
 Now let us define the trace and norm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be a finite field extension and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

.
 We define the 
\series bold
trace function
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tr}_{L\slash K}\colon L\to K$
\end_inset

 and 
\series bold
norm function
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}\colon L\to K$
\end_inset

 as follows: choose any ordered 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}=(e_{1},\dots,e_{n})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

 let 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]$
\end_inset

 be the matrix representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 with respect to this basis.
 Then we set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Tr}_{L\slash K}(\alpha)=\mathrm{tr}[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]\quad\text{and}\quad\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha)=\det[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]
\]

\end_inset

We also define the 
\series bold
characteristic polynomial 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 relative to the extension 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 to be the polynomial
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\chi_{\alpha,L\slash K}(X)=\det(X\cdot I_{n}-[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}])\in K[X],
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n=[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{exampletracenormcharex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\mathbb{Q}(\gamma)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{3}-X-1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{3}=1+\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Use the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,\gamma,\gamma^{2}\}$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=a+b\gamma+c\gamma^{3}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 rational, multiply 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $1,\gamma$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\alpha\cdot1 & =a+b\gamma+c\gamma^{2}\\
\alpha\cdot\gamma & =a\gamma+b\gamma^{2}+c\gamma^{3}=c+(a+c)\gamma+b\gamma^{2}\\
\alpha\cdot\gamma^{2} & =c\gamma+(a+c)\gamma^{2}+b\gamma^{3}=b+(b+c)\gamma+(a+c)\gamma^{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]$
\end_inset

 equals
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}a & c & b\\
b & a+c & b+c\\
c & b & a+c
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{Tr}_{L/K}(\alpha) & =3a+2c\\
\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha) & =a^{3}+2a^{2}c-ab^{2}-3abc+ac^{2}+b^{3}-bc^{2}+c^{3}\\
\chi_{\alpha,L\slash K}(X) & =X^{3}-(3a+2c)X^{2}+(b^{2}+3bc-c^{2}-4ac-3a^{2})X-(a^{3}+2a^{2}c-ab^{2}-3abc+ac^{2}+b^{3}-bc^{2}+c^{3})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 square matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, its trace and determinant appear up to sign as coefficients in its characteris
tic polynomial:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det(XI_{n}-A)=X^{n}-\mathrm{tr}(A)X^{n-1}+\cdots+(-1)^{n}\det A.
\]

\end_inset

Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\chi_{\alpha,L\slash K}(X)=X^{n}-\mathrm{Tr}_{L\slash K}(\alpha)X^{n-1}+\cdots+(-1)^{n}\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha).
\]

\end_inset

This tells us the trace and norm of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 are, up to sign, coefficients of the characteristic polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, which can been seen in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{exampletracenormcharex})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Unlike the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, whose degree 
\begin_inset Formula $[K(\alpha):K]$
\end_inset

 varies with 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\alpha,L\slash K}(X)$
\end_inset

 is always 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, which is independent of the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a root of its own characteristic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\alpha,L\slash K}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is a consequence of the Cayley-Hamilton theorem in linear algebra.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Properties of Trace and Norm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be a finite field extension.
 The trace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tr}_{L\slash K}\colon L\to K$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-linear and the norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}:L\to K$
\end_inset

 is multiplicative.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(L^{\times})\subseteq K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta\in L$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Choose any basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{Tr}_{L\slash K}(a\alpha+b\beta) & =\mathrm{tr}[\mathrm{m}_{a\alpha+b\beta}]\\
 & =\mathrm{tr}[a\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}+b\mathrm{m}_{\beta}]\\
 & =a\mathrm{tr}[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]+b\mathrm{tr}[\mathrm{m}_{\beta}]\\
 & =a\mathrm{Tr}_{L\slash K}(\alpha)+b\mathrm{Tr}_{L\slash K}(\beta).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similarly we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha\beta) & =\det[m_{\alpha\beta}]\\
 & =\det[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}\mathrm{m}_{\beta}]\\
 & =\det[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]\det[\mathrm{m}_{\beta}]\\
 & =\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha)\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\beta).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tr}_{L\slash K}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-linear and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}$
\end_inset

 is multiplicative.
 For the last statement, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
1 & =\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(1)\\
 & =\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha\alpha^{-1})\\
 & =\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha)\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha^{-1}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha)\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Trace and Norm For a Galois Extension
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be a finite Galois extension with Galois group 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\mathrm{Gal}(L\slash K)$
\end_inset

.
 We can express characteristic polynomials, traces, and norms for the extension
 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 When 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is a finite Galois extension with Galois group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\chi_{\alpha,L\slash K}(X)=\prod_{\sigma\in G}(X-\sigma(\alpha)).
\]

\end_inset

In particular,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Tr}_{L\slash K}(\alpha)=\sum_{\sigma\in G}\sigma(\alpha),\quad\text{and}\quad\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha)=\prod_{\sigma\in G}\sigma(\alpha).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)$
\end_inset

 be the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\alpha,L\slash K}(X)=\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)^{n/d}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $n=[L:K]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d=[K(\alpha):K]=\deg\pi_{\alpha,K}$
\end_inset

.
 From Galois theory,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)=\prod_{i=1}^{d}(X-\sigma_{i}(\alpha))
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1}(\alpha),\dots,\sigma_{d}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 are all the distinct values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 runs over the Galois group.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in G$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\alpha)=\sigma_{i}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 for a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\alpha)=\sigma_{i}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\sigma_{i}H$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H=\{\tau\in G\mid\tau(\alpha)=\alpha\}=\mathrm{Gal}(L\slash K(\alpha)).
\]

\end_inset

Therefore as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 runs over 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, the number 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 appears as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is in the left coset 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}H$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 occurs 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|$
\end_inset

 times, and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|H| & =[L:K(\alpha)]\\
 & =[L:K]/[K(\alpha):K]\\
 & =n/d.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\prod_{\sigma\in G}(X-\sigma(\alpha)) & =\prod_{i=1}^{d}(X-\sigma_{i}(\alpha))^{n/d}\\
 & =\left(\prod_{i=1}^{d}(X-\sigma_{i}(\alpha))\right)^{n/d}\\
 & =\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)^{n/d}\\
 & =\chi_{\alpha,L/K}(X).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Perfect Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 fields have a very handy feature: every irreducible polynomial in characteristi
c 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 Fields in characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 may or may not have this feature.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
perfect 
\series default
if every irreducible polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Extension of Rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Integral and Finite Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Integral extension of a ring means adjoining roots of monic polynomials
 over the ring.
 This is an important tool for studying affine rings, and it is used in
 many places, for example, in dimension theory, ring normalization and primary
 decomposition.
 Integral extensions are closely related to finite maps which, geometrically,
 can be though of as projections with finite fibres plus some algebraic
 conditions.
 Let us record the following definitions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 be an extension of rings.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
An element 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
integral over
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 if there is a monic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)\in A[T]$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $f(b)=0$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
root 
\series default
of the monic 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
integral over 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 or an 
\series bold
integral extension of
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 if every 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
finite extension 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

 is a ring map then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is called an 
\series bold
integral
\series default
 (respectively 
\series bold
finite
\series default
) 
\series bold
extension
\series default
 if this holds for the subring 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(A)\subset B$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, an element 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 
\series default
if it is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(A)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples and Nonexamples of Integral Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 Then for any ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, the quotient map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon A\to A\slash\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
 More generally, any surjective ring map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x,y]\subset K[x,y,z]/\langle x-yz\rangle$
\end_inset

 is not an integral extension.
 Indeed, there is no monic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in K[x,y][t]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)=0$
\end_inset

.
 To see why, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z^{n}+a_{n-1}z^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}=0,\label{eq:1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0},\dots,a_{n-1}\in K[x,y]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $z\equiv x/y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x,y,z]/\langle x-yz\rangle$
\end_inset

, we can rewrite 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:1-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{x^{n}}{y^{n}}+a_{n-1}\frac{x^{n-1}}{y^{n-1}}+\cdots+a_{0}=0.
\]

\end_inset

After clearing the denominators and rearranging terms, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{n}=-y(a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}y^{n-1}).
\]

\end_inset

This is clearly false since 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x,y]$
\end_inset

 is a UFD.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $K[y,z]\subset K[x,y,z]/\langle x-yz\rangle$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
 Indeed, clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 are integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $K[y,z]$
\end_inset

.
 Also, since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 satisfies the monic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(t)=t-yz\in K[y,z][t],
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[y,z]$
\end_inset

 as well.
 We will see shortly that the product and sum of integral elements is integral,
 and thus every element in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x,y,z]/\langle x-yz\rangle$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $K[y,z]$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x,y,z]\slash\langle x-yz\rangle\cong K[y,z]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 be a nonzerodivisor.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\to A[x^{-1}]$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A[x^{-1}]=A$
\end_inset

, and so obviously 
\begin_inset Formula $A\to A[x^{-1}]$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0},\dots,a_{n-1}\in A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{-n}+a_{n-1}x^{-(n-1)}+\cdots+a_{0}=0.\label{eq:xinverse}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Multiplying both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:xinverse})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n-1}$
\end_inset

 and rearranging terms, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{-1}=-a_{n-1}+a_{n-2}x+\cdots+a_{0}x^{n-1}\in A.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}$
\end_inset

 be an algebraic closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq\overline{K}$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\overline{K}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, which means there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0},\dots,a_{n-1},a_{n}\in K$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{n}x^{n}+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}=0.\label{eq:algebraicelementmultbothsidesss}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Multiplying by 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 on both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:algebraicelementmultbothsidesss})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{n}+a_{n-1}a_{n}^{-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}a_{n}^{-1}=0.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a root of the monic 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=T^{n}+a_{n-1}a_{n}^{-1}T^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}a_{n}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq\overline{K}$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Properties of Integral Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Integrality is a local property in the following sense:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 be an extension of rings and let 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\mathfrak{p}}(b)=b/1$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 for all primes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0},\dots,a_{n-1}\in A$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b^{n}+a_{n-1}b^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}=0.\label{eq:integralllocaiff}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Applying the localization map 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:integralllocaiff})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(b/1)^{n}+(a_{n-1}/1)(b/1)^{n-1}+\cdots+(a_{0}/1)=0
\]

\end_inset

where each 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}/1\in A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $b/1$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 for all prime ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\mathfrak{p}}(b)=b/1$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 for all prime ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $b/1$
\end_inset

 being integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 means that there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathfrak{p}}\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{\mathfrak{p}}\in A\backslash\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathfrak{p},n_{\mathfrak{p}}-1},\dots,a_{\mathfrak{p},0}\in A$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{\mathfrak{p}}b^{n_{\mathfrak{p}}}+a_{\mathfrak{p},n_{\mathfrak{p}}-1}b^{n_{\mathfrak{p}}-1}+\cdots+a_{\mathfrak{p},0}=0.
\]

\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\{s_{\mathfrak{p}}\mid\mathfrak{p}\text{ prime ideal}\}\rangle$
\end_inset

 be the ideal generated by all 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

's.
 Then we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\{s_{\mathfrak{p}}\}\rangle=A$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, otherwise 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\{s_{\mathfrak{p}}\}\rangle$
\end_inset

 would be contained in a maximal ideal, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

, which would be a contradiction as this would imply 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{\mathfrak{m}}\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus since 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\{s_{\mathfrak{p}}\}\rangle=A$
\end_inset

, there exists finitely many primes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{1},\dots\mathfrak{p}_{k}$
\end_inset

 and elements 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{k}\in A$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{1}s_{\mathfrak{p}_{1}}+\cdots+a_{k}s_{\mathfrak{p}_{k}}=1.
\]

\end_inset

By reordering if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathfrak{p}_{1}}\geq n_{\mathfrak{p}_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq k$
\end_inset

.
 Then note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\sum_{i=1}^{k}a_{i}b^{n_{\mathfrak{p}_{1}}-n_{\mathfrak{p}_{i}}}\left(s_{\mathfrak{p}_{i}}b^{n_{\mathfrak{p}_{i}}}+a_{\mathfrak{p}_{i},n_{\mathfrak{p}_{i}}-1}b^{n_{\mathfrak{p}_{i}}-1}+\cdots+a_{\mathfrak{p}_{i},0}\right)\\
 & =\left(\sum_{i=1}^{k}a_{i}s_{\mathfrak{p}_{i}}\right)b^{n_{\mathfrak{p}_{1}}}+\text{lower terms in }b\\
 & =b^{n_{\mathfrak{p}_{1}}}+\text{lower terms in }b.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Finite Extensions are Integral Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propfiniteimpliesintegral}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 be a finite extension of rings.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
 More generally, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

-module, then any 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $bN\subseteq\mathfrak{a}N$
\end_inset

 satisfies a relation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b^{n}+a_{n-1}b^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}=0,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in\mathfrak{a}^{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i<n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{m}_{b}\colon B\to B$
\end_inset

 be the multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 map, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{m}_{b}(x)=bx$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{m}_{b}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-linear endomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a finite generating set of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{b_{1},\dots,b_{n}\}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{m}_{b}]$
\end_inset

 be a matrix representation of this endomorphism with respect to this generating
 set: for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
bb_{i}=\sum_{j=1}^{n}a_{ji}b_{j}
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ji}\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Then we set 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{m}_{b}]=(a_{ij})$
\end_inset

.
 By the Cayley-Hamiltonian Theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{m}_{b}]$
\end_inset

 satisfies it's own characteristic polynomial, which is a monic polynomial
 with coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 must satisfy this monic polynomial too.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For the moreover part, note that one can show that the characteristic polynomial
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{m}_{b}]$
\end_inset

 has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\chi_{[\mathrm{m}_{b}]}(T)=T^{n}-\mathrm{tr}[\mathrm{m}_{b}]T^{n-1}+\cdots+(-1)^{n}\mathrm{tr}(\Lambda^{n}[\mathrm{m}_{b}]).
\]

\end_inset

Thus if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ji}\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, then the coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda^{k}[\mathrm{m}_{b}]$
\end_inset

 have entries in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}^{k}$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{tr}(\Lambda^{k}[\mathrm{m}_{b}])\in\mathfrak{a}^{k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-Algebra Generated by Integral Elements is Finite
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propfiniteimpliesintegral}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 be an extension of rings.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-algebra of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $B=A[b_{1},\dots,b_{k}]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}\in B$
\end_inset

 integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq k$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is finite over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We prove this by induction on the number of generators 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 First consider the base case 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $B=A[b_{1}]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Thus there exists a First observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $A[b_{1}]$
\end_inset

 is finite over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}$
\end_inset

 satisfies a monic polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 with coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,b_{1},\dots,b_{1}^{n-1}\}$
\end_inset

 form a system of generators of 
\begin_inset Formula $A[b_{1}]$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 By the same reasoning, 
\begin_inset Formula $A[b_{1},b_{2}]=A[b_{1}][b_{2}]$
\end_inset

 is finite over 
\begin_inset Formula $A[b_{1}]$
\end_inset

, and hence finite over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 An inductive argument completes the proof.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
If 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

 is Integral Over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A[b]$
\end_inset

 is Finite
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{corintegraleltestfin}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset B$
\end_inset

 be a ring extension.
 Then an element 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $A[b]$
\end_inset

 is a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $b'\in B$
\end_inset

 is also integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $bb'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b+b'$
\end_inset

 are integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, then there is a monic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)\in A[T]$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $f(b)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A[b]\cong A[T]\slash\langle f(T)\rangle$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $A[b]$
\end_inset

 is a finitely-generated 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 The converse direction follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propfiniteimpliesintegral})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Finally, to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $bb'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b+b'$
\end_inset

 are integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq A[b,b']$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension since both 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b'$
\end_inset

 are integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $b+b'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $bb'$
\end_inset

 are integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $b+b',bb'\in A[b,b']$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Transitivity of Integral Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{proptransitivityofintext}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq C$
\end_inset

 be integral extensions.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq C$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in C$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0},\dots,b_{n-1}\in B$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c^{n}+b_{n-1}c^{n-1}+\cdots+b_{0}=0.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq A[b_{0},\dots,b_{n-1}]\subseteq A[b_{0},\dots,b_{n-1}][c]$
\end_inset

 is a composition of finite extensions.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq A[b_{0},\dots,b_{n-1},c]$
\end_inset

 is a finite extension, hence an integral extension.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Integral Extension 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 an Integral Domain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma1intabfield}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset B$
\end_inset

 be an integral extension and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is a field if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero element in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, we know that it is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=1$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0},\dots,a_{n-1}\in A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b^{n}+a_{n-1}b^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}=0.\label{eq:integralext1234d}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{n-1}$
\end_inset

 on both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:integralext1234d})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b+a_{n-1}+\cdots+a^{n-1}a_{0}=0.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero element in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0},\dots,a_{n-1}\in A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b^{n}+a_{n-1}b^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}=0,
\]

\end_inset

where we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is minimal.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is minimal and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
1 & =(-a_{0})^{-1}(b^{n}+a_{n-1}b^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{1}b)\\
 & =(-a_{0})^{-1}(b^{n-1}+a_{n-1}b^{n-2}+\cdots+a_{1})b
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(-a_{0})^{-1}(b^{n-1}+a_{n-1}b^{n-2}+\cdots+a_{1})
\]

\end_inset

is the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be an algebraic extension of fields and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K\subseteq A\subseteq L.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First note that 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq A$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension since 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is an algebraic extension.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in L$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is algebraic, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0},a_{1},\dots,a_{n}\in K$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{n}x^{n}+\cdots+a_{1}x+a_{0}=0.\label{eq:algipmliesint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a field, we can multiply both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:algipmliesint})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{n}+\cdots+a_{n}^{-1}a_{1}x+a_{n}^{-1}a_{0}=0.\label{eq:algimplimflksdjlfksd}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:algimplimflksdjlfksd})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 was arbitrary, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq A$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
 Now it follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma1intabfield})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a field, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 must be a field too.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Inverse Image of Maximal Ideal under Integral Extension is Maximal Ideal
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmainverseimagemaxint}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{n}$
\end_inset

 be a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{n}\cap A$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The inverse image of any ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, so it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap\mathfrak{n}$
\end_inset

 is maximal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash(A\cap\mathfrak{n})\subseteq B\slash\mathfrak{n}$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
 Thus, since 
\begin_inset Formula $B\slash\mathfrak{n}$
\end_inset

 is a field, it follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma1intabfield})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash(A\cap\mathfrak{n})$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap\mathfrak{n}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
More Integral Extension Properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 be an integral extension.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a multiplicatively closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{S}\subset B_{S}$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}\subset B$
\end_inset

 be an ideal.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash A\cap\mathfrak{b}\to B\slash\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\subset A$
\end_inset

 be a maximal ideal.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}B\neq B$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{m}\to B\slash\mathfrak{m}B$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $b/s\in B_{S}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0},\dots a_{n-1}\in A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b^{n}+a_{n-1}b^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}=0.\label{eq:localizationintegral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Multiplying both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:localizationintegral})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{-n}$
\end_inset

, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{b}{s}\right)^{n}+\left(\frac{a_{n-1}}{s}\right)\left(\frac{b}{s}\right)^{n-1}+\cdots+\left(\frac{a_{0}}{s^{n}}\right)=0.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}/s^{n-i}\in A_{S}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i<n$
\end_inset

, we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $b/s$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{S}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{S}\subset B_{S}$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension since 
\begin_inset Formula $b/s$
\end_inset

 was arbitrary.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon A\to B\slash\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 is a composition of integral extensions, and hence must be an integral
 extension.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
A\slash A\cap\mathfrak{b} & =A\slash\ker\pi\\
 & \cong\mathrm{im}\,\pi\\
 & \subset B\slash\mathfrak{b}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

is an integral extension.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon A\to B/\mathfrak{m}B$
\end_inset

 is a composition of integral extensions, and hence must be an integral
 extension.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
A\slash(A\cap\mathfrak{m}B) & =A\slash\ker\pi\\
 & \cong\mathrm{im}\,\pi\\
 & \subseteq B\slash\mathfrak{m}B
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
 Now we claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap\mathfrak{m}B=\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap\mathfrak{m}B$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and since
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{m}\subseteq A\cap\mathfrak{m}B\subseteq A,
\]

\end_inset

we must either have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=A\cap\mathfrak{m}B$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap\mathfrak{m}B=A$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap\mathfrak{m}B=A$
\end_inset

, then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{n}\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1},\dots,b_{n}\in B$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=a_{1}b_{1}+\cdots+a_{n}b_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

But this also implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\mathfrak{m}B$
\end_inset

.
 Contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us give another reason why 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x,y]\subset K[x,y,z]/\langle x-yz\rangle$
\end_inset

 is not an integral extension.
 Assuming it was, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
K & \cong K[x,y]/\langle x,y\rangle\\
 & \subset K[x,y,z]/\langle x-yz,x,y\rangle\\
 & \cong K[z]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

would also be an integral extension.
 Contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Going up Implies Lying Over
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 be an extension of rings.
 The following are equivalent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 is going up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S=R\backslash\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 which is maximal with respect to the property that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\cap S=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 lies over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 be an extension of rings.
 The following are equivalent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 is INC
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 which lies over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 is maximal with respect to exclusion of 
\begin_inset Formula $S=R\backslash\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Lying Over and Going Up Properties for Integral Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 be an integral extension.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Lying over property) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\subset B$
\end_inset

 that lies over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap\mathfrak{q}=\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\subseteq\mathfrak{q}'$
\end_inset

 are two prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 which lie over the same prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}=\mathfrak{q}'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Going up property) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\subset\mathfrak{p}'$
\end_inset

 be prime ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap\mathfrak{q}=\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}'$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\subset\mathfrak{q}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap\mathfrak{q}'=\mathfrak{p}'$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}\subseteq B_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{n}$
\end_inset

 be a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{n}\cap A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmainverseimagemaxint})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring, it must be the unique maximal ideal, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{n}\cap A_{\mathfrak{p}}=\mathfrak{p}A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

.
 Now we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}=\mathfrak{m}\cap B$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 which lies over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}\subseteq B_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is maximal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 and both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}'_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 lie over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}'_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 are maximal ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}_{\mathfrak{p}}=\mathfrak{q}'_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}=\mathfrak{q}'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash A\cap\mathfrak{q}\subseteq B\slash\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
 In other words, since 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap\mathfrak{q}=\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{p}\subseteq A\slash\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
 By part 1 of this proposition, there exists a prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}'\slash\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $B\slash\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(A\slash\mathfrak{p})\cap(\mathfrak{q}'\slash\mathfrak{q})=\mathfrak{p}'\slash\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}'$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\subset\mathfrak{q}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap\mathfrak{q}'=\mathfrak{p}'$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 be an integral extension.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}_{0}\subset\cdots\subset\mathfrak{q}_{r}$
\end_inset

 be a chain of prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap\mathfrak{q}_{0}\subset\cdots\subset A\cap\mathfrak{q}_{r}$
\end_inset

 forms a chain of prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Going up property) Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{0}\subset\cdots\subset\mathfrak{p}_{r}$
\end_inset

 be a chain of prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 which lies over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a chain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}_{0}\subset\cdots\subset\mathfrak{q}_{r}$
\end_inset

 of prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 with origin 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}_{0}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}_{i}$
\end_inset

 lies over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i\leq r$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\dim A=\dim B$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 which lies over an ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{ht}\,\mathfrak{b}\leq\mathrm{ht}\,\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Geometric Interpretation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to B$
\end_inset

 be an integral extension.
 Then the induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{\#}:\text{Spec }B\to\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\mapsto\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

, is a closed map.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For any ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{\#}(V(\mathfrak{b}))=V(\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{b}))$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supseteq\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

, then we can find a prime 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\supseteq\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})=\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.

\series bold
 
\series default

\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\mathbb{Q}[x,y]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\mathbb{Q}[x,y,z]/\langle z^{2}-xz-1\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 We want to find a prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\subset\mathfrak{p}B$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\cap A=\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 We compute a primary decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}B$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{p}B=\langle x,z^{2}-xz-1\rangle=\langle x,z-1\rangle\cap\langle x,z+1\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

Both prime ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x,z-1\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x,z+1\rangle$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 give as intersection with 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
  
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 be rings, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to B$
\end_inset

 an integral extension.
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:B\to C$
\end_inset

 a ring homomorphism such that the restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:B\to C$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mbox{Ker}(\psi)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b^{n}+a_{n-1}b^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}=0\label{eq:inteq2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in A$
\end_inset

, and where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is minimal.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}\neq0$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 Applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:inteq2})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(a_{0})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since the restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is injective, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For a finite map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\subset A$
\end_inset

 a maximal ideal, 
\begin_inset Formula $B/\mathfrak{m}B$
\end_inset

 is a finite dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $(A/\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 This implies that the fibres of closed points of the induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\text{Max}(B)\to\text{Max}(A)$
\end_inset

 are finite sets.
 To be specific, let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]/I$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B=K[y_{1},\dots,y_{k}]/J$
\end_inset

, and let 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathbb{A}^m 
\backslash
supset 
\backslash
mathbf{V} (J) 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
phi "] & 
\backslash
mathbf{V} (I) 
\backslash
subset 
\backslash
mathbb{A}^m 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

be the induced map.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\langle x_{1}-p_{1},\dots,x_{n}-p_{n}\rangle\subset K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is the maximal ideal of the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\dots,p_{n})\in\mathbf{V}(I)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}B=(J+\mathfrak{n})/J$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{n}:=\langle\varphi(x_{1})-p_{1},\dots,\varphi(x_{n})-p_{n}\rangle\subset K[y_{1},\dots,y_{k}]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(J+N)=\phi^{-1}(p)$
\end_inset

 is the fibre of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, which is a finite set, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{dim}_{K}(K[y_{1},\dots,y_{k}]/(J+N))<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The converse, however, is not true, not even for local rings.
 But, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to B$
\end_inset

 is a map between local analytic 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebras, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is finite if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{dim}_{K}(B/\varphi(\mathfrak{m}_{A})B)<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[x,y]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B=K[x,y,z]/\langle x-yz\rangle$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to B$
\end_inset

 be the ring homomorphism induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)=x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(y)=y$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec}(A)$
\end_inset

 corresponds tof the 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

-plane, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec}(B)$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

blown up
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

-plane.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to B$
\end_inset

, induces a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{\#}:\text{Spec}(B)\to\text{Spec}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 We calculate the inverse images of some points 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i,j}=\langle x-i,x-j\rangle$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Max}(A)\subset\text{Spec}(A)$
\end_inset

: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s,t\in K\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\varphi^{\#}\right)^{-1}(p_{0,0}) & =\langle x-yz,x,y\rangle=\langle x,y\rangle\\
\left(\varphi^{\#}\right)^{-1}(p_{s,0}) & =\langle x-yz,x-s,y\rangle=\langle1\rangle\\
\left(\varphi^{\#}\right)^{-1}(p_{0,t}) & =\langle x-yz,x,y-t\rangle=\langle x,y-t,z\rangle\\
\left(\varphi^{\#}\right)^{-1}(p_{s,t}) & =\langle x-yz,x-s,y-t\rangle=\langle x-1,y-1,s-tz\rangle
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So there is one point which maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{s,t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0,t}$
\end_inset

, no points which maps 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{s,0}$
\end_inset

, and a whole line of points which maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0,0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename 20180210_132406.jpg
	lyxscale 30
	scale 30

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, if we let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[y,z]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to B$
\end_inset

 be the map given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(y)=y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(z)=z$
\end_inset

, then it's easy to see 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a ring isomorphism, and hence, the induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{\#}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now let us considered the projective version of this map.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{A}=K[x,y,w]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{B}=K[x,y,z,w]/\langle xw-yz\rangle$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}:\widetilde{A}\to\widetilde{B}$
\end_inset

 be the ring homomorphism induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}(x)=x$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}(y)=y$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}(w)=w$
\end_inset

.
 Then in the 
\begin_inset Formula $w=1$
\end_inset

 plane, we recover 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to B$
\end_inset

.
 We calculate the inverse images of some points 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i,j,k}=\langle x-i,x-j,x-k\rangle$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Max}(\widetilde{A})\subset\text{Spec}(\widetilde{A})$
\end_inset

: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s,t,u\in K\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\varphi^{\#}\right)^{-1}(p_{0,0,0}) & =\langle x,y,w\rangle\\
\left(\varphi^{\#}\right)^{-1}(p_{s,0,0}) & =\langle x-s,y,w\rangle\\
\left(\varphi^{\#}\right)^{-1}(p_{0,t,0}) & =\langle x,y-t,w\rangle\\
\left(\varphi^{\#}\right)^{-1}(p_{0,0,u}) & =\langle x,y,w-u\rangle\\
\left(\varphi^{\#}\right)^{-1}(p_{0,t,u}) & =\langle x,y-t,w-u\rangle\\
\left(\varphi^{\#}\right)^{-1}(p_{s,t,0}) & =\langle x-s,y-t,w\rangle\\
\left(\varphi^{\#}\right)^{-1}(p_{s,0,u}) & =\langle1\rangle\\
\left(\varphi^{\#}\right)^{-1}(p_{s,t,u}) & =\langle su-tz,x-s,y-t,w-u\rangle
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x-yz,x-s,y-t\rangle$
\end_inset

 can be considered as an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $K(s,t)[x,y,z]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Criterion for Integral Dependence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field, 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 an ideal and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{k}\in K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 The residue classes 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}_{i}=f_{i}\mbox{ mod }I$
\end_inset

 generate a subring
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A:=K[\overline{f}_{1},\dots,\overline{f}_{k}]\subset B:=K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]/I.
\]

\end_inset

 We want to check whether a given 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in K[x]$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $K[f_{1},\dots,f_{k}]\mbox{ mod }I$
\end_inset

, that is, whether 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{b}$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{integral}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Criterion for integral dependence).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $b,f_{1},\dots,f_{k}\in K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle g_{1},\dots,g_{s}\rangle\subset K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 an ideal, and 
\begin_inset Formula $t,y_{1},\dots,y_{k}$
\end_inset

 new variables.
 Consider the ideal
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M:=\langle t-b,y_{1}-f_{1},\dots,y_{k}-f_{k},g_{1},\dots,g_{s}\rangle\subset K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n},t,y_{1},\dots,y_{k}].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $>$
\end_inset

 be an ordering on 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x,t,y]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x\gg t\gg y$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gg$
\end_inset

 refers to a block ordering where terms in 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})$
\end_inset

 are always greater than terms in 
\begin_inset Formula $y=(y_{1},\dots,y_{k})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a Groebner basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 with respect to this ordering.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $K[f_{1},\dots,f_{k}]\mbox{ mod }I$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 contains an element 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 with leading monomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LM}(g)=t^{p}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $p>0$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, any such 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 defines an integral relation for 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K[f_{1},\dots,f_{k}]\mbox{ mod }I$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LM}(g)=t^{p}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 must have the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(t,y_{1},\dots,y_{k})=a_{0}t^{p}+a_{1}(y_{1},\dots,y_{k})t^{p-1}+\cdots+a_{p}(y_{1},\dots,y_{k})\in K[t,y_{1},\dots,y_{k}],\qquad a_{0}\in K\setminus\{0\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}=1$
\end_inset

.
 There is a ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n},t,y_{1},\dots,y_{k}]\to K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 given by sending 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mapsto b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\mapsto f_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The image of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in M$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(g)=g(b,f_{1},\dots,f_{k})\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 defines an integral relation for 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K[f_{1},\dots,f_{k}]\mbox{ mod }I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is integral, then there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in K[t,y_{1},\dots,y_{k}]$
\end_inset

 as above.
 By Taylor's formula, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(t,y_{1},\dots,y_{k})=g(b,f_{1},\dots,f_{k})+b_{0}\cdot(t-b)+\sum_{i=1}^{k}b_{i}\cdot(y_{i}-f_{i}),
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}\in K[t,y_{1},\dots,y_{k}]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,\dots,k$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in M$
\end_inset

, and therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{p}=\mbox{LM}(g)\in\mbox{LT}(M).$
\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a Groebner basis, 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{p}$
\end_inset

 is divisible by the leading monomial of some element of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 which implies the result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Criterion for Finiteness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Criterion for finiteness).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y=(y_{1},\dots,y_{m})$
\end_inset

 be two sets of variables.
 Moreover, let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset K[x]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $J=\langle h_{1},\dots,h_{s}\rangle\subset K[y]$
\end_inset

 be ideals and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:K[x]/I\to K[y]/J$
\end_inset

 a morphism, defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x_{i}):=f_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M:=\langle x_{1}-f_{1},\dots,x_{n}-f_{n},h_{1},\dots,h_{s}\rangle\subset K[x,y],
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and let 
\begin_inset Formula $>$
\end_inset

 be a block ordering on 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x,y]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $>$
\end_inset

 is the lexigraphical ordering for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}>\cdots>y_{m}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\gg x$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\{g_{1},\dots,g_{t}\}$
\end_inset

 be a standard basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 with respect to this ordering.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is finite if and only if for each 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in\{1,\dots,m\}$
\end_inset

 there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LM}(g)=y_{j}^{\nu_{j}}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{j}>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{s_{j}}=y_{j}^{\nu_{j}}+\sum_{\nu=0}^{\nu=v_{j}-1}a_{j\nu}(x,y_{j+1},\dots,y_{m})\cdot y_{j}^{\nu}\in M$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{s_{j\mid x=f}}:=g_{s_{j}}(f_{1}(y),\dots,f_{n}(y),y_{j+1},\dots,y_{m})\in J
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\dots,m$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{m}\mbox{ mod }J$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x]/I$
\end_inset

.
 Using induction and the transitivity of integrality, we obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}\mbox{ mod }J$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x]/I$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $K[y]/J$
\end_inset

 is finite over 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x]/I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, the finiteness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 guarantees an integral relation 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}^{\nu_{j}}+\sum_{\nu=0}^{\nu=v_{j}-1}a_{j\nu}(f_{1}(y),\dots,f_{n}(y))\cdot y_{j}^{\nu}\in J$
\end_inset

 for suitable 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j\nu}\in K[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Using Taylor's formula, as in the proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{integral})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{j}^{\nu_{j}}+\sum_{\nu=0}^{\nu=v_{j}-1}a_{j\nu}(f_{1}(y),\dots,f_{n}(y))\cdot y_{j}^{\nu}\in M,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and therefore its leading monomial, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}^{\nu_{j}}$
\end_inset

 is an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(M)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Integral Closure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 be an extension of rings.
 The 
\series bold
integral closure 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A_{B}}$
\end_inset

, is defined to be set of all elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 which are integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{A_{B}}=\{b\in B\mid b\text{ is integral over }A\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Corollary~(
\backslash
ref{corintegraleltestfin})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A_{B}}$
\end_inset

 is closed under addition and multiplication.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A_{B}}$
\end_inset

 is a ring.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
integrally closed
\series default
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\overline{A_{B}}$
\end_inset

.
 In the situation where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=K$
\end_inset

 is its fraction field, then we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A_{K}}$
\end_inset

.
 We also say 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A}$
\end_inset

 is the integral closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is integrally closed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A}$
\end_inset

 is the integral closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is integrally closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Integral Closure is Integrally Closed
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 be an extension of rings.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A_{B}}$
\end_inset

 is integrally closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A_{B}}=\overline{(\overline{A_{B}})_{B}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This follows from transitivity of integral extensions.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

 be integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A_{B}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A_{B}}[b]$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A_{B}}$
\end_inset

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A_{B}}$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A_{B}}[b]$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\overline{A_{B}}$
\end_inset

 (by definition of integral closure).
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A_{B}}$
\end_inset

 is integrally closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Every Valuation Ring is Integrally Closed
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every Valuation Ring is Integrally Closed.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a valuation ring with fraction field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

 be integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n-1},\dots,a_{0}\in A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{n}+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}=0
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 we are done, so assume 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}\in A$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a valuation ring.
 Multiplying the equation above by 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-(n-1)}\in A$
\end_inset

 and moving all but the first term on the lefthand side to the righthand
 side yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=-a_{n-1}-\cdots-a_{0}x^{-(n-1)}\in A,
\]

\end_inset

contradicting our assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin A$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is integrally closed.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Integral Closure Properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Localization Commutes With Integral Closure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propintegralclosureandlocalization}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 be an extension of rings and let 
\begin_inset Formula $S\subseteq A$
\end_inset

 be a multiplicatively closed set.
 Then the integral closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 localized at 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the same as
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the integral closure of the 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{S}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{S}$
\end_inset

.
 In symbols, this says 
\begin_inset Formula $(\overline{A_{B}})_{S}=\overline{(A_{S})_{B_{S}}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{S}\subseteq B_{S}$
\end_inset

 is an extension of rings (localization preserves injective maps).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $b/s\in(\overline{A_{B}})_{S}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\overline{A_{B}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0},\dots,a_{n-1}\in A$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b^{n}+a_{n-1}b^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}=0.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $b/s\in\overline{(A_{S})_{B_{S}}}$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{b}{s}\right)^{n}+\left(\frac{a_{n-1}}{s}\right)\left(\frac{b}{s}\right)^{n-1}+\cdots+\left(\frac{a_{0}}{s^{n}}\right)=0.
\]

\end_inset

Convsersely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $b/s\in\overline{(A_{S})_{B_{S}}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}/s_{0},\dots,a_{n-1}/s_{n-1}\in A_{S}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{b}{s}\right)^{n}+\left(\frac{a_{n-1}}{s_{n-1}}\right)\left(\frac{b}{s}\right)^{n-1}+\cdots+\left(\frac{a_{0}}{s_{0}}\right)=0.\label{eq:bothsideslocintclosconv}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiplying both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:bothsideslocintclosconv})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{n}s_{0}^{n}\cdots s_{n-1}^{n}$
\end_inset

 gives us
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(s_{0}\cdots s_{n-1}b)^{n}+ss_{0}\cdots s_{n-2}a_{n-1}(s_{0}\cdots s_{n-1}b)^{n-1}+\cdots+s^{n}s_{0}^{n-1}\cdots s_{n-1}^{n}a_{0}=0.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}\cdots s_{n-1}b$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $b/s=(s_{0}\cdots s_{n-1}b)/(s_{0}\cdots s_{n-1}s)$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $b/s\in(\overline{A_{B}})_{S}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The notation here is admittedly a bit clumsy.
 However when 
\begin_inset Formula $B=K$
\end_inset

 is a field, the notation becomes a little more readable.
 In this case, our notation says 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A}_{S}=\overline{A_{S}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Integral Closure Is Intersection of all Valuation Overrings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain, let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be its quotient field, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A}$
\end_inset

 be the integral closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{A}=\bigcap_{A\subseteq B\subseteq K}B
\]

\end_inset

where the intersection runs over all valuation overrings 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 be a valuation overring of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is integrally closed and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A}\subseteq B$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 was arbitrary, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A}\subseteq\bigcap_{A\subseteq B\subseteq K}B$
\end_inset

 where the intersection runs over all valuation overrings 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\bigcap_{A\subseteq B\subseteq K}B$
\end_inset

 and assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is not integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}A[x^{-1}]$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}A[x^{-1}]=A[x^{-1}]$
\end_inset

, then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{n-1},a_{n}\in A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{n}x^{-n}+a_{n-1}x^{-n+1}+\cdots+a_{1}x^{-1}=1.\label{eq:notintegral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Multiplying both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:notintegral})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}$
\end_inset

 and rearranging terms gives us
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{n}-a_{1}x^{n-1}-\cdots-a_{n-1}x-a_{n}=0,
\]

\end_inset

which contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is not integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}A[x^{-1}]$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A[x^{-1}]$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, it is contained some maximal ideal, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is a valuation ring 
\begin_inset Formula $(B,\mathfrak{n})$
\end_inset

 that dominates 
\begin_inset Formula $(A[x^{-1}]_{\mathfrak{m}},\mathfrak{m}A[x^{-1}]_{\mathfrak{m}})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}\in\mathfrak{m}\subseteq\mathfrak{n}$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin B$
\end_inset

 (we can't have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
and 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}\in\mathfrak{n}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{n}$
\end_inset

 does not contain any units).
 This contradicts our assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\bigcap_{A\subseteq B\subseteq K}B$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Applications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem3.5.2}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Hilbert's Nullstellensatz).
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\bar{K}$
\end_inset

 is an algebraically closed field.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset K[x]:=K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 be an ideal.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in K[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{V}(I)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\sqrt{I}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We consider the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $J:=IK[x,t]+\langle1-tg\rangle$
\end_inset

 in the polynomial ring 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x,t]:=K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n},t]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $J=K[x,t]$
\end_inset

, then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},\dots,g_{s}\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h,h_{1},\dots,h_{s}\in K[x,t]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $1=\sum_{i=1}^{s}g_{i}h_{i}+h(1-tg)$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $t:=\frac{1}{g}\in K[x]_{g}$
\end_inset

, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=\sum_{i=1}^{s}g_{i}\cdot h_{i}\left(x,\frac{1}{g}\right)\in K[x]_{g}.
\]

\end_inset

Clearing denominators, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\rho}=\sum_{i}g_{i}h_{i}'$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}'\in K[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\sqrt{I}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $J\subset K[x,t]$
\end_inset

.
 We choose a maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\subset K[x,t]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $J\subset\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Using Theorem 3.5.1 (5), we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x,t]/\mathfrak{m}\cong K$
\end_inset

, and, hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\langle x_{1}-a_{1},\dots,x_{n}-a_{n},t-a\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i},a\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $J\subset\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},\dots,a_{n},a)\in\mathbf{V}(J)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})\in\mathbf{V}(I)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $1-tg\in J$
\end_inset

 does not vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})$
\end_inset

, contradicting the assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},\dots,a_{n},a)\in\mathbf{V}(J)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})\notin\mathbf{V}(I)$
\end_inset

, then there is some 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in I$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $h(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})\neq0$
\end_inset

, in particular 
\begin_inset Formula $h(a_{1},\dots,a_{n},a)\neq0$
\end_inset

 and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},\dots,a_{n},a)\notin\mathbf{V}(J)$
\end_inset

, again contradicting our assumption.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Noether Normalization and Hilbert's Nullstellensatz
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this subsection, we will prove the Noether normalization theorem over
 a field and, more generally, over an integral domain.
 We then deduce Hilbert's Nullstellensatz.
 The key to our proofs of the Noether normalization theorem and Hilbert's
 Nullstellensatz is the following idea:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}x_{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},x_{2}]$
\end_inset

.
 It is not monic in either variable.
 However if we let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\colon K[x_{1},x_{2}]\to K[x_{1},x_{2}]$
\end_inset

 be the unique automorphism such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x_{1})=x_{1}+x_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x_{2})=x_{2}$
\end_inset

, then we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x_{1}x_{2})=(x_{1}+x_{2})x_{2}=x_{2}^{2}+x_{1}x_{2}$
\end_inset

 becomes monic as a polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1}]$
\end_inset

.
 We think of the effect of applying an automorphism as a change of variables.
 Thus by a change of variables, we can turn the non-monic 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}x_{2}$
\end_inset

 into a monic 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{2}+x_{1}x_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This trick works more generally:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmapolytomonicauto}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 be a domain and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in D[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N\geq1$
\end_inset

 be an integer that bounds all the exponents of the variables occuring in
 the terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

-automorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $D[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\mapsto x_{i}+x_{n}^{N^{i}}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i<n$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 maps to itself.
 Then the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial whose highest degree term involving 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $cx_{n}^{m}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is a nonzero element in 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $D=K$
\end_inset

 is a field, then the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a nonzero scalar of the field times a polynomial that is monic in 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 when considered as a polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider any nonzero term of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, which will have the form 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\alpha}x_{1}^{a_{1}}\cdots x_{n}^{a_{n}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is a nonzero element in 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 The image of this term under 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi(c_{\alpha}x_{1}^{a_{1}}\cdots x_{n}^{a_{n}}) & =c_{\alpha}(x_{1}+x_{n}^{N})^{a_{1}}(x_{2}+x_{n}^{N^{2}})^{a}\cdots(x_{n-1}+x_{n}^{N^{n-1}})^{a_{n-1}}x_{n}^{a_{n}}\\
 & =c_{\alpha}x_{n}^{a_{n}+a_{1}N+a_{2}N^{2}+\cdots+a_{n-1}N^{n-1}}+\text{terms lower in }x_{n}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The exponents that one gets on 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 in these largest degree terms coming from distinct terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 are all distinct, because of uniqueness of representation of integers in
 base 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, no two exponents are the same, and no two of these terms can cancel.
 Therefore if we set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m=\sup\{a_{n}+a_{1}N+\cdots+a_{n-1}N^{n-1}\mid c_{\alpha}x_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}\cdots x_{n}^{\alpha_{n}}\text{ is a term of }f\},
\]

\end_inset

then we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi(f)=cx_{n}^{m}+\text{terms lower in }x_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $D=K$
\end_inset

 is a field, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{-1}\phi(f)$
\end_inset

 is monic of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 when viewed as a polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Noether Normalization Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-algebra and let 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1},\dots,z_{d}\in R$
\end_inset

.
 We shall say that the elements 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1},\dots,z_{d}$
\end_inset

 are 
\series bold
algebraically independent 
\series default
over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 if the unique 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism from the polynomial ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A[x_{1},\dots,x_{d}]$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 that sends 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 Equivalently, the monimals 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}^{a_{1}}\cdots z_{d}^{a_{d}}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},\dots,a_{d})$
\end_inset

 varies in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}^{d}$
\end_inset

 are all distinct and span a free 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 The failure of the 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{j}$
\end_inset

 to be algebraically independent means precisely that there is some nonzero
 polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{1},\dots,x_{d})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A[x_{1},\dots,x_{d}]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z_{1},\dots,z_{d})=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain and let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be any finitely-generated 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

-algebra extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is a nonzero element 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in D$
\end_inset

 and elements 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1},\dots,z_{d}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}$
\end_inset

 algebraically independent over 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{c}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}$
\end_inset

 is module-finite over its subring 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{c}[z_{1},\dots,z_{d}]$
\end_inset

, which is isomorphic to a polynomial ring (
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 may be zero) over 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $D=K$
\end_inset

 is a field, then it is not necessary to invert an element: every finitely-gener
ated 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra is isomorphic with a module-finite extension of a polynomial ring.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We use induction on the number 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 of generators of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $R=D$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we may take 
\begin_inset Formula $d=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c=1$
\end_inset

.
 Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

 and that we know the result for algebras generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 or fewer elements.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $R=D[\theta_{1},\dots,\theta_{n}]$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 generators.
 If the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 are algebraically independent over 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, then we are done: we may take 
\begin_inset Formula $d=n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}=\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $c=1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we may assume that we have a nonzero polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\in D[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\theta_{1},\dots,\theta_{n})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Instead of using the original 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}$
\end_inset

 as generators of our 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

-algebra, note that we may use instead the elements
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\theta_{1}' & =\theta_{1}-\theta_{n}^{N}\\
\theta_{2}' & =\theta_{2}-\theta_{n}^{N^{2}}\\
 & \vdots\\
\theta_{n-1}' & =\theta_{n-1}-\theta_{n}^{N^{n-1}}\\
\theta_{n}' & =\theta_{n}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is chosen for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmapolytomonicauto})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 as in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmapolytomonicauto})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we have that these new algebra generators satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi(f)=f(x_{1}+x_{n}^{N},\dots,x_{n-1}+x_{n}^{N^{n-1}},x_{n})
\]

\end_inset

which we shall write as 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 We replace 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 by their localizations 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the coefficient of the highest power of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 occuring, so that the polynomial may be replaced by a multiple that is
 monic in 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 After multiplying by a unit of 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{c}$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is monic in 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 with coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{c}[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{n}'$
\end_inset

 is integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{c}[\theta_{1}',\dots,\theta_{n-1}']=R_{0}$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}$
\end_inset

 is module-finite over 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 generators over 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}$
\end_inset

, we have by the induction hypothesis that 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}$
\end_inset

 is module-finite over a polynomial subring 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{cc'}[z_{1},\dots,z_{d}]\subseteq R_{0}$
\end_inset

, and then 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{cc'}$
\end_inset

 is module-finite over 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{cc'}[z_{1},\dots,z_{d}]$
\end_inset

 as well.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
\end_document
